1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 c6 (4... Bg7 5. h3 $5 {,followed by f4
promises White a space advantage. It's better for Black to de- lay the
development of his Bishop, in order to play e5 with the better placed Bf8.}) 5.
f3 Nbd7 6. g4 $5 (6. Qd2 {is more usual, e.g.} e5 7. O-O-O Qa5 8. Kb1 Bg7 9. h4
h5 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Nh3 Bf8 $1 12. Ng5 Bc5 13. Bc4 O-O 14. Bxc5 Qxc5 15. Bb3
Qe7 16. Qd6 Qxd6 17. Rxd6 Kg7 18. Rhd1 Nc5 19. Rd8 Nxb3 20. axb3 Ne8 21. Na4
Nc7 22. Nc5 b6 23. Rxf8 Kxf8 24. Nd7+ Kg7 $10 {
and Black maintained equality, Magem Badals,J-Beim,V/Novi Sad olm/1990/}) 6...
b5 (6... Qb6 7. Qc1 Bg7 8. Nge2 a6 9. h4 c5 10. h5 Rg8 11. a3 Qc6 12. Bg2 b6
13. Qd2 Bb7 14. Rg1 Qc7 15. h6 Bh8 16. g5 Nh5 17. O-O-O cxd4 18. Bxd4 Bxd4 19.
Qxd4 Qc5 20. f4 Qxd4 21. Rxd4 Nc5 22. Nd5 Rc8 23. Kb1 b5 24. Bf3 $16 {
Yudasin,L-Chernin,A/Pamplona/1991/ White has a large space advantage and Black
has no counterplay.}) 7. h4 (7. g5 Nh5 8. a4 b4 9. Nce2 e5 10. Qd2 Bg7 11.
O-O-O O-O 12. Kb1 Qa5 13. b3 c5 14. dxc5 dxc5 15. Nh3 Nb6 16. c4 Be6 17. Nc1
Nxa4 $5 18. bxa4 Rad8 19. Qc2 b3 20. Nxb3 Rb8 21. Kb2 Rb7 $13 {
Georgiev,Kr-Smirin,I/Elenite/1993/}) 7... Bb7 (7... Nb6 $5 $13 {/\Nc4<=>}) (
7... h5 $6 8. g5 {is bad, as the Knight must retreat passively and White has a
huge space advan- tage on the Kingside.}) (7... e5 8. h5 b4 (8... exd4 $2 9.
Qxd4 b4 10. Nce2 d5 11. hxg6 fxg6 12. g5 c5 13. Qd2 d4 14. Nxd4 cxd4 15. Bxd4
Bg7 16. gxf6 Nxf6 17. Qxb4 Be6 18. O-O-O Rb8 19. Bxf6 {
1-0,Georgiev,Kr-Moutousis,K/Athens/1991/}) 9. Nce2 Nb6 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Qxd8+
Kxd8 12. Nc1 Be6 13. Bg5 Nbd7 14. Nd3 Bd6 15. f4 Ke7 16. Nf3 h6 17. Bh4 g5 $8
18. fxe5 Nxe5 19. Ndxe5 gxh4 20. O-O-O (20. Nxc6+ $5) 20... Rac8 21. Ba6 Rc7
22. Rxh4 Nxe4 23. Re1 Ng5 $13 {Georgiev,Kr-Chabanon,J/Sofia tt/1990/}) 8. h5
Rg8 $8 (8... Bg7 $6 9. h6 Bf8 10. g5 $16 {loses too much time and space.}) (
8... gxh5 $2 9. g5 $40) 9. Qd2 Qc7 10. Nh3 (10. h6 e5 $132) 10... a6 11. O-O-O
e6 $146 (11... c5 12. dxc5 Nxc5 13. hxg6 hxg6 14. g5 {
/\Nd5|^. Opening the position is premature, as Black is behind in development.}
) (11... e5 12. Be2 O-O-O 13. Ng5 exd4 14. Bxd4 c5 15. Be3 Nb6 16. hxg6 hxg6
17. Bf4 Qd7 18. Qe1 $36 {
and Black's position is rather shaky, Canfell,G-Chabanon,J/Novi Sad om/1990/})
12. hxg6 hxg6 13. Ng5 $14 {White has advantage in the center and occupies the
only open file, but Black's position is still solid.} Be7 14. Kb1 Rf8 {/\0-0-0}
(14... c5 15. dxc5 Nxc5 16. Bxb5+ $5 axb5 17. Nxb5 $36 {
With three passed pawns for a piece in an endgame White is clearly better.})
15. Nh7 Nxh7 (15... Rh8 $5 16. Nxf6+ Bxf6 17. Rxh8+ Bxh8 18. Qh2 O-O-O {
+/=/<=> This seems to be a better possibility for Black, as the Rook is more
dan- gerous on the h-file, than the White Queen.}) 16. Rxh7 Nf6 (16... O-O-O
17. g5 $14 {-16...Nf6}) 17. Rh2 O-O-O 18. g5 Nd7 (18... Nh5 19. Bh3 {/\Bg4,d5->
Black's Knight on h5 is misplaced, so Beliavsky must allow the Rook back to h7.
}) 19. Rh7 Nb6 (19... c5 20. d5 $36) 20. Qf2 c5 $8 (20... d5 $6 21. Qh4 $16 {
/\Bf4 would seriously weaken the black squares.}) 21. b3 (21. d5 $2 b4 $17)
21... cxd4 (21... Nd7 22. d5 $1 e5 23. Bh3 $36) 22. Bxd4 Nd7 {/\e5-+} 23. Qe3
Kb8 (23... e5 $6 24. Ba7 $16 {><d5}) 24. a4 $1 b4 25. Na2 Rc8 (25... d5 26.
exd5 Bxd5 27. Bxa6 $16) 26. Rd2 (26. Nxb4 $2 d5 $19) 26... Qa5 27. Bg7 $5 (27.
f4 e5 $132 {would give Black play against White's weakened pawns e4,g5. The
interesting maneuvre in the text keeps the advantage.}) 27... Rfe8 (27... Bxg5
$2 28. f4 $16) 28. Bh6 Ne5 29. Be2 {/\f4} (29. f4 $6 Ng4 $13) 29... Rh8 $8 30.
Rxh8 Rxh8 31. Qd4 Rc8 32. Qxb4 (32. Nxb4 Nd7 33. Na2 d5 $5 {
gives Black conterchances for a pawn, so White strives for a better endgame.})
32... Qxb4 33. Nxb4 d5 34. Bg7 $1 (34. Nxa6+ $2 Ka7 {><Na6}) (34. Nd3 Nxf3 $1
35. Bxf3 dxe4 $13) 34... Bxb4 (34... Nxf3 $5 35. Nxa6+ $1 Bxa6 36. Bxf3 Bxg5 (
36... dxe4 $2 37. Be5+ $18) 37. Be5+ Ka7 38. Rg2 dxe4 39. Bxe4 $14 {><Ka7 White
is slightly better, as his pawns are more dangerous and his King is better
sheltered. But this was much better than the game, where Black has no 
counterchances.}) 35. Bxe5+ Ka8 36. Rd1 dxe4 37. fxe4 Bxe4 38. Bd3 Bxd3 (38...
Bf5 39. Bxf5 gxf5 40. Rd7 $16) (38... Bb7 39. Rf1 $18) 39. Rxd3 Be7 40. Rd7
Bxg5 41. Rxf7 $16 {
><P Black's passed pawns are weak and his pieces are tied to their defence.}
Rc5 (41... Rg8 42. Bd4 $16) 42. Bb2 (42. Bd4 Rd5 43. c3 e5 $132) 42... Bh4 (
42... e5 43. Rg7 e4 44. Rxg6 $16) 43. Rf8+ Kb7 44. Re8 Rc6 (44... g5 45. Rxe6 {
/\} g4 46. Re4 $18) 45. c4 $1 (45. Rg8 g5 46. Bf6 Rc5 $14) 45... Bg3 (45... Rc8
46. Rxe6 Rg8 47. Bd4 $18) 46. Kc2 Bf4 47. Bf6 g5 48. Re7+ Kc8 (48... Rc7 49.
Rxe6 Rf7 50. Bd4 Bc7 51. Rg6 $18) 49. Rg7 Rc5 50. Kd3 a5 $6 {><a5,><b5 The
decisive mistake, which weakens the a-pawn. But White had a big  advantage
anyway.} (50... Rf5 $142 51. Be7 Re5 52. b4 $5 $16 (52. c5 Re3+ 53. Kc4 Re4+
$10)) 51. Be7 Rf5 (51... Re5 52. c5 Re3+ 53. Kc4 {/\Kb5->}) 52. c5 {/\Kc4-b5-c6
} Kd7 $8 53. Bxg5+ Kc6 54. Bxf4 Rxf4 55. Ra7 Rf3+ (55... Kxc5 56. Rxa5+ Kb4 57.
Rb5+ $18) 56. Kc4 Rf4+ 57. Kc3 Rf3+ 58. Kb2 $8 Kxc5 59. Rxa5+ Kd4 60. Ra8 e5
61. a5 Rf6 (61... Kc5 62. Rb8 {/\a6+-}) 62. Re8 e4 (62... Ra6 63. b4 Kc4 64.
