1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3
O-O 9. h3 Bb7 10. d4 Re8 11. Nbd2 Bf8 12. d5 Ne7 (12... Nb8) 13. Nf1 (13. c4
Nd7 14. Bc2 c6 15. b3 Rc8 16. Nf1 Qc7 17. Ne3 $14 {
Anand,V-Deshmukh,A/Calcutta/1992}) 13... Ng6 14. N3h2 Nd7 {N} (14... Qd7 15.
Ng4 Nxe4 $5 16. Rxe4 f5 17. Re1 fxg4 {
Rodriguez,Am-Arencibia,W/Capablanca mem-B/1994} 18. Qxg4 Qxg4 19. hxg4 Ne7 20.
Rd1 $14) 15. a3 Nc5 16. Ba2 Nf4 17. c4 c6 18. cxb5 cxb5 19. Bb1 a5 20. h4 g6
21. g3 Nh5 {The main theme of this game is the positioning of the minor pieces.
White constantly tries to push blacks minors away from the good central
squares.} 22. Ng4 Qe7 23. Bc2 Bc8 24. b3 Bd7 (24... f5 25. exf5 gxf5 26. Nxe5
Nxg3 27. Nxg3 dxe5 28. Qh5 $40) 25. Nh6+ Kh8 26. Qf3 f6 27. Bd2 Rec8 28. Rec1
Be8 29. Ng4 Bg7 30. Qe2 Qb7 31. Nge3 Bf8 32. Qe1 Qb6 33. b4 $14 axb4 34. axb4
Rxa1 35. Rxa1 Na4 36. Ra3 Bd7 37. Rb3 Be7 38. Bd3 Ng7 39. Nh2 Bd8 40. Qe2 Qa6
41. Kg2 Nb6 42. Rc3 Rxc3 43. Bxc3 {
White has a space advantage. And blacks minor pieces are just defending.} Na4
44. Be1 Kg8 45. Nhg4 h5 $2 {Now white gets someting to attack on the kingside.
Its a long way back for Na4 to the defence.} 46. Nh2 Bb6 47. Nhf1 {Whites minor
pieces looks a bit cramped. But its just temporary. In fact they are quite
mobile, with easy access to both flanks.} Kf7 48. Nd1 Ba7 49. Nfe3 Qb6 50. f3
Qb7 51. Nc2 Ne8 52. Kh2 Qa6 53. Nce3 Bd4 54. f4 $1 $16 {
Now the h5-P looks really weak.} Qb6 55. f5 Ng7 56. fxg6+ Kxg6 57. Nf5 $1 Nxf5
58. exf5+ Bxf5 59. Bxf5+ Kxf5 60. Qc2+ $1 {
A series of Q-checks forces the black K into a mating net.} (60. Qxh5+ $2 Ke4
$13) 60... e4 (60... Kg4 61. Qe4#) 61. Qc8+ Kg6 62. Qg8+ Kf5 (62... Kh6 63.
Bd2+ e3 64. Nxe3 Bxe3 65. Qh8+ Kg6 66. Qe8+ $18) 63. Qh7+ Ke5 64. Qxh5+ f5 65.
Qf7 Be3 66. Kg2 $1 {
The K delivers the final blow by preparing Bf2 after an exchange on e3.} f4 (
66... Bc1 67. Bf2 e3 68. Nxe3 Bxe3 69. Qe6+ Kd4 70. Bxe3+ $18) 67. gxf4+ Bxf4
68. Nf2 1-0

