1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Bc4 O-O 8.
Bb3 d6 9. h3 Na5 10. O-O b6 11. Qd3 (11. Bg5 Nxb3 12. axb3 Bb7 13. Qd3 a6 {
transposes to the game}) (11. Re1 Bb7 12. Bg5 h6 13. Bh4 Rc8 14. Nd5 g5 15.
Nxf6+ Bxf6 16. Bg3 Nxb3 17. axb3 Bxd4 18. Qxd4 Rxc2 19. Rxa7 Qc7 20. Qd1 Rc8
$13 {De Firmian,N-Kaliksteyn,A 1995}) 11... Bb7 12. Bg5 (12. Bd5 Qd7 13. Bxb7
Qxb7 14. Rad1 Rac8 15. Rfe1 {Moldovan,D-Marin,M Bucuresti 1994 60/230 [Marin,M]
} a6 $1 16. Nf3 b5 17. a3 Nc4 18. Bc1 Rc7 $15 {Marin}) (12. Rad1 Rc8 13. Rfe1
Rxc3 14. Qxc3 Nxe4 15. Qd3 Nxb3 16. Nxb3 Qc7 17. c3 Nc5 18. Nxc5 bxc5 19. Bg5
$13 {/+/= Kholmov,R-Hachian,M Moscow 1995}) (12. f4 Rc8 13. Rae1 Rxc3 14. Qxc3
Nxe4 15. Qd3 Nxb3 16. axb3 e5 17. Ne2 Qa8 18. b4 Nf6 19. Rf2 Ne4 20. Rff1 Re8 {
with good compensation for black Mortensen-Kudrin 1983}) 12... Nxb3 13. axb3 a6
14. Rfe1 h6 15. Bd2 $2 {normally in this position the bishop goes to h4,where
he can put some presure along the h4-d8 diagonal,and indeed white's bishop is
not good on d2} (15. Bh4 Re8 16. Rad1 Qc7 17. Nde2 Rac8 18. Rd2 b5 19. f3 b4
20. Na4 d5 21. exd5 Nxd5 {
when black has a good position Mitkov,N-Osmanbegovic,S Cannas op 1995}) 15...
b5 16. f4 e6 {black is already better,he has the pair of bishops it is not
clear where white wants to attack,and black just wants to open the center with
e5 and d5,now we can see why the bishop is needed on h4} 17. Kh2 $6 {
putting the king in the h2-b8 diagonal is not the best idea} Rc8 {white played
a wrong plan,insted of playing positionly,with B on h4 and rooks on d1-e1
white is playing for the attack,but this only serves black since  white really
has no attack but creating weakness} 18. Re2 Qc7 19. b4 Rfd8 {it is clear now
black is going to break in the center and his 2 bishops will  become very
powerfull} 20. Nb3 e5 $1 21. fxe5 d5 $1 {of course not 21...dxe5,now the g7
bishop will enter the game and with the "d" and "c" file black's rooks are
also placed very good,white is paying now for Kh2} 22. exd5 Nxd5 23. Qg3 Nxb4
24. Rf1 Re8 $1 {going for the e5 pawn there is no defence} (24... Nxc2 25. Bxh6
Bxh6 26. Rxc2 b4) 25. Bf4 g5 26. Nd4 gxf4 27. Rxf4 Rxe5 28. Rxe5 (28. Nf5 Rxf5
29. Rxf5 Qxg3+ 30. Kxg3 Bxc3 31. bxc3 Rxc3+) 28... Qxe5 29. Nf5 Rc4 $1 {
the game is over,it is impossible to prevent the exchange of queens} 30. Nxh6+
Kh7 31. Rxc4 bxc4 32. Nxf7 Qxg3+ 33. Kxg3 Kg6 34. Nd8 Bc8 35. Na4 Be5+ 0-1

