1. d4 {Petursson  Hazai} Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 O-O 5. e4 d6 6. Be2 e5
7. Be3 c6 8. d5 (8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Nd2 (9. Qxd8 Rxd8 10. Nxe5 Re8 (10... Nxe4)
11. f4 Nbd7 $3 12. Bd4 (12. Nxd7 Nxe4 13. Ne5 Nxc3 14. bxc3 f6) 12... Nh5 $1
13. Bxh5 Nxe5 14. Be2 (14. Bxe5 Bxe5 15. fxe5 gxh5 16. O-O-O Bg4) 14... Nf3+
15. Bxf3 Bxd4 16. Rd1 (16. Kd2 Be6 17. b3 Rad8 18. Kc2 Be3 $17) 16... Bxc3+ 17.
bxc3 Bf5 $10 18. Kf2 Bxe4 19. Rd7 $10 {
Stojanovic,Mi-Damljanovic,B JUG-ch Podgorica 1996}) 9... Qe7 10. c5 Nbd7 11.
Qa4 Rd8 (11... Nxc5 $2 12. Qa3 Nfd7 13. Na4 b6 14. Nb3) 12. Nb3 Nf8 13. O-O Ne6
14. Rad1 Rxd1 15. Rxd1 Nf4 16. f3 h5 $1 $40 {
Portisch,L-Ivanchuk,V Reykjavik Wcup 1991}) (8. Qd2 {this move  was played 2
round later by Shirov against Topalov but it was  another very convincing
Victory for Topalov with the King's Indian with black} Qe7 (8... Nbd7 9. Rd1
Re8 10. d5 cxd5 11. cxd5 a6 12. O-O b5 $2 (12... Ng4 13. Bg5 f6 14. Bh4 h5 15.
Ne1 $13) 13. Qc2 Nb6 14. a4 $1 bxa4 15. Nxa4 Nxa4 16. Qxa4 Rb8 17. Nd2 $1 $16 {
Kasparov,G-Ivanchuk,V Reggio Emilia 1992}) 9. d5 cxd5 (9... Ng4 10. Bg5 f6 11.
Bh4 Na6 12. O-O Bh6 (12... g5 13. Bg3 h5 14. h3 Nh6 15. a3 $14) (12... h5 13.
h3 Nh6 14. a3 $14) 13. Qd1 $1 Bf4 (13... g5 14. Bg3 f5 15. exf5 Bxf5 16. h4 $1
$16) 14. a3 g5 15. Bg3 c5 16. Nxg5 $1 Nxh2 17. Bxf4 Nxf1 18. Ne6 Bxe6 19. Bh6
$1 $14 {/+/- Khalifman,A-Wahls,M Deutschland 1992 54/597 [Khalifman,A]}) 10.
cxd5 Ng4 11. Bg5 f6 12. Bh4 Na6 13. O-O Nh6 14. Ne1 Nf7 15. Bxa6 bxa6 16. Nc2
Rb8 17. Ne3 a5 18. Rfc1 h5 19. f3 Bh6 20. Ncd1 Ng5 21. Qxa5 f5 $36 {
Shirov,A-Topalov,V Vienna 1996}) 8... Na6 (8... Ng4 9. Bg5 f6 10. Bh4 Na6 11.
Nd2 Nh6 (11... h5 12. h3 Nh6 13. g4 hxg4 14. hxg4 Nf7 15. Nb3 c5 16. Nc1 $13 {
Giorgadza,G-Poluljahov,A Kropotkin 1995}) 12. a3 (12. O-O Nf7 13. Bd3 $1 c5 14.
a3 Bh6 15. Qe2 Bg5 16. Bxg5 fxg5 (16... Nxg5 17. g3 {with f4}) 17. f3 Bd7 18.
Rab1 h5 19. Qe3 $1 $14 {
Ehlvest,J-Novik,M Sankt_Peterburg 1994 60/561 [Nesis,G; Novik,M]}) 12... Nf7
13. f3 Bh6 14. Bf2 f5 15. Qc2 Bd7 16. b4 c5 $1 17. Rb1 b6 $13 {
Karpov,An-Kasparov,G Lyon Wch (19) 1990}) 9. a3 {
White is playing against Na6 planning b2-b4. This, however looks a bit slow.} (
9. Nd2 {(Hazai: is the typical common sense move here.)} Ne8 10. O-O f5 11. f3
f4 12. Bf2 c5 13. a3 b6 14. b4 h5 15. bxc5 Nxc5 16. a4 $6 a5 $1 {
San Segundo,P-Topalov,V Madrid 1996}) 9... Nh5 (9... Nc5 $6 {Hazai} 10. Nd2 a5
11. b4 $16) (9... Ne8 10. dxc6 bxc6 11. c5 $1 $14) 10. g3 (10. b4 {Hazai} Nf4
11. Bf1 c5) 10... cxd5 11. Nxd5 (11. cxd5 {Hazai} f5) 11... Nf6 12. Nxf6+ (12.
Nc3) (12. Nd2 {Hazai} Nxd5 13. cxd5 f5) 12... Qxf6 13. b4 Qe7 14. O-O b6 $1 {
a very strong move the bishop will be best placed on the a8-h1 while white 
does not have a c5break} 15. Qa4 $6 {
wasting too much time with useless queen moves} Nc7 (15... Bb7 $2 16. c5 $1)
16. Qc6 Ba6 $1 {a good move playing against a c5 break} (16... Rb8 17. c5) 17.
Rfd1 (17. b5 $2 Bc8 18. Rfd1 Rd8 {and white's queen is in great danger}) 17...
Rfd8 {The weakness on d6 does not play an important role here.} 18. Rac1 Ne6
19. Qa4 Bb7 20. Qc2 {
The attack against d6 is repelled, Black has a comfortable game.} Rf8 $1 {
prepering the f5 break,it is already clear black has the initiative    Now
f7-f5 is threatening, after which the weakened diagonal may cause some
headache for White.} 21. Nh4 (21. c5 dxc5 $1 22. bxc5 Rac8 {winning the c5 pawn
}) 21... Nd4 22. Bxd4 exd4 23. Bd3 Rae8 24. Kf1 (24. f3 {Hazai} Bh6 $17) (24.
Re1 {Hazai} f5 $17) 24... Qd7 $1 {much better than 24...Bxe4} (24... Bxe4 25.
Bxe4 Qxe4 26. Qxe4 Rxe4 27. Nf3 {
gives some chances to save the game in the ending.}) 25. Re1 {#} f5 $1 {
Black opens up the long diagonal with a great effect.  Now White is going to
have great problems on the whitesquares} 26. exf5 g5 $1 {
this is topalov's idea the knight must go to g2} 27. Ng2 Qc6 28. f3 (28. f4
gxf4 29. gxf4) 28... Qxf3+ 29. Kg1 Re3 $1 30. Rxe3 (30. Nxe3 dxe3 {
and there is nothing to do against Qh1}) (30. Rcd1 $5 {
defending the bishop on d3 and threating Rf1 was a better defencive way}) 30...
dxe3 31. Rf1 Qg4 32. f6 $2 (32. Qe2) (32. Be2) (32. Nxe3 {Petursson} Bd4 33.
Qf2 Qh5 34. Re1 Re8 35. Bf1 {had to be tried}) 32... Rxf6 33. Rxf6 Bxf6 34.
Bxh7+ Kh8 35. Bd3 Bd4 36. Qe2 $4 {
a terrible blunder losing immediately white must have played 36.Be2} (36. Be2
Qe6 37. Qd1 {black was threatening Qf6} Qe4 38. Qf1 Kg7 {
and white's position is hopeless}) 36... Bf3 0-1

