1. d4 {Shamkovich} Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 c5 4. d5 d6 5. Nc3 exd5 6. cxd5 g6 7. e4
Bg7 8. h3 O-O 9. Bd3 b5 $5 {This tactical shot initiates a forced sequence, in
which Black's chances are certainly better, than in the quiet lines. After e.g.
9...Nbd7 White's center and space advantage give him the upper hand.   
Shamkovich: This sharp continuation leads to interesting complications} 10.
Bxb5 (10. Nxb5 Re8 11. Nd2 Nxd5 12. Nc4 Nb4 13. Be2 Ba6 14. Nbxd6 Re6 15. Bf4
Nd7 16. O-O Ne5 17. Bxe5 Bxe5 18. a3 Rxd6 19. Nxd6 Qxd6 20. axb4 Qxd1 21. Bxd1
(21. Rfxd1 Bxe2 22. Rd2 Bb5 $13) 21... Bxf1 22. Kxf1 cxb4 (22... Bxb2 23. Ra2
Bd4 24. b5 c4 $11) 23. Ra4 a5 24. b3 Rd8 25. Be2 Bc7 {
1/2,Hilarp Persson,T-Gdanski,J/Goteborg Excelsior Cup/1997/}) 10... Nxe4 11.
Nxe4 Qa5+ 12. Nfd2 Qxb5 13. Nxd6 Qa6 (13... Qd3 14. N2c4 Qxd1+ 15. Kxd1 {
gives White more chances to get an advantage.}) 14. N2c4 Nd7 15. O-O Nb6 16.
Nxb6 Qxb6 17. Nxc8 Raxc8 18. Rb1 $5 {The latest wrinkle. After other moves
Black usually quickly regains his pawn with a drawish position.} Rfd8 $5 ({
Not long ago} 18... Qd6 {was considered the best, as now the d-pawn really
falls. But lately White managed to create some problems for Black  especially
after this move.} 19. Bg5 $5 (19. Be3 $5 Rfd8 20. Qa4 Qxd5 21. Rfd1 Bd4 22. Rd2
Qc6 23. Qxc6 Rxc6 24. b3 $14 {Kozul,Z-Vranesic,Z/Toronto/1990/}) (19. Re1 Rcd8
20. Bg5 f6 $6 (20... Rd7 $142) 21. Be3 Qxd5 22. Qa4 f5 23. Qxa7 f4 24. Bxc5 Ra8
25. Qe7 Rf7 26. Qe4 $1 $16 {Lima,D-Outerelo,M/Aceimar op/1995/}) (19. Qf3 Rfd8
20. Rd1 Bd4 21. Be3 Qxd5 22. Qxd5 Rxd5 23. Rd2 a5 24. Rbd1 Rb8 25. Kf1 Kg7 26.
Rc2 a4 27. Rcd2 Rf5 28. Bxd4+ cxd4 29. b3 axb3 30. axb3 Rxb3 31. Rxd4 {
1/2,Smejkal,J-Wahls,M/BL/1989/}) 19... h6 20. Be3 Rfd8 21. Qa4 Qxd5 22. Qxa7 c4
23. Qa4 Ra8 24. Qc2 Rxa2 25. Rfd1 Qa8 26. Rxd8+ Qxd8 27. Qxc4 Rxb2 28. Rxb2
Bxb2 29. Bxh6 $14 {Ibragimov,I-Nepomnishay,M/St.Petersburg op/1995/}) 19. Bf4 (
19. Bg5 $143 $6 Rd7 20. Qg4 Qb7 21. Rfd1 h5 {
1/2,Ibragimov,I-De Firmian,N/Reykjavik op/1994/}) 19... Qb7 $1 $146 {Topalov di
d his homework well and found an important improvement, which finally checks
the dangerous pawn. The previous tries failed rather drastically, e.g.} (19...
Rd7 20. d6 Bf8 21. Qg4 Qb7 22. Rfd1 Rc6 23. Rd2 Bxd6 24. Rbd1 Qc7 25. Rd5 h5
26. Qf3 Kf8 27. Be5 Qd8 28. b3 Qc7 29. Qd3 Ke7 30. g3 h4 31. Qe3 {
1-0,Grabarczyk,M-Oliwa,M/POL-ch Brzeg Dolny/1996/}) (19... Qa6 20. d6 Rd7 21.
Qd5 c4 22. Rbd1 Bxb2 23. Rfe1 Bf6 24. Be5 Bxe5 25. Rxe5 Rf8 26. Re7 Rdd8 27. d7
Qxa2 28. Rde1 Qa4 29. Kh2 a6 30. Rxf7 {
1-0,Rogozenko,D-Marin,M/Bucharest Ciocaltea/1995/}) 20. d6 Bf8 21. Qd2 (21. Qd3
{Simplest and the best is however} Bxd6 $1 (21... Qb4 $143 22. Qg3 $36 {o^d6})
(21... c4 22. Qg3 (22. Qd4 Bxd6 23. Bxd6 Rc6 $11) 22... Rc6 23. Rfd1 Qb6 $5 24.
Rd5 (24. d7 Qb7 25. Qg4 h5 $11) 24... Bxd6 25. Rbd1 Be7 $132) 22. Bxd6 Rc6 23.
Rfd1 Qd7 $1 {[]} (23... Qb6 $2 24. Bxc5 $16) 24. Qb5 Rxd6 25. Qxd7 R8xd7 26.
Rxd6 Rxd6 $11) 21... Bxd6 22. Bxd6 Rc6 23. Rfd1 Qa6 $1 (23... Rdxd6 $2 24. Qxd6
Rxd6 25. Rxd6 $16 {Two mobile R are stronger than the Q in such open positions.
}) 24. Qg5 (24. Qc2 Rcxd6 25. Rxd6 Rxd6 26. b3 Rd5 $11) 24... Rdxd6 (24...
Rcxd6 $2 25. Qxd8+ Rxd8 26. Rxd8+ Kg7 27. a3 $16) 25. Rxd6 Rxd6 26. Qxc5 Qxa2
$1 $11 {Shamkovich: Tactically, Black holds the equality Blow for blow.Black
has calculated the tactical sequence well and is rewarded by equality.} 27. Re1
Rd8 ({Also possible was} 27... Re6 28. Rd1 (28. Rxe6 Qxe6 29. Qxa7 Qe1+ 30. Kh2
Qe5+ $11) 28... Re8 $11 (28... Qxb2 $4 29. Rd8+ Kg7 30. Qf8+ Kf6 31. Qh8+ $18))
28. b4 a6 29. Qg5 Rf8 (29... Qd5 $4 30. Re8+ $18) (29... Rc8 $142 $5) 30. h4 {
Shamkovich: White is still better, but it is hard to believe that he can win
the game} Qc4 31. Qe7 h5 (31... Rb8 32. Re4 Qd5 $11) 32. g3 {White's pieces
are slightly more active, but of course this advantage is merely formal.
Karpov continues to probe in this lifeless position, probably due to
dissatisfaction with his result in Las Palmas.} Rc8 33. Rd1 Qc6 (33... Qc2 34.
Rd7 Qf5 35. Kg2 Kg7 $11) 34. Rd6 Qa8 (34... Qf3 $143 $6 35. Qe1 Ra8 36. Qd2 $14
) 35. Qe1 Qb7 (35... Rc6 $143 36. Rd7 $36) 36. Qd2 Re8 37. Qc3 Rc8 38. Qd2 Re8
39. Rd5 Qc6 40. Kh2 Qf6 41. Rd4 Qc6 $6 (41... Kg7 $142 42. Rd6 Re6 $11 {
Black should have moved his K to a safer place long ago and would have saved
himself the trouble later on.}) 42. Rd6 Qf3 43. Qd4 Qe4 44. Qc3 Qb7 (44... Re6
$5 45. Qc8+ Re8 $142 $11 (45... Kg7 46. Qxa6 Qxb4 {
leads to the position in the game.} (46... Qf3 47. Qa1+ Kh7 48. Rd2))) 45. Rc6
Qb5 46. Rf6 $1 $36 Re7 47. Qc8+ Re8 48. Qxa6 Qxb4 49. Qa2 $1 {This double
attack against f7 and g6 wins a pawn. Luckily for Black the arising Q_|_
doesn't offer Karpov realistic winning chances.    Shamkovich: suddenly,
Topalov realized that he must give up a pawn (the threat is Rxg6+) Yet it
seems that the Queen ending is still drawn} Re6 $1 {[]} (49... Qe7 $2 50. Rxg6+
Kh7 51. Rg5 $18) 50. Rxe6 fxe6 51. Qxe6+ Kg7 52. Qd7+ Kf6 53. Qc6+ Kg7 54. Qd5
Qc3 55. Kg2 Qf6 56. Qd7+ Kg8 57. Qc7 Qe6 58. Qf4 Qc6+ 59. Kf1 Qe6 60. Qe3 Qc4+
61. Ke1 Qc2 62. Kf1 Qd1+ 63. Kg2 Qd5+ 64. f3 {White can't penetrate anywhere
with his K and after advancing his pawns he will be liable to perpetual check.}
(64. Qf3 Qe5 $11) 64... Qa2+ 65. Kh3 Qb1 66. g4 hxg4+ 67. fxg4 Qf1+ 68. Kg3 Qf6
69. Qc5 Qe6 70. Qc3 Qe4 1/2-1/2

