Qd1 (13. Qb2 a4 14. b4 d5 $15) 13... d5 (13... a4 14. bxa4 d5 15. cxd5 Qxd5 16.
a5 $1 $14) 14. Rc1 Nbd7 15. Re1 (15. Bh3 $6 dxc4 16. bxc4 Bxf3 17. exf3 e5 $1)
15... Qc8 16. Bf1 Qb7 (16... Bxf3 17. exf3 $14 {/\ f4, Bg2}) 17. Nd2 Bh7 18.
Bb2 c6 19. e3 b5 $5 20. cxb5 (20. c5 a4 $15) 20... cxb5 21. Qe2 $1 Reb8 (21...
Rab8 22. Bc3 $5) 22. f3 $14 {Karpov,A-Anand,V/Tilburg 1991/1-0 (53)}) (9... Be4
10. Qb2 d5 11. a3 Bxd2 12. Nbxd2 Nbd7 13. Rfd1 Qe7 14. Rac1 c6 15. Nxe4 Nxe4
16. cxd5 cxd5 17. Rc2 {
1/2-1/2 Garcia Ilundain,D-Gomez Esteban,J/Linares zt 1995}) 10. Nbxd2 d5 11.
Rfd1 $146 (11. cxd5 exd5 12. Ne5 Qe7 13. Ndc4 g6 14. Rac1 Na6 15. Qb2 Rac8 16.
Rfd1 Ne8 17. Ne3 c6 18. a3 Nd6 19. Rd2 Kg7 20. Rdc2 Nb8 21. a4 f6 22. Nd3 Rce8
23. b4 axb4 24. Qxb4 $16 {
1-0 Beliavsky-Ahmed/32nd Chess Olympiad, Yerevan 1996 (33)}) 11... Na6 12. cxd5
exd5 13. Nf1 (13. Rac1 Re8 14. Ne5 c5 15. Ndf3 Ne4 $11) (13. Ne5 Re8 {
with next c5}) 13... Ne4 (13... c5 14. Ne3 $14) 14. Ne5 (14. Rac1 Qf6 15. e3 c5
16. Ne5 Rfc8 17. Qb2 cxd4 18. exd4 b5 $132) 14... Qe7 $6 (14... Nb4 $142 15.
Qb2 f6 16. Nf3 $14) 15. Bxe4 $1 {Unusual, positional decision, but very strong.
} dxe4 16. a3 $1 c5 (16... Rad8 17. Nc6 Bxc6 18. Qxc6 Nb8 19. Qb7 $1 $16) 17.
Nc4 Rad8 (17... cxd4 $142 18. Rxd4 (18. Nxb6 $2 Rad8 $17) 18... Rad8 19. Rad1
Rxd4 20. Rxd4 Qc7 (20... Rd8 21. Qd2 Rxd4 22. Qxd4 Nc5 23. b4) 21. Nfe3 Nc5 22.
Qd1 $14) 18. d5 b5 (18... Rxd5 $143 19. Nxb6 Rxd1 20. Rxd1 Rd8 21. Ne3 $16) 19.
d6 Qe6 20. Nxa5 Ba8 (20... Bd5 21. Ne3 Rxd6 22. a4) 21. a4 bxa4 22. bxa4 Rxd6
23. Rxd6 Qxd6 24. Rd1 Qc7 (24... Qe6 25. Ne3 $16) 25. Qc3 Rd8 (25... Nb4 26.
Nb3 Rc8 27. Qxc5) 26. Rxd8+ Qxd8 27. Nb3 h6 28. Ne3 $16 {it's difficult to
believe , but black's position is very hard.The  white's  piecies  more active
, than their opponents, as well , as  a pawn more dangerous,than black's one,
at the same time black has no active play and white can gradually to intesify
their position.} Qc8 29. h4 h5 30. a5 g6 31. Qf6 Qc6 (31... c4 $2 32. Qc3 $18)
(31... Qb7 32. Nd2) 32. Qd8+ Kg7 33. Nd2 Nc7 34. Ndc4 Ne6 35. Qb8 Qa6 (35...
Nd4 36. Kf1 Bb7 37. Qe5+ Kg8 38. Nd6 Ba6 39. Qe7 {with decisive attack.}) 36.
Nd6 $2 {i think  the time trouble mistake.} (36. Qb6 Qxb6 (36... Bb7 37. Nd6
$18) 37. axb6 Kf6 38. Na5 Nd8 39. Kf1 Ke6 40. Ke1 Kd6 41. Kd2 Bb7 42. Ng2 Ba6
$11) (36. Qd6 Qxd6 37. Nxd6 Nc7 {not so clear.}) (36. Nb6 Bc6) (36. Qe8 Bc6 37.
Qe7 Qb7 38. Qd6 Bb5 $11) (36. Qe5+ $1 {was the right way.} Kg8 (36... f6 37.
Qb8 {and black has no chances to hold position.}) 37. Qf6) 36... Bc6 $2 (36...
Qxa5 37. Qe8 (37. Ne8+ Kh7 38. Nf6+ Kg7 39. Ne8+ Kh7 40. Qe5 Qe1+ 41. Kg2 Qxe2
42. Nf6+ Kh6 43. Ng8+ Kh7 $11) 37... Qa7 38. Nxf7 Qxf7 39. Qxa8 Nd4 40. Qxe4
Nxe2+ 41. Kg2 Nd4 {and it must be draw.}) 37. Qb6 Qa8 (37... Qxb6 38. axb6 Nd8
39. Nec4 $18) 38. a6 Nd4 39. Kf1 Ne6 40. a7 {Fantastic domination of white
piecies,of course black hopeless against 41Qb8 with next Ne3-c4-a5-b7. We are
not often see , such a  positional games of  Veselin, usually his games full
of tactics and complicated variations;no wonder , that he considered  one of
the best players of the world.} 1-0

