1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5 {
Topalov is the only one of the world elite who employs this sharp opening.} 4.
d5 d6 {A refined move order, championed by the great Benoni devotee Mihai Suba.
The point is after} (4... exd5 5. cxd5 d6 {White can, amongst others, continue}
6. e4 $5 g6 7. Bd3 {and the Nb1 can be also developed via a3 or d2, thus
controlling the important c4 square. Thus 4...d6 limits White's options.}) 5.
Nc3 exd5 6. cxd5 g6 7. e4 {Currently White's most popular weapon against the
Benoni is the setup with Bd3,h3, and subsequent play in the center.} ({
If White tries to reach his goal by a different move order} 7. h3 {
he must be prepared also for} a6 (7... Bg7 8. e4 {-A70}) 8. a4 Qe7 $5 {
Here White's attempts to gain an advantage have not been too successful lately:
} 9. Bg5 h6 10. Bh4 Nbd7 (10... Bg7 11. e3 Bf5 $5 12. Bd3 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 O-O 14.
O-O Nbd7 15. e4 Rfe8 16. Rfe1 g5 17. Bg3 Nh5 18. Bh2 Ne5 19. Nxe5 Bxe5 20. Qf3
Bxh2+ 21. Kxh2 Qe5+ 22. g3 Nf6 23. Qe3 Qd4 24. Rad1 Qxe3 25. Rxe3 Rab8 26. Rde1
b5 27. axb5 axb5 28. e5 $11 {Komarov,D-Yudasin,L/St.Petersburg/1997/}) 11. e3
Bg7 12. Nd2 O-O 13. Bd3 Rb8 14. O-O g5 15. Bg3 Ne8 16. Qc2 Ne5 17. Bh7+ Kh8 18.
Bf5 Bxf5 19. Qxf5 b5 20. axb5 axb5 21. Ra5 Nc4 22. Nxc4 bxc4 23. Ra2 Kg8 24.
Rc1 Rb4 $132 {Cramling,P-Suba,M/ESP-chT/1994/}) 7... a6 {
Last year Topalov managed to take some sting out of the aforementioned line:} (
7... Bg7 8. h3 O-O 9. Bd3 b5 $1 10. Bxb5 Nxe4 11. Nxe4 Qa5+ 12. Nfd2 Qxb5 13.
Nxd6 Qa6 14. N2c4 Nd7 15. O-O Nb6 16. Nxb6 Qxb6 17. Nxc8 Raxc8 18. Rb1 Rfd8 19.
Bf4 Qb7 $1 {This new move neutralizes the passed pawn for good.} 20. d6 Bf8 21.
Qd2 Bxd6 $1 22. Bxd6 Rc6 23. Rfd1 Qa6 24. Qg5 Rdxd6 25. Rxd6 Rxd6 26. Qxc5 Qxa2
$11 {Kaprov,An-Topalov,V/Las Palmas/1996/ Now, however, hte Bulgarian
grandmaster plays a more ambitious move, which is new in his Black repertoire.}
) 8. a4 {This prophylaxis is usually played automatically, but it certainly is
not the only move.} ({Another move deserves more attention:} 8. Bf4 b5 9. Qe2
$5 Be7 10. Qc2 O-O 11. a4 b4 12. Nb1 Re8 13. Bd3 Bf8 14. O-O b3 (14... a5 15.
Nbd2 Nbd7 16. h3 Nb6 17. Rfe1 Nfd7 18. Bb5 Ba6 19. Bc6 Ra7 20. e5 dxe5 21. Nxe5
Nxe5 22. Bxe5 Ree7 23. Rad1 $16 {Yakovich,Y-Filippov,V/Jekaterinburg/1997/})
15. Qxb3 Nxe4 16. Nc3 Nf6 17. a5 Nbd7 18. Qc2 Nh5 19. Bg5 Be7 20. Bd2 Bf6 21.
Ne4 Be7 22. Rfe1 Nhf6 23. Nc3 Bf8 24. Rxe8 Qxe8 25. h3 Rb8 26. Bc4 Ne5 27. Nxe5
Qxe5 28. Re1 Qd4 29. b3 Bb7 30. Be3 Qh4 31. Qd3 Ra8 32. Bd2 $16 {
Yakovich,Y-Totsky,L/St.Petersburg op/1994/}) ({Rather tame seems to be} 8. h3
b5 9. Bd3 Bg7 10. O-O c4 $5 11. Bc2 O-O 12. Bf4 Re8 13. Re1 Bb7 14. a3 Qb6 15.
Be3 Qc7 16. Nd4 Nbd7 17. Qd2 Nc5 18. f3 Re7 19. Re2 Nfd7 20. Nd1 Nb6 $13 {
Malaniuk,V-Emms,J/Hastings/1996/}) 8... Bg4 ({
Black has a good reason to avoid the lines after} 8... Bg7 9. h3 O-O 10. Bd3)
9. Qb3 {The most ambitious, but also extremely risky} (9. Be2 Bxf3 10. Bxf3
Nbd7 11. O-O Bg7 12. Bf4 Qe7 {
doesn't give White big chances to gain an advantage.}) ({The same applies to} 
9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Nbd7 11. Be2 Bg7 12. O-O O-O 13. Bf4 Qe7 14. Rfe1 Rae8 15.
Bf1 Nh5 {1/2,Topalov,V-Franco,Z/Elgoibar/1991/}) 9... Bxf3 ({After} 9... Qc7 $6
10. Nd2 {the B-sortie just looses sense.}) 10. Qxb7 (10. gxf3 $143 Qc7 $132 {
><[+],f2,f3}) 10... Nbd7 $5 {An enterprising sacrifice of 1-2 pawns.} ({
Also possible is} 10... Bxg2 11. Bxg2 Nbd7 12. O-O (12. Qc6 Be7 13. e5 Rc8 14.
exf6 Rxc6 15. fxe7 Qxe7+ 16. Kd1 Rb6 17. Re1 Ne5 18. f4 O-O 19. fxe5 dxe5 20.
Kc2 f5 21. Rb1 Rb4 22. Be3 Rfb8 23. Bf1 Qb7 24. Bxc5 Rxb2+ 25. Kd3 Rc8 {
0-1,Olafsson,H-De Firmian,N/Reykjavik op/1994/}) 12... Qb8 $5 (12... Be7 $5 $11
) (12... Bg7 $5 13. Bf4 $36) 13. Qc6 Bg7 14. Bf4 Ke7 15. e5 dxe5 16. Rfe1 Rd8
17. d6+ Qxd6 18. Qxd6+ Kxd6 19. Rad1+ Ke6 20. Bg5 h6 $5 $13 {
