1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 c5 5. Nge2 cxd4 6. exd4 O-O 7. a3 Be7 8. d5
exd5 9. cxd5 Bc5 10. Nd4 $6 {The more I look at this variation, the more I am
convinced that if black is allowed to construct his 'standard' position
without interference he can look forward to a comfortable middle-game.} d6 11.
Be2 a6 12. O-O Nbd7 13. Be3 {This seems a logical attempt to keep this piece
in the centre to contest the key dark squares, but as we shall see this is not
the whole story! The older move was} (13. Bg5 Re8 14. b4 (14. Nb3 Ba7 15. Nd2
h6 16. Bh4 Ne5 17. Nde4 g5 18. Nxf6+ Qxf6 19. Bg3 Bf5 20. Kh1 Ng6 21. Bg4 Nf4
$1 $15 {Sadler,M-Short,N/ch-GBR, Torquay ENG 1998.}) 14... Ba7 15. Rc1 h6 16.
Bh4 Nf8 17. h3 Bd7 18. Bg3 {It may be that g3, pressuring black's only really
discernable weakness, is after all the best square for this piece.} Rc8 19. Bf3
Qb6 20. Nb3 Ng6 21. Na5 Ne5 22. Be2 Qd4 23. Qb3 Nd3 24. Bxd3 Qxd3 25. Bxd6 Bd4
26. Na2 Qxb3 27. Nxb3 Bb2 28. Rxc8 Rxc8 29. Nc5 Bxa3 $11 {
Lautier,J-Anand,V/Monte Carlo 1997/EXP 57.}) 13... Ne5 14. h3 Re8 15. b4 $6 {
An understandable decision, since if white does not expand on the queen-side
it is hard to suggest a plan. Still, the weakness of c4 is by no means just
theoretical.} Bb6 {The choice of between b6 and a7 is here rather simply
determined. Since there are potential tactics on the e3-a7 diagonal the bishop
is most solidly placed on the square where its defender can stay put for some
time. Since the a8 rook is urgently needed to exploit white's 'looseness' on
the c-file the queen best performs this role, and hence Topalov's move is the
most logical.} 16. Qb3 {Choosing a square for the white queen is more tricky.
The text is suitable for offering support to the weakened c4 square, and for
promoting white's plan of pushing his queenside pawns ( it is difficult indeed
to see another plan! ). On the other hand the d2 square might, as we shall see,
be a more prudent choice for the less ambitious role of keeping white's
centralised pieces well defended.} Bd7 17. a4 Rc8 18. Rac1 Ng6 $1 {I already pr
efer black, and it may be that even after a more prudent move such as} 19. Rfd1
$2 (19. Rfe1 {black can consider the positional sacrifice} Rxe3 $5 20. fxe3 Qe7
21. Bf1 Qe5 $5 {with great play on the dark squares. However, the text is
clearly a mistake after which black gets decisive tactical threats instead of
mere positional compensation.}) 19... Rxe3 $1 $17 {A beautiful resolution of
the tension by which black shows that his superiority on the dark squares is
not so latent after all. The very concrete tactical follow-up however, puts
this more into the category of combination than intuitive sacrifice.} 20. fxe3
Qe7 (20... Qe8 $5 {is also possible, eyeing a4 and thus preventing the game
defence. However, white can still struggle with} 21. Kf2 $5 Rxc3 $5 22. Rxc3
Bxa4 23. Rc8 $1 Qxc8 24. Qxa4 Nxd5 25. Bg4 Qd8 $17) 21. Na2 Rxc1 22. Nxc1 Bxa4
$1 23. Qxa4 Qxe3+ 24. Kh1 Ne4 $6 {Unnecessary sophistication! The simple} (
24... Bxd4 $1 {looks very strong.}) 25. Nf5 (25. Qe8+ $1 Nf8 26. Ne6 {Fritz 5!}
fxe6 27. dxe6 Nf2+ 28. Kh2 Qxe6 29. Qxe6+ Nxe6 30. Re1 {is far from clear.})
25... Nf2+ 26. Kh2 Qe5+ 27. Ng3 Ne4 28. Qb3 Bf2 29. Rd3 h5 $1 $19 30. Bxh5 Nxg3
31. Rxg3 Qxh5 $1 (31... Bxg3+ $2 32. Qxg3 Qxh5 33. Qxd6 $132) 32. Rxg6 {
The rook cannot run away, since, thematically enough, black would then
penetrate on the dark squares eg.} (32. Rf3 Qe5+ 33. g3 Qe1) 32... Qxg6 33. Qf3
Bd4 34. Nd3 Qg5 35. Qe4 Qe3 36. Qxe3 Bxe3 {With a pawn and an excellent minor
piece, the technical phase poses no difficulties.} 37. Kg3 g6 38. Kf3 Bd4 39.
Ke2 Kg7 40. Ne1 Kf6 41. Kd3 Bf2 42. Nf3 Kf5 43. Ke2 Ba7 0-1

