1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 c5 5. Nge2 cxd4 6. exd4 O-O 7. a3 Be7 8. d5
exd5 9. cxd5 Bc5 10. b4 $5 {I am sure that white has to look here to those
moves which disrupt the smooth flow of black's planned set-up, viz: ...d6, ...
Re8, ...Nbd7, ...a6 etc. Either 10 Na4, or the text therefore look the most
likely to make an impact, and I am not surprised to see Sadler turn to it.} ({
After} 10. Na4 $5 {the reply} b6 {seems to be holding up well eg.} 11. Nec3 $5
{I prefer this to} (11. Nxc5 $6 bxc5 12. Nc3 Re8+ 13. Be2 Ba6 14. O-O Bxe2 15.
Nxe2 Qb6 16. Nc3 d6 17. Rb1 Nbd7 18. Be3 Qa6 19. b4 Qc4 20. Qd2 Rac8 21. bxc5
Nxc5 22. Nb5 Nce4 {
when black was very active.  Gallego,V-Lalic,B/Benasque 1996/CBM 53 ext.})
11... Re8+ 12. Be2 Ba6 13. O-O Bxe2 14. Nxe2 Na6 15. Nac3 $5 Bd6 16. h3 Nc5 17.
Be3 Nfe4 18. Rc1 Qf6 19. b4 Nxc3 20. Nxc3 Ne4 21. Nb5 $5 Qe5 22. Nxd6 Qxd6 23.
Qd3 Nf6 24. Rfd1 Rac8 {with a very slight edge for white at the most..
Yakovich,Y-Alterman,B/Beijing 1997/CBM 61.}) 10... Bd6 {Topalov decides to
keep this piece, since white's arguably loosening 10th move creates  fresh
opportunities for play on the e5-a1 diagonal. It is also quite possible to
play 10...Bb6 and look to rapid development to compensate for the bishop pair
after} (10... Bb6 11. Na4 Re8 $1 12. Nxb6 axb6 13. h3 $5 d6 (13... Re5 $6 {
This kind of greed is very often misguided in these positions} 14. Bb2 Rxd5 15.
Qc2 Nc6 16. g4 d6 17. Bg2 Be6 18. O-O Rc8 19. Nf4 Rg5 20. Nxe6 fxe6 21. f4 $16
{Malaniuk,V-Tunik,G/Yalta op 1996}) 14. Be3 Ne4 $1 {Black's counterchances
rest on impeding white's development and play on the light squares.} 15. Qd4
Nd7 16. g4 f5 $1 17. Bg2 Ne5 18. O-O Ng6 $1 19. gxf5 Bxf5 20. Ng3 Nh4 21. Nxf5
Nxf5 22. Qxb6 Qf6 23. Bf4 Nh4 $44 {Guliev,S-Volzhin,A/Moscow 1994/CBM 45 ext.})
11. g3 (11. Bb2 Be5 12. Ng3 a5 13. b5 (13. Be2 axb4 14. axb4 Rxa1 15. Qxa1 Na6)
13... d6 14. Be2 Nbd7 (14... Nfd7 15. O-O Nc5 16. f4 Bf6 17. Nh5 $1 $40) 15.
O-O Nc5 (15... Nb6 $5 16. f4 (16. Qd2 Nbxd5 17. Nxd5 Bxb2) (16. Bf3 $2 Nc4 $132
) 16... Bxc3 17. Bxc3 Nbxd5 18. Bd4 Re8 19. Qd2 $44 Bg4 $140 $5 20. Bd3 $1 (20.
Bxg4 $6 Nxg4 21. Bxg7 Qh4 22. h3 Nge3 23. Rf3 Rac8 24. Re1 Kxg7 25. Rfxe3 Nxe3
26. Rxe3 Kg8 27. Nf5 Qf6 $15)) 16. f4 Bxc3 17. Bxc3 a4 18. f5 Bd7 19. Rb1 Re8
$132 {Knaak,R-Piket,J/GER-chT 1997. Black has sufficent squares for his
knights and rook to compensate for the bishop pair.}) 11... Re8 12. Bg2 Be5 13.
O-O a5 $1 {An important element in black's set-up. He needs either the c5
square, or a weak b4 pawn to attack.} 14. b5 (14. Bb2 axb4 15. axb4 Rxa1 16.
Bxa1 Na6 $5 (16... d6) 17. f4 $5 (17. b5 Nc5 $132) 17... Bxc3 (17... Qb6+ 18.
Kh1 Bxc3 19. Nxc3 Qxb4 20. d6 $44 {looks quite reasonable for white since
there are still quite a few question marks hanging over black's development.})
18. Nxc3 $1 (18. Bxc3 Qe7 $1 $36) 18... Nxb4 (18... d6 19. Qd4 $14) 19. d6 Qb6+
$140 20. Kh1 Re6 21. Na4 Qxd6 22. Qxd6 Rxd6 23. Rc1 $132 {I am not surprised
that Sadler rejected 14 Bb2 since it looks rather speculative, but still I
find it interesting and worth further investigation.}) 14... d6 15. h3 (15. f4
Qb6+ 16. Kh1 Bxc3 17. Nxc3 Bg4 $5 $132 (17... Bf5) (17... Ng4 $6 18. Ra2 $1 $14
)) 15... Nfd7 $5 16. f4 Bf6 17. Ra2 $1 {Efficient development. Working along
the second rank the rook can find a role either on the c-file, or supporting
the king-side push. The c1 bishop, on the other hand, is best placed at home,
particularly covering e3.} Nc5 18. g4 g6 $1 19. Rc2 Bg7 {
Is this really what Nimzovitch had in mind?} 20. Ng3 Nbd7 {The position
somewhat resembles a Benoni. Black has a great square on c5, but white has
secured the e4 square, and will challenge this with Ne4 while keeping some
hopes on the king-side.} 21. Kh2 $5 {This square turns out to have some
drawbacks in the game continuation, but at the same time there are good
reasons to wish to vacate g1 ( the desire to threaten d6 among others ).
Black's reply also raises interesting questions. It arguably misplaces his
other knight, since that would ideally reserve the option to jump into c5
after its colleague is exchanged. On the other hand, the bishop on c8 gets to
support f5.} (21. Nce4 Nxe4 22. Nxe4 f5 (22... Nc5 $5) 23. gxf5 gxf5 24. Ng5
Nf6 (24... Nc5 $6 25. Qh5 h6 $140 26. Qf7+ Kh8 27. Bb2) 25. Qd3 $5) 21... Nb6
22. Nce4 Nxe4 23. Nxe4 f5 24. Ng5 (24. gxf5 $2 Bxf5 $17) 24... fxg4 25. hxg4
Bd7 26. Ne6 (26. Rh1 $5 {-Fritz 5.}) 26... Qh4+ 27. Kg1 Bxe6 28. dxe6 Rxe6 29.
Rc7 $1 (29. Bxb7 Rae8 $40) 29... Re7 (29... Rae8 $2 30. Rxg7+ Kxg7 31. Qd4+ Kg8
32. Qxb6 Qxg4 (32... Re1 33. Bd5+) 33. Qxb7) (29... d5 30. Rxb7 Rae8 31. Rxg7+
Kxg7 32. Bb2+ Kf7 33. Qd4 $132) 30. Rxb7 Rxb7 31. Bxb7 Qg3+ 32. Kh1 $1 (32. Bg2
Rc8 33. Qxd6 (33. Qf3 Bd4+ 34. Kh1 Qh4+ 35. Qh3 Qxh3+ 36. Bxh3 Rc3 37. Bg2 Bc5
$132) 33... Rc2 34. Bd2 Qxg4 $13) 32... Qh3+ (32... Re8 33. Qf3 Qh4+ 34. Kg2
$14) 33. Kg1 Qg3+ 34. Kh1 Qh3+ 1/2-1/2

