1. e4 {Alterman,B} c5 2. Nc3 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 6. Be3 Nf6 7.
Bc4 O-O 8. Bb3 a5 9. a4 Ng4 10. Qxg4 Nxd4 11. Qh4 d6 $5 {After} (11... Nxb3 12.
cxb3 d6 {is supposed to be bad because of:} 13. Nd5) 12. Nd5 (12. O-O Nxb3 13.
cxb3 Be6 $132) 12... Re8 13. Rd1 (13. O-O Be6 $132) 13... Nxb3 14. Bb6 {
'!' Alterman,B.} (14. cxb3 {Alterman,B} Ra6 15. Bg5 f6 16. Bh6 Rc6 $11) 14...
Qd7 15. cxb3 Ra6 16. Bd4 Qd8 {The blacksquared B will soon be exchanged so the
black Q has to be in a position to defend these squares.} 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 {
Threatening to exchange even more pieces with e7-e6. After alle black has the
slightly better P-structure so the ending might even be a little bit better
for him} 18. Qg3 (18. O-O $6 {Alterman,B} e6 19. Qxd8 Rxd8 20. Ne3 Rc6 $1 21.
Nc4 b6 22. Rd4 Ba6 $11) 18... Be6 {in the lines where black plays d7-d6 this
bishop is always well-placed on e6. It attacks the P on b3 and can be
exchanged against the strong N on d5.} 19. O-O Rc6 20. Qe3 Bxd5 (20... f6 $5 {
maybe best. The idea is to follow up with Rc5-c5 and b7-b5} 21. Nf4 Bf7 {
This is why f7-f6 maybe better than 20. - Rc5}) (20... Rc5 {
Black would like to see what white will do before he takes on d5} 21. Nf4 $5
$14) 21. exd5 Rc5 22. h4 $1 $14 {'|^' Alterman,B.  ()} (22. f4 $5) 22... Qd7 (
22... e5 $2 23. dxe6 Rxe6 {
would be a good idea if it was not for the tactical trick:} 24. Qxc5) (22... h5
23. f4 (23. Rd4 $14 {Alterman,B}) 23... Qb6 24. Kh1 $36) 23. Qd4+ Kg8 24. h5
Qf5 {Now d5 is just as weak as e7, but still black has some problems after the
opening of the h-<-> to coordinate the defence of Kg8 and Pe7} 25. hxg6 hxg6
26. Rfe1 b5 (26... e5 {Alterman,B} 27. dxe6 Rxe6 28. Rxe6 Qxe6 29. Qxd6 Qxd6
30. Rxd6 Rc1+ 31. Kh2 Rc2 32. Kg3 Rxb2 33. Rb6 $16) 27. Rd3 (27. Re3 {
Now the R on the third rank now does not have to cover d5 as in the game.} b4 (
27... f6 $6 28. axb5 Rxb5 29. Qa4 $1 $14) 28. Rh3 Qf6 $1 {
This is the negative side of 27.Te3 - no pressure in the e-<->}) 27... f6 28.
axb5 (28. Rh3 {Alterman,B} g5 29. Qd1 Qxd5 30. Qh5 Kf8 31. Qh6+ Kf7 $11) 28...
Rxb5 29. Rh3 g5 30. Qc4 Rb4 $6 (30... Rc5 31. Qa4 $14) (30... Qxd5 $1 31. Qe2
$44 {However this is similar to a postion in the game - only in the game black
does not have an extra P} (31. Qc2 Qf7 $17) (31. Rxe7 {Alterman,B} Rxe7 32.
Qc8+ Kf7 33. Rh7+ Kg6 34. Rxe7 Qd1+ 35. Kh2 Qh5+ $11) 31... Kg7 32. Rh7+ (32.
Qh5 Qg8 33. f4 (33. Rc1 Kf8 $5 (33... Rc5 $11)) 33... Kf8 {
Black does not seem to be in any real danger - white is a P down.}) 32... Kxh7
33. Qh5+ Kg7 34. Qxe8 Rb7 $11) 31. Qe2 Qg6 (31... Qxd5 {Alterman,B} 32. Qh5 Kf8
$1 33. Qh6+ (33. Rhe3 Rh4) 33... Kf7 34. Qh7+ Kf8 $11) 32. Qe6+ Kg7 33. Qd7 Qf7
34. Rhe3 Kf8 {'[]' Alterman,B.} (34... e5 {Alterman,B} 35. dxe6 Qxd7 36. exd7
Rd8 37. Re7+ Kg6 38. Rd1 $18) 35. Rh3 Kg7 36. Rhe3 (36. Re6 $5 {
With the idea 37.Rxd6 exd6 38.Rh7+ seems to put black in a difficult position}
Rbb8 37. Qa4 $1) 36... Kf8 37. Rh3 (37. Qa7 {Alterman,B} Rb5) 37... Kg7 1/2-1/2

