$19) 25... Kb6 (25... Qxe7 $2 26. Qxd4+ $18) (25... Kb8 26. Qxd4 Nd7 27. Bxd7
Bxd5 28. c4 $1 $18) 26. Qxd4+ Kxa5 (26... Qc5 27. Qxf6+ Qd6 28. Be6 $3 Bxd5 29.
b4 $18) 27. b4+ Ka4 28. Qc3 $5 {This shows Kasparov's combination was more
intuitive, than arithmetically exact. Ftacnik: 'It seems, that white could
have won more easily with the help of a fine move 28.Ra7!!'} ({
A simpler and even more beautiful win was found by (I think) Kavalek:} 28. Ra7
$1 {/\} Bb7 (28... Nxd5 {Ftacnik} 29. Rxa6+ $3 Qxa6 30. Qb2 Nc3+ 31. Qxc3 Bd5
32. Kb2 Qe6 33. Bxe6 fxe6 34. Qb3+ $1 Bxb3 35. cxb3#) 29. Rxb7 Qxd5 (29... Nxd5
30. Bd7 $3 Ra8 (30... Rxd7 31. Qb2 Nc3+ 32. Qxc3 Qd1+ 33. Kb2 Rd3 34. Ra7 $1
