1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Qa4+ Bd7 5. Qb3 dxc4 6. Qxc4 a6 $1 {I has foun
d this idea during my preparation to the match against Psakhis.It worked very
well and after several moves White had to be careful to equalize(The game you
can find below).} ({After natural} 6... Bg7 {
black has to solve serious problems.For example:} 7. e4 $1 O-O 8. e5 $1 Ng4 9.
d4 {and black has to choose between} Nc6 {
tried in the game Ivanchuk-Shirov,Rubinstein mem 1998} ({and} 9... Be6 10. d5
Bf5 11. Bf4 Nd7 12. Qe2 f6 {
Otherwise black pieces feel very uncomfortable on the kingside.} 13. e6 Nde5
14. Rd1 $1 $146 ({In the origin game black has got good counterchances after} 
14. Bxe5 fxe5 15. h3 Nf6 16. Rd1 e4 17. Ne5 c6 $1 18. dxc6 Qc7 19. cxb7 Rad8 $1
$36 {0-1 Goldin,A-Mikhalevski,V/Rishon Le Zion 1997/CBM 62 ext (30);71/12})
14... c6 $2 (14... Nxf3+ $5) (14... Qd6 $5) 15. Nd4 Bd3 16. Rxd3 Nxd3+ 17. Qxd3
cxd5 18. Be2 Ne5 19. Qb5 g5 20. Be3 f5 21. Bxg5 f4 22. O-O Ng6 23. Rd1 {
1-0 Rustemov,A-Zezulkin,J/Swidnica POL 1999 (23)My analysis of this game you
can find in CBM 71.}) {but after} 10. Bf4 Na5 11. Qe2 $1 $14 {
White is better in view of unfortunate position of black knights.}) 7. g3 {
Strange enough that Topalov chooses this inoffensive move.} (7. d4 {
Looks more logical and puts much more problems.} b5 8. Qb3 Nc6 9. Bf4 Bg7 10.
e3 O-O 11. Be2 Be6 12. Qd1 Nb4 $6 (12... Nd5 $5) 13. e4 $1 Bc4 14. a3 Nc6 15.
Bxc4 bxc4 16. O-O Rb8 17. d5 Nh5 18. Be3 Na5 19. Qa4 c6 20. dxc6 e6 21. e5 Qc7
22. g4 $18 {1-0 Lautier,J-Bacrot,E/Enghien-les-Bains FRA 1999 (30).See my
comments in CBM70.}) 7... Nc6 {Another surprise.} ({Why not} 7... b5 8. Qb3 c5
9. d3 Nc6 10. Bg2 Rc8 {solving all opening problems easily?} 11. Qd1 Bg7 12.
O-O O-O 13. Be3 Nb4 14. h3 Nfd5 15. Bd2 Nb6 16. Qc1 c4 17. dxc4 Rxc4 18. Bh6
N4d5 19. Bxg7 Kxg7 20. Ne5 Rc5 21. Bxd5 Nxd5 22. Nxd7 Qxd7 23. Rd1 Qc6 24. Rxd5
Rxd5 25. Nxd5 Qxd5 {1/2-1/2 Psakhis,L-Mikhalevski,V/Ramat Aviv 1998/CBM 68 (25)
}) 8. Bg2 Bg7 9. O-O e5 10. d3 h6 {Similar position with White's queen on d1
can be reached by 1.c4 Nf62.Nc3 d5 3.cd N:d5 4.g3g6 5.Bg2 Nb6 6.Nf3 Bg7 and so
on.The position of queen on c4 is in the Black's favour as he can win few
tempos by the means of Be6 and then Nd5 and Nb6.} 11. Rd1 Be6 12. Qa4 O-O 13.
Be3 Nd5 14. Bc5 Nb6 (14... Re8 $5 {leaving the idea of Nb6 for later use.} 15.
d4 Nxc3 (15... exd4 16. Nxd4 Nxd4 17. Bxd4 Nxc3 (17... Bxd4 18. Bxd5 $1) 18.
Bxc3 {with some pressure.}) 16. bxc3 e4 (16... exd4 17. Nxd4 Nxd4 18. Bxd4 $14
(18. cxd4 Bd5)) 17. Ne5 (17. Ne1 f5 18. d5 $140 $2 Bxd5 19. c4 b5 $1) 17... Bd5
(17... Nxe5 $5 18. dxe5 Qg5) 18. c4 (18. Qc2 $5) 18... b5 {and Black is OK.})
15. Qa3 Re8 16. Rac1 Nd4 {
White's queen life doesn't promise to be very quite in this game.} 17. Nd2 Nb5
18. Qb4 (18. Qa5 $143 Nd5 $1 (18... Nd7 19. Nxb5 b6 20. Qa3 $1) 19. Nxb5 $140
$2 b6 $1 20. Qa3 (20. Bxd5 $142) 20... axb5) 18... c6 19. Qa5 Nd7 20. Qxd8 {
A big relief for White.His main problem has finally gone.} Raxd8 $11 21. Bb4
Nf6 ({Of course not} 21... Nxc3 22. bxc3 Bxa2 $4 23. c4 {
and Black has to look for an escape by} a5) (21... c5 $2 22. Nxb5 cxb4 (22...
axb5 23. Bxc5) 23. Nc7 (23. Nd6 $5)) (21... Nd4 $5 {
in order to meet Ba5 with b6.} 22. e3 Nf5) 22. Ba5 Rb8 {
Creating a threat of b6 catching White's bishop.} 23. Nc4 Nd5 {
Look at this knight.That's its second loop.} 24. Nxd5 {
This knight should be killed.} cxd5 25. Nb6 e4 $5 {
An interesting decision.Black chooses immediate counterattack.} (25... Rbd8 26.
Na4 $1) (25... Nd4 $5 26. Kf1 Nc6 27. Bc3 Rbd8 $11) 26. e3 {
restricting Black's knight.} ({After} 26. dxe4 dxe4 {
Black's bishops are too active.}) 26... Bxb2 27. Rc2 Bg7 28. a4 exd3 (28... Na3
$6 {is dangerous in view of} 29. Ra2 Bf8 30. Rda1 exd3 31. Rxa3 Bxa3 32. Rxa3)
29. Rcc1 (29. Rxd3 $2 Bf5) 29... Na7 (29... Nd6 30. Nxd5 b6 31. Bb4 $1 $14 (31.
Bxb6 $2 Bxd5) (31. Nxb6 Bf5 $13)) 30. Rxd3 Nc6 31. Bc3 Ne5 {This knight has
worked not worse than its colleague and also is killed on its second loop.} 32.
Bxe5 Bxe5 33. Bxd5 Rbd8 ({After} 33... Bxd5 34. Rxd5 {White is slightly better.
}) 34. e4 Re7 35. Kg2 Bc7 36. Rb1 Kg7 {Preparing series of exchanges.} (36...
Bxd5 $2 37. Nxd5 Rxe4 $140 $2 38. Nf6+ Kg7 39. Rxd8 $18) 37. Nc4 Bd7 38. Rxb7 (
38. a5 Bb5) (38. Rxb7 {
Here are the variations which show possible developing of the play:} Bxa4 (
38... Bc6 $143 39. Ra7 Bxa4 (39... Rxe4 40. Bxc6 Rxc4 41. Rxd8 Bxd8 42. Rxa6
$14 (42. Bd5 $5 Rc7 43. Rxa6 $14)) 40. Rxa6 Bb5 (40... Bc2 41. Re3) 41. Ra7
Bxc4 (41... Rxd5 $2 42. Rxd5 Bxc4 43. Rc5 Bd6 44. Rxe7 Bxc5 45. Rc7) 42. Bxc4
Rxd3 (42... Rxe4 $2 43. Rxd8 (43. Rxc7 $2 Rxc4 $1 44. Rxf7+ Kxf7 45. Rxd8 $11)
43... Bxd8 44. Rxf7+ Kh8 45. Bd3 $18) 43. Bxd3 $14) 39. Nb6 (39. Rc3 Be8) 39...
Bb5 (39... Bc6 $6 40. Bxc6 $1 Rxd3 41. Nc8 $1 Red7 (41... Re6 $2 42. Bd5 $1)
42. Bxd7 (42. e5 a5 $3 43. Bxd7 Rxd7 {see 42.B:d7}) 42... Rxd7 43. e5 $1 (43.
Nb6 Rd6) 43... a5 $1 44. Nd6 (44. Nb6 Re7 45. Nd5 Rxe5 46. Nxc7 Re7 47. Ra7 a4
$1 $11) (44. Na7 Re7 45. Nc6 Rd7 $1 (45... Rxe5 $5 46. Nxe5 (46. Rxc7 Rc5 $11)
46... Bxe5 $14) 46. Nxa5 Rd5 47. Rxc7 Rxa5 48. e6 Kf6 49. exf7 Kg7 $11) (44.
Ra7 $5 a4 $1 45. Nb6 (45. Nd6 Re7 $1) 45... Re7 46. Nxa4 $14) 44... Rxd6 (44...
Re7 $2 45. Rxc7 $18) 45. exd6 Bxd6 $14) 40. Rc3 Bd6 41. Rxe7 Bxe7 42. Rc7 Kf8
$11) 1/2-1/2

