16. f5 b6 17. Qg4 a5 18. a3 Ra7 $13 19. Bg5 Bf6 20. Bh6 Bg7 21. Bg5 Bf6 22. Bh6
Bg7 23. Bg5 {1/2,Trifunovic,P-Forintos,G/EU-chT Hamburg/ 1965/}) 8... Qb6 (8...
e6 $6 {Prematurely opening the position, when Black is still undeveloped.} 9.
Na3 Ne7 10. Nb5 exd5 11. cxd5 f5 12. Nxd4 fxe4 13. Bb5+ Kf8 14. Ne6+ Bxe6 15.
dxe6 Qb6 16. Bd7 h5 17. Be3 Qxb2 18. Qxd6 Be5 19. Qc5 b6 20. Qc4 Bf6 21. Rab1
Qa3 22. Bd4 Kg7 23. Bxf6+ Kxf6 24. Qd4+ Kg5 25. Rb3 Qxa2 26. Rg3+ Kh6 27. Qf6 {
1-0,Chernin,A-Shirazi,K/New York/1989/}) (8... e5 9. dxe6 $5 fxe6 10. Qa4+ Qd7
11. Qb3 Ne7 12. Na3 O-O 13. Bg5 h6 14. Bh4 g5 15. Bg3 Ng6 16. Nb5 Nf4 17. Bxf4
Rxf4 18. g3 Rf8 19. Rad1 a6 20. Nxd4 Kh8 21. Nc2 Qc7 22. Qb4 Be5 23. Ne3 Qc5
24. Qd2 Bd7 25. Ng4 Bc6 26. b4 Qa7 27. Nxe5 dxe5 28. Qd6 Rf6 29. Qxe5 {
1-0,Sofieva,A-Mukhim,G/Leningrad/1990/}) 9. Nd2 Nf6 {
Black's N belongs on f6, on e7 it's misplaced.} 10. Rb1 {/\b4|^<<} a5 $1 11. b3
O-O 12. a3 $1 $146 {Certainly more logical, than} (12. Bb2 $143 $6 e5 13. Ba3
Bh6 $1 $36 14. c5 dxc5 15. Nc4 Qc7 16. d6 Qc6 17. Nxe5 Qxd6 18. Nc4 Qc7 19. Bf3
Be6 20. e5 Nd7 21. Re1 Bg7 22. Rc1 Rab8 23. Bg4 Bxg4 24. Qxg4 b5 25. e6 Nf6 26.
exf7+ Qxf7 {0-1,Hartoch,R-Tal,M/Wijk aan Zee/1973/}) 12... e5 13. b4 (13. dxe6
fxe6 14. b4 axb4 15. axb4 e5 $15 {(),[+]}) 13... axb4 14. axb4 Bd7 15. Bd3 (15.
c5 $6 dxc5 16. bxc5 Qxc5 17. Rxb7 Ba4 18. Qe1 Bc2 $36) 15... Qc7 16. Nb3 b6 $11
{/=/+ Black has stabilized his central and << position (by preventing c5) and
now can turn his sights to active play on the >>. His position is more
pleasant, although one can't speak aboout some sizeable advantage.} 17. Bd2 Nh5
18. Rc1 (18. Qc2 $5 $11 {/\c5}) 18... Ra3 $1 19. Ra1 (19. c5 dxc5 20. bxc5 Ba4
$17) 19... Rxa1 20. Nxa1 (20. Qxa1 f5 $5 $36) 20... Nf4 ({Overoptimistic is} 
20... f5 $2 21. exf5 Nf6 22. fxg6 e4 23. gxh7+ Kh8 24. Bc2 Qxc4 25. Bb3 $16) (
20... b5 $6 21. cxb5 Qb6 22. Qe2 Rb8 23. Nb3 Bxb5 24. Bxb5 Qxb5 25. Qxb5 Rxb5
26. Ra1 $36 {o^b}) 21. Bxf4 exf4 22. Nc2 Ba4 $5 (22... Ra8 23. Qd2 Be5 24. Ra1
Rxa1+ 25. Nxa1 Qa7 26. Qb2 $132 {/\Nc2,><d4}) 23. Qd2 Bxc2 24. Qxc2 Ra8 25. Qb2
Qa7 26. Rd1 Be5 $15 {^-,<->a Black has a slight edge, but it's somewhat
academical, as he has no realistic chances of preparing an effective pawn
break.} (26... f3 $5 27. gxf3 Qe7 28. Ra1 {<=>} Qg5+ 29. Kf1 $11) (26... Qa3
27. Qxa3 Rxa3 28. Kf1 Rb3 29. b5 $11 {/\Ke2,Ra1-a6}) 27. f3 Qa4 28. Rd2 Ra7 29.
Rc2 h5 30. Kf1 Qe8 (30... g5 31. h3 $11) 31. c5 $5 $132 {
White doesn't want to sit and wait.} (31. Rc1 {/\Ra1=} Qa8 $15) 31... bxc5 32.
bxc5 dxc5 33. Rxc5 Qa8 34. Rc1 Ra2 35. Qb3 Kg7 (35... Rd2 36. Rd1 $11) 36. Rd1
Qa5 37. Qb5 Qa3 38. d6 $5 {Again active defence by White.} (38. Qe8 $2 Qb2 39.
Qxe5+ Kh7 $19) (38. Kg1 $5 {/\} Rd2 39. Rxd2 Qc1+ 40. Bf1 Qxd2 41. Qd3 $11)
