1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 Ng4 7. Bc1 {
After my second round game against Kasparov I wasn't very convinced about} (7.
Bg5) 7... Nf6 8. Be2 e5 9. Nb3 Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Be3 {I used to employ} (11.
Kh1 {
but now decided to go for the line that Svidler and Short like among others.})
11... Be6 12. Nd5 Nbd7 13. Qd3 {The idea is to make quick threats against the
d6 pawn (by exchanging on e7 and putting the rook on d1). Black's reply is now
forced.} Bxd5 14. exd5 Nc5 15. Qd2 Nfe4 16. Qb4 b6 $5 $146 {
A new and interesting continuation.} (16... a5 {
was known but it weakens the White squares on the queenside.}) 17. f3 $5 {
Here I thought for some forty minutes. Nothing really attracted me, for example
} (17. Nxc5 Nxc5 18. a4 a5 $5 19. Qb5 Bg5 $5 20. Bxg5 Qxg5 21. Qxb6 Qe7 $44)
17... Nf6 18. Qd2 Qd7 $5 {Now I can repeat the queen's trip to b4 but already
attacking the b6 pawn. An alternative would be} (18... Nh5 $5) 19. f4 $1 Nfe4
20. Qb4 Rfb8 $1 21. Nxc5 $6 {Losing the touch. I should play} (21. Bf3 $5 {
with a very unclear position.}) 21... Nxc5 22. fxe5 $6 dxe5 23. Rad1 Bd6 $1 24.
Qh4 Rf8 $1 $15 {Here I realised that besides not having any advantage I was
also running the risk to get an inferior position. Now Black wants to play f5
which immediately was not good:} (24... f5 25. b4 Na4 26. Rxf5 $1 Qxf5 27. Bd3
{and Black is under fire.}) 25. g4 $1 Qa4 $1 26. c4 $1 {Forced.} (26. c3 $2 f5
$1 27. b4 Ne4 $17 {is curtains.}) 26... Qc2 $6 {By not taking the pawn Black
also gives White the initiative. It would be extremely difficult to prove
White's compensation after} (26... Qxa2 $1 {
but having analysed a great deal I think I managed it:} 27. Rf3 $1 (27. Rd2 $2
Rae8 $17) 27... Qxb2 28. Rh3 h6 $1 (28... Qc2 $6 29. Rd3 $1 (29. Rf1 $2 f6)
29... Qb1+ (29... h6 30. Bxh6 Qxe2 $2 31. Bxg7 $18) 30. Bf1 h6 31. Bxh6 Nxd3
32. Be3 $40) 29. g5 $1 (29. Bxh6 $2 Qxe2) 29... f6 (29... Be7 30. Qg4 $44) 30.
Bg4 $1 (30. g6 $2 f5) (30. gxh6 $2 Qxe2 31. Re1 (31. Rd2 g5 32. Bxg5 Qf1+ $3
33. Kxf1 fxg5+ 34. Qf2 Ne4 $19) 31... g5 $1 32. Bxg5 Qxe1+ 33. Qxe1 fxg5 $17)
30... fxg5 31. Bxg5 Qc2 $1 (31... Ra7 $2 32. Bxh6 gxh6 33. Qxh6 Qf2+ 34. Kh1
Qf6 35. Qh5 Rff7 36. Rg1 Kf8 37. Rf3 Qg7 38. Bf5 Qf6 39. Rg6 $18) 32. Bxh6 Qh7
33. Be3 Qxh4 34. Rxh4 {# Black is still pawn up and he has also exchanged
queens but I think that White holds enough fighting resources not to lose the
game. I think the assessment of this position is critical for the overall
evaluation of the 26...Qxa2 line.}) 27. Rd2 Qe4 28. Qh3 $1 $14 a5 29. b3 {
White's pieces are now better consolidated so he is not in hurry.} Qg6 30. Kh1
Qe4+ 31. Kg1 Qg6 32. g5 $1 {
Probably the best way to keep fighting for the advantage.} Ne4 33. Bd3 {
The temptation to win his queen was extremely high, so I didn't realise that} (
33. Bh5 $142 $1 {(which I saw, of course, as well)} Nxg5 34. Qg4 Nh3+ 35. Kh1
Qxg4 36. Bxg4 Nf4 37. Bxb6 f5 38. Bd1 $14 {would be a better option.}) 33...
Nxg5 $8 34. Bxg5 e4 $1 (34... Qxg5+ $4 35. Rg2 $18) 35. Rg2 exd3 36. Bf6 $1 (
36. Be7 Bxe7 37. Rxg6 hxg6 38. Qxd3 Bc5+ 39. Kg2 Rae8 $132) 36... gxf6 37. Qxd3
$14 Rae8 38. Rxf6 Bc5+ $1 39. Kh1 (39. Kf1 $4 Re1+ 40. Kxe1 Qxg2 $19) 39... Re3
40. Qd1 (40. Qd2 $5 Rfe8 41. Rf1) 40... Rfe8 $1 41. Rgxg6+ $1 {Good that the
time-trouble ended right before this move. Otherwise I might have gone for the
line} (41. Rf1 Qxg2+ $1 42. Kxg2 Re2+ 43. Kh1 Bd6 {
and the immediate draw is the most likely outcome, for instance} 44. Qd4 Rxh2+
45. Kg1 Ree2 (45... Bc5 $5 46. Qxc5 bxc5 47. Kxh2 $13) 46. Qg4+ Kf8 47. Qc8+
Kg7 48. Qg4+ $11) 41... hxg6 42. Rf1 {So, I gained an important tempo
comparing to the last variation but I also improved his pawn structure. Black
can probably hold this position but I still hoped for practical chances. And
my hopes weren't in vain.} R8e7 43. Qg4 Kg7 44. Qh4 f5 $6 ({
The day after Topalov suggested} 44... Kg8 $1 45. Qf6 Rd3 $44) 45. Rd1 $1 {
It's extremely important to take the d3 square from Black's rook. Now his king
is more exposed than before, so his chances are mainly in activity. White is
required a high level of precision in his calculations.} R3e4 (45... R7e4 $142
46. Qd8 f4 47. Qc7+ $1 $14 Kh6 $140 48. Qf7) 46. Qg3 Kf7 47. Qb8 $1 Re8 48.
Qc7+ R4e7 49. Qg3 (49. Qc6 $5 Rd8 $140 50. a3 $1 (50. d6 $2 Red7) 50... Rd6 51.
Qa4 $16) 49... Re3 50. Qh4 $1 R3e4 51. Qh7+ Kf6 52. Qc7 $1 $16 g5 (52... Re1+
53. Rxe1 Rxe1+ 54. Kg2 g5 55. Qc6+ $1 Kf7 (55... Ke7 56. Qg6 $1 g4 57. Kg3 $16)
56. d6 $16) 53. Qc6+ Kg7 54. d6 {Finally this pawn moves forward. If the
tricks don't work, the game should be over for Black.} g4 55. Rf1 $1 Rf4 (55...
Re1 56. Qd7+ $18) 56. Rg1 Bxg1 57. Qxe8 Bd4 58. Qe2 $1 {
In the second time-trouble I nearly overlooked} (58. Kg2 $2 Rf2+ 59. Kg3 Rf3+
60. Kh4 $4 (60. Kg2 $11) 60... Bf6+ 61. Kh5 Rh3#) 58... Re4 59. Qd2 Kf7 60. d7
Ke7 61. Qg5+ Kxd7 (61... Ke6 62. d8=N+ $1 $18 {looked amusing to me.}) 62.
Qxf5+ Re6 63. Qxg4 $18 {
The active pawns are finally taken and the rest is just technic.} Bc5 64. h4
Ke7 65. Qg7+ Ke8 66. h5 Bf8 67. Qb7 Rf6 68. Kg2 Be7 69. Kg3 Kf8 70. Kg4 Rh6 71.
Qa8+ Kf7 72. Qd5+ Kf8 73. Qd2 Rd6 74. Qe3 Kf7 75. c5 bxc5 76. Qxc5 1-0

