Bd7 10. Nge2 e6 11. h4 Qe7 12. Bh2 gxh4 $6 $146 (12... a6 13. g4 Nf6 14. f3
O-O-O 15. Kb1 Kb8 16. Bg1 Bc8 17. hxg5 hxg5 18. Rxh8 Rxh8 19. Ng3 d5 20. exd5
Nxd5 21. Nxd5 exd5 22. Qxe7 Nxe7 23. Be3 Nc6 24. c3 Bf6 25. Bd3 Rh3 26. Bf2 Be7
27. Rh1 Rxh1+ 28. Nxh1 $11 {1/2-1/2 Leko,P-Beliavsky,A/Ubeda 1997/CBM 58 (45)})
13. Bg1 O-O-O 14. g4 Nf6 15. f3 (15. Rxh4 $2 Nxe4) 15... Nh7 16. Bf2 e5 (16...
Bf6 $2 17. d5 exd5 18. Nxd5 Qe5 19. Nxf6 Nxf6 20. Bxh4 $16) 17. d5 Nd4 18. Nxd4
$1 exd4 19. Rxd4 {Topalov seems to attract various rook sacrifises on the d4
square in 99 ( although this time it's just an exchange as opposed to
Kasparov-Topalov/Wijk/99 where Kasparov sacked a whole rook on d4)} Bxd4 20.
Qxd4 b6 {Not quite black's dream but there's  nothing better} (20... c5 21.
dxc6 Bxc6 22. Qxa7 $40) 21. Nb5 $1 Kb7 (21... Bxb5 {
is unthinkable, the  white squares will become deadly.} 22. Bxb5) 22. Qc3 Rc8 (
22... Bc8 23. Nd4 Bd7 24. Qd3 $16) 23. Nd4 Qf6 (23... c5 24. dxc6+ Bxc6 25.
Nxc6 Qd7 (25... Rxc6 26. Qxh8) 26. Ba6+ Kxa6 27. Qa3+ Kb7 28. Qxa7+ Kxc6 29.
Qxb6#) 24. Qd3 Ka8 25. Bxh4 Qf4+ 26. Kb1 Nf8 (26... c5 27. dxc6 Bxc6 28. Nxc6
Rxc6 29. Qd5 $18) 27. Qc3 Ng6 (27... Kb8 28. Ba6 (28. Nc6+ $2 Bxc6 29. Qxc6
Qxf3 $19)) 28. Ba6 Nxh4 (28... Rb8 29. Qxc7 $18) 29. Bxc8 Rxc8 30. Rxh4 $18 {
Not only white has an extra pawn, he has also a positionally winning position.}
Kb7 31. a3 Rg8 32. Ne2 Qg5 33. Rh5 Qe7 34. Rxh6 f5 35. gxf5 Bxf5 36. Nd4 Bd7
37. Ne6 Bc8 38. f4 Rg4 39. Qc6+ Kb8 40. Rh8 1-0

