{An excellent game by Topalov against one of the most renowned experts of the
black side of the Ruy Lopez.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O
b5 6. Bb3 Bb7 7. d3 Be7 8. Nc3 d6 9. a4 Na5 10. Ba2 b4 11. Ne2 c5 (11... O-O
12. c3 bxc3 13. bxc3 d5 14. Nxe5 dxe4 15. d4 c5 16. Ng3 cxd4 17. cxd4 Bd5 18.
Nf5 Re8 19. Bg5 $36 {
1-0 Dvoirys,S-Polovodin,I/St. Petersburg 1998/CBM 67 ext (61)}) 12. Ng3 O-O (
12... Bc8 13. Nh4 O-O 14. Ngf5 (14. Nhf5) 14... Ne8 15. Bd5 Rb8 16. Nxe7+ Qxe7
17. Qh5 Be6 18. Nf5 Qd7 19. Bg5 f6 20. Bxe6+ Qxe6 $11 {
1-0 Jedryczka,K-Nurkiewicz,M/Czestochowa 1998/EXT 2000 (38)}) 13. Bd2 {
This is quite an important move in this line. The idea is to always be ready
for Bxa5 when Black tries b3.} Rb8 14. Nf5 Bc8 15. N3h4 Be6 16. Qf3 Ne8 17.
Nxe7+ (17. Bxe6 fxe6 18. Nxe7+ Qxe7 19. Qh3 Nc6 20. c3 bxc3 21. bxc3 Rb2 $11 {
1-0 Galdunts,S-Michalczak,T/Schwaebisch Gmuend 1995/CBM 45 ext (25)}) 17...
Qxe7 18. Nf5 Qd7 19. Qg4 Kh8 (19... b3 20. Bxa5 bxa2 21. b3 $16) 20. f4 $40 {
Topalovs handling of this position is a nice model for the White side in this
anti-arkhangel. Seemingly without effort he gets a strong attack on the K-side.
} Nc6 (20... g6 21. Bxe6 fxe6 22. Nh4 $16) 21. fxe5 Nxe5 22. Qg3 Bxa2 23. Rxa2
b3 {Black finally manages to get b3 in, but it turns out to be a hollow
victory, since White gets a new strong post for his B on c3.} 24. cxb3 Rxb3 25.
Bc3 $16 f6 26. Raa1 Nc7 27. d4 $1 cxd4 28. Nxd4 Rbb8 29. Nf5 g6 {Weakening ever
ything, but the N was difficult to stand on f5, attacking both d6 and g7.} 30.
Ne3 Rf7 31. Rad1 Qc6 32. h3 Re8 33. Qh4 Kg7 34. Kh1 Re6 35. Nd5 $1 Qxa4 36. Nf4
Re8 37. Rxd6 Qc4 38. Nh5+ $1 {
The brilliant point of the sequence leading up to this position.} gxh5 39.
Rfxf6 $18 Nb5 (39... Kg8 40. Bxe5 $18) 40. Qg5+ Kf8 41. Qh6+ Kg8 42. Bxe5 (42.
Bxe5 Rxe5 43. Rd8+ $18) 1-0

