dxe4 9. Nbd2 $146 {A surprising move - it certainly smells like preparation.} (
9. Nxe5 Nxe5 10. dxe5 Qxd1 11. Rxd1 Ng4 12. Bxe4 Nxf2 (12... Rb8 13. Bc6+ Ke7
14. Bg5+ Ke6 15. Bh4 Nxe5 16. Bd5+ Kf5 17. Nd2 Bb7 18. Ne4 Bb6 19. Ng3+ Kg6 20.
Bb3 f6 $13 {1-0 Shirov,A-Ivanchuk,V/Monte Carlo 1998/CBM 63 ext (57)}) 13. Bc6+
Ke7 14. Rd5 Bb6 15. Bxa8 Nd3+ (15... Be6 16. Rd4 $1 $18 {
1-0 Lutz,C-Onischuk,A/Germany 1996/GER-chT (44)}) 16. Kf1 Nxc1 17. Na3 Be6 18.
Rxc1 Rxa8 19. Rd3 Bf5 20. Rdd1 Bg4 21. Rd3 Bf5 22. Rdd1 Bg4 {
1/2-1/2 Mariano,N-Onischuk,A/Jakarta  1997/CBM 58 ext (22)}) (9. dxc5 Qxd1 10.
Bxd1 exf3 11. Bxf3 Bb7 12. b4 (12. a4 b4 $5 $132 {
1/2-1/2 De Firmian,N-Benjamin,J/Salt Lake City 1999/CBM 73/[Wedberg] (29)})
12... e4 (12... a5 13. Na3 $36) 13. Be2 O-O 14. a4 bxa4 15. Rd1 Ne5 16. Bf4
Rfe8 17. c4 Re7 18. Nc3 $14 {
1/2-1/2 Rowson,J-Benjamin,J/Edmondton 2000/EXT 2001 (54)}) 9... exf3 (9... exd4
10. Nxe4 $36) 10. Qxf3 Be7 11. Qxc6+ Bd7 12. Qf3 exd4 13. cxd4 O-O {
Black has defused White's opening initaitive.} 14. Ne4 Be6 15. Nxf6+ $6 (15.
Rd1 $5) 15... Bxf6 16. Be4 Bxd4 $1 {A beautiful exchange sacrifice. Black can
never be worse after this. His pressure against White's queen-side and the
strong B on d4 assures that.} (16... Rb8 17. d5 $36) 17. Rd1 (17. Bxa8 Qxa8 18.
Qxa8 Rxa8 19. Bf4 c5 $44) 17... c5 18. Bxa8 Qxa8 19. Be3 $5 (19. Qxa8 Rxa8 20.
Be3 Bxb2 21. Rab1 Bf6 $17) 19... Qxf3 20. gxf3 Bxb2 21. Bxc5 Rc8 {It's importan
t for Black to keep his R. With R and the pair of Bs he can play against the
white K.} 22. Rab1 h6 23. Bb4 (23. Rxb2 Rxc5 $15 {Black has an easier game.
White has to guard all his weaknesses, including the K.}) 23... Be5 24. a3 Rc6
25. Rbc1 Bc4 26. Rd8+ Kh7 27. Re1 Bc7 28. Rd7 (28. Rc8 $4 Bxh2+ $19) 28... Be6
29. Rd3 Bf5 30. Rd5 Bh3 31. Kh1 Rf6 32. Rd3 Be6 (32... Bb6 $6 33. Rd6 $1 Rxd6
34. Bxd6 Bxf2 35. Re8 {Should be OK for White. The R is the dominating piece.})
33. Bc3 Rf5 34. Rxe6 $1 (34. Rxe6 fxe6 35. Rd7 Be5 36. Bxe5 Rxe5 37. Ra7 $11)
1/2-1/2

