1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3
O-O 9. h3 Bb7 10. d4 Re8 11. Nbd2 Bf8 12. a4 h6 13. Bc2 exd4 14. cxd4 Nb4 15.
Bb1 c5 16. d5 Nd7 17. Ra3 f5 (17... c4 {
is the safest for Black, but it doesn't give many winning chances.}) 18. Nh2
Nf6 19. Rg3 Qe7 {This move gave Bacrot a nice victory last year.} 20. Nhf3 $1
$146 {More logical than Grischuks choice. Toplalov just builds his attack,
following the standard approach of not counting P:s with White in this line.} (
20. Rf3 Bxd5 21. Rxf5 Bf7 22. Ndf3 Be6 23. g4 Bxf5 24. gxf5 Qb7 $13 {
0-1 Grischuk,A-Bacrot,E/Enghien les Bains 2001/CBM 83/[Ftacnik] (56)}) 20...
fxe4 21. Nxe4 Bxd5 $5 {
Black needs the P to justify giving White such a nice attacking position.} 22.
Nxf6+ Qxf6 23. Bd2 $1 $40 {White is a P down, but he has a very nice game with
easy to find attacking moves in the pipeline. The most prominent threat is
Bxb4.} Bf7 $6 (23... Qxb2 $5 24. Bxb4 (24. Bxh6 $2 Bb3 $1) 24... Bxf3 25. Qd3
$5 {looks very strong, but it's not so easy to prove a win for White.} Rxe1+ (
25... Bh5 26. Rxe8 (26. Qh7+ Kf7 27. Qf5+ Kg8 28. Qh7+ $11) 26... Rxe8 27. Bc3
Qc1+ 28. Kh2 Qf4 $1 $13) 26. Bxe1 Bc6 27. Bc3 Qc1+ 28. Kh2 Qf4 29. Bxg7 Bxg7
30. Qh7+ Kf7 31. Qxg7+ Ke6 32. axb5 axb5 33. Bh7 $13) (23... Bxf3 24. Rxf3 Qxb2
$2 25. Bc3 $16) 24. Bc3 Rxe1+ 25. Qxe1 Qe6 26. Ne5 $1 {
An excellent attacking move simply threatening to win with Qe4.} Nd5 (26... d5
27. Rf3 Be8 (27... Ra7 28. Nxf7 Qxe1+ 29. Bxe1 Rxf7 30. Bh7+ $18) (27... d4 28.
Bxb4 cxb4 29. Qe4 $18) 28. Bh7+ $1 Kxh7 29. Rxf8 Bc6 30. Qb1+ g6 31. Nxg6 Qe4
32. Qxe4 dxe4 33. Rf6 $18) (26... dxe5 $2 27. Qe4 $18) 27. Qe4 $18 {
All white pieces are taking part in the onslaught. Black is defenceless.} Nf6
28. Qxa8 dxe5 29. axb5 axb5 30. Qb8 Qd6 31. Qxb5 1-0

