(8... Nc6 9. Nxg6 fxg6 10. Ne2 Qb6 (10... cxd4 {
- Grischuk-Ehlvest, FIDE-Wch k.o. 2000 CBM 81}) 11. Nf4 cxd4 12. Bd3 (12. Nxg6
{- Morozevich-Bareev, Bosna Super GM Sarajevo 2000 CBM 77}) 12... Nxe5 13. Nxg6
Nxg6 14. Bxg6+ Kd7 15. gxh5 Bb4+ $1 $17 {
- Zhang Pengxiang-Khalifman, CHN-RUS Summit Men 2001 CBM 85}) 9. Nxh5 (9. Bb5+
Nc6 10. Nxh5 cxd4 11. Qxd4 Nge7 {- 9.Nh5}) (9. g5 {
- Arizmendi Martinez-Piankov, Ciudad de Ubeda op 2000 CBM 75}) 9... Nc6 (9...
cxd4 {- Grischuk-Seirawan, FIDE GP Moscow rapid 2002 CBM 90}) 10. dxc5 (10. Bb5
cxd4 11. Qxd4 Nge7 12. Bh6 (12. Bg5 {All this looks extremely frightening for
Black, but White cannot make use of the pins.} a6 ({Even} 12... Bxc2 13. Rc1
Qd7 $1 {is possible according to GM Kallai.}) 13. Bxc6+ Nxc6 $1 14. Qa4 (14.
Qd2 Qc7 $15) (14. Qf4 Qc7 15. O-O Bg6 16. Rfe1 Bxh5 17. gxh5 Rxh5 $17 {
Holmsten-Hansen, Rilton Cup Stockholm 1998}) 14... b5 15. Qf4 Qc7 16. O-O (16.
O-O-O $2 b4 {- Ehlvest-Bareev, FIDE-ch k.o. 2001 CBM 86}) 16... Bg6 17. Ng3
Qxe5 {and White's psition is falling apart.} 18. Qd2 Bc5 $15 {
Orso-Kallai, ch-HUN k.o. Budapest 2000}) 12... Rg8 $1 {
Black needs good nerves playing this variation!} 13. O-O-O a6 14. Bxc6+ Nxc6
15. Qf4 (15. Qe3 Qa5) 15... Qa5 16. Qa4 $1 (16. Rhe1 {
allows the quick counterattack after} Nb4 $1 17. a3 Rc8 $1 18. axb4 Qa1+ 19.
Kd2 Qxb2 $19 {Chapman-Rogers, Australien Open 1999}) (16. Kb1 {
is also met by the same tactics:} Nb4 $1 17. Rc1 Rc8 18. a3 Nxc2 19. Rxc2 Rxc3
$1 $19 {A.David-Kallai, France 1999}) 16... Qxa4 17. Nxa4 gxh6 18. Nf6+ Ke7 19.
Nxh7 Nxe5 $5 (19... Rxg4 20. Nb6 Rd8 21. Nf6 Rf4 22. Ng8+ Ke8 23. Nf6+ $11 {
is a nice draw by perpetual checks.}) 20. g5 Ng4 {/\ Rh8 Kallai}) 10... Bxc5 $1
11. Bb5 (11. Bd3 $2 {is feeble due to} Bxd3 12. Qxd3 (12. cxd3 {McShane}) 12...
g6 $1 $15 {Nataf-N.P.Nielsen, North Sea Cup Esbjerg 2001 CBM 85}) (11. Nxg7+
Kf8 12. Nh5 Qb6 (12... d4 {McShane} 13. Na4 Be7 14. Bf4 b5 $1 15. Bxb5 Qd5 $1)
13. Rh2 Nxe5 14. f4 $13) (11. Bg2 {
- Grischuk-Bareev, FIDE GP Moscow rapid 2002 CBM 90}) 11... Qc7 (11... Qb6 12.
Bxc6+ (12. Qe2 a6 (12... Kf8 $2 13. Na4 $16) 13. Bxc6+ Qxc6 14. f3 Kf8 $13 {
and Black has some compensation for the P, his ^^ is very strong, and White's
P structure is weakened.}) 12... bxc6 (12... Qxc6 {- 11...Qc7}) 13. Qd2 (13.
Nxg7+ Kf8 14. Nh5 Bxf2+ $13) 13... Bf8 14. Ng3 $14) (11... Kf8 12. Bxc6 bxc6
13. Na4 Be7 (13... Be4 14. Rh3) 14. Be3 {with some blockading ideas on >< c5.}
Bg6 15. Nf4 Be4 16. f3 (16. Rh3 Qa5+ 17. c3 Rxh4 18. Rxh4 Bxh4 19. Nc5 $14)
16... Qa5+ 17. c3 Rxh4 18. Rxh4 Bxh4+ 19. Bf2 Bxf2+ 20. Kxf2 Bh7 21. b4 Qb5 22.
Nc5 $14 {and the strong blockading N has arrived.}) 12. Bxc6+ (12. Qe2 Kf8 $13)
12... Qxc6 (12... bxc6 {gives White time to consolidate his position.} 13. f4 (
13. Nxg7+ Kf8 14. Nh5 Qxe5+ 15. Kf1 $14) 13... Kf8 14. Ng3 $14) 13. Qf3 (13.
Qe2 $4 d4 $19) (13. Rh2 d4 14. Ne2 O-O-O $1 $13) 13... O-O-O {
Black puts his cards on the advance of his d P.} (13... Kf8 {
was also possible passively defending the P.} 14. Be3 $5 (14. Bd2 Bxc2 15. Rc1
Bh7) 14... Bb4 (14... d4 $6 {Now this push is out of order.} 15. Qxc6 bxc6 16.
Na4 Be4 17. Rh3 $16) 15. O-O Bxc3 16. bxc3 Bxc2 (16... Qxc3 17. Nxg7 Qc6 18.
Nh5) 17. Qf4 (17. Bc1 Ne7 $13) 17... Ne7 18. Qb4 a5 19. Qa3 Qc7 $13) 14. Nxg7 (
14. Bg5 $5 {is met by the aggressive} f6 $1 15. exf6 gxf6 16. Bxf6 $1 (16. Nxf6
Rf8 17. O-O-O Bb4 $13) 16... Rf8 (16... Nxf6 17. Nxf6 Bxc2 18. Rc1 Bg6 19. h5
Be8 20. g5) 17. g5 Bg6 18. Nf4 (18. Ng3 Nxf6 19. gxf6 Bd4 $17) 18... Nxf6 19.
Nxg6 Ne4 $1 $13) 14... d4 $5 ({Inserting} 14... Bb4 15. Rh3 {and then} d4 {
was the alternative.} 16. a3 (16. Qxc6+ bxc6 17. a3 Bf8 $1) 16... Bxc3+ (16...
Bf8 17. Qxf7 $1) 17. bxc3 Qc7 18. Bf4 (18. Qf4 d3 $1) (18. Bg5 d3 $13) 18... d3
$1 (18... Ne7 19. Rd1) 19. Rd1 dxc2 20. Rxd8+ Qxd8 $13) 15. Qxc6+ bxc6 16. Na4
(16. Bg5 $6 {is inferior because of} dxc3 17. Bxd8 cxb2 18. Rb1 Bd4 $1 $17)
16... Bf8 17. Nh5 Bxc2 18. b3 {Both white knights are on the edge of the board,
and the o^ on d4 is strong. However White has a very strong P majority on the
>>, which will be important in the _|_.} Rd5 19. Bf4 (19. f4 Be7 (19... Be4 20.
Rh3 Bg6 21. Nf6 $1 (21. Ng3 f6 $1 $132) 21... Nxf6 22. exf6 $16) 20. Bb2 Nh6
21. g5 Be4 22. Rh3 Nf5 23. Nf6 Bxf6 24. gxf6 $14) 19... Bb4+ 20. Ke2 (20. Kf1
d3 $13) 20... d3+ 21. Kf3 d2 22. Rad1 {
White has to neutralize the strong o^ at any cost.} (22. Ke2 Rd4) 22... Ne7 (
22... Bxd1+ 23. Rxd1 Be7 24. Kg3 $44) 23. Nf6 Rd3+ (23... Bxd1+ 24. Rxd1 $14)
24. Ke2 Nd5 (24... Ng6 25. Bg3 Bxd1+ 26. Rxd1 Rd4 27. h5 $16) 25. Bg5 (25. Bg3
Nxf6 26. exf6 Rd4 27. f3 Bxd1+ 28. Rxd1 $13) (25. Nxd5 Rxd5 (25... Bxd1+ $2 26.
Kxd3) 26. Rxd2 Bxd2 27. Bxd2 Rhd8 28. Bg5 (28. Be3 Bd1+) 28... Rxe5+ 29. Be3
Red5 $13) 25... Bxd1+ 26. Rxd1 Rh3 27. h5 Be7 $2 {This is the big mistake.} (
27... Nxf6 28. Bxf6 Rg8 29. f3 Rh2+ 30. Kd3 Rh3 31. Ke4 Rh2 32. Nb2 $14 {
was certainly better for White, but the text loses.}) 28. Rxd2 {
eliminating Black's only pride.} Bxf6 29. Bxf6 Nf4+ 30. Kd1 Rg8 31. Nc5 $1 $18
{and suddenly the black K is in clear and present danger.} (31. f3 Rxf3 32. h6
Rh3 33. g5 Nd5 34. Bg7 Rd8 $13) 31... Rxg4 32. Rd8+ Kc7 33. Rd7+ Kb6 (33... Kc8
34. Rxf7 $18) 34. Be7 $1 Nd5 35. Rb7+ Ka5 36. Rxa7+ Kb5 37. Rb7+ Nb6 38. a4+
Ka5 39. Kc2 1-0

