{Nowadays nobody can deny the importance of theoretical knowledge. The present
game is a prove that even on the highest level one must keep one's knowledge
and analysis up-to-date.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 a6 9. Na3 b5 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Nd5 Bg7 12. Bd3 Ne7
13. Nxe7 Qxe7 14. c4 f5 15. O-O O-O 16. Qf3 bxc4 17. Nxc4 d5 18. exd5 e4 19.
Qe3 Bb7 20. d6 Qf6 21. Bc2 f4 22. Qh3 Rac8 23. b3 Qg5 24. Rad1 f5 25. d7 Rcd8
26. Nd6 Ba8 $1 {For more information about the subtleties of the present line
look in CBM 89, game Morovic Fernandez-Nataf.} 27. f3 {Apparently Alexey
didn't know the above mentioned game (which, by the way, was played two months
before the present one) and as a consequence gets in trouble very quickly.} (
27. b4 {is the right move, although Black seems to have no particular problems
here, according to the following game:} Kh8 (27... Rxd7 {fails into} 28. Bb3+
Kh8 29. Nxe4 $1) 28. Bb3 e3 $1 29. fxe3 fxe3 30. Rxf5 Rxf5 31. Nxf5 e2 32. Re1
Bxg2 33. Qxg2 Qxf5 34. Qxe2 Qxd7 35. Qe4 Qd4+ {
with a soon draw, Kulaots-Yakovich, Bergen 2002.}) 27... Rxd7 28. fxe4 f3 $1 {
Nataf's brilliant idea.} 29. Qg3 {In fact only this move is a novelty and I
can hardly believe it was Shirov's home preparation, because Black is
obviously doing fine.  One must pay credit to Alexey Shirov, who in spite of
the "hole" in the opening preparation found the safest way and saved half a
point.} (29. Rxf3 Rxd6 $1 30. Rxd6 Qc1+) (29. Qxf3 Rxd6 30. Rxd6 fxe4 {
threatening ...Qc5+}) (29. Nxf5 Rxd1 {
was winning for Black in Morovic Fernandez-Nataf, Havana 2002.}) 29... Qe3+ 30.
Qf2 {Rightly realising the change of the situation, White is looking for
escape in endgame.} (30. Kh1 fxe4 $17) 30... Qxf2+ 31. Kxf2 fxg2 (31... fxe4 $5
) 32. Kxg2 Rfd8 33. Nc4 $1 {Takes important square d2 under control and allows
White to avoid the trade of his rook.} (33. Nxf5 Bxe4+ ({After} 33... Rxd1 {
White has the intermezzo} 34. Ne7+ $1) 34. Bxe4 Rxd1 $17) 33... Bxe4+ 34. Bxe4
Rxd1 35. Rxf5 Re1 {A pawn for the exchange and active pieces secure White a
draw.  Probably Black could still play on for a while without much risk. All
the more that Veselin might have made only 2-3 moves on the board on his own. 
In the end I would like to point out several things, some of them mentioned
above:  1. the modern opening theory can be very deep and one must accept it
no matter if one likes it or not;  2. the memory plays a higher role than, say
10-15 years ago. It is not enough to see variations, one must be able to
remember them and in critical moments to reproduce them;  3. Alexey Shirov
proved again to be an excellent player (did I say something new?). Even with a
careless opening preparation he succeeded to save half a point from an
inferior position against one of the toughest players in the world.} 1/2-1/2

