1. e4 {Ftacnik} c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7.
e5 Nd5 8. Ne4 Bb7 $5 {For the first time 8...Bb7 has entered in practice by
Leko in his game against Garry Kasparov in Linares 1999.} 9. Be2 ({
Is a possible continuation of the play:} 9. c4 {
See comments to Movsesian,S-Gavric,M/Neum,2002/CBM 90(1-0)(Golod,V)(32)}) 9...
c5 10. O-O Qc7 11. Nd6+ Bxd6 12. exd6 Qc6 13. f3 c4 14. Qd4 O-O 15. Bxc4 Rfc8 {
This move twice applied Grischuk in games against Garry Kasparov.} ({This posit
ion, with change of colours, already was met in a game by the same contender:} 
15... Qxd6 16. Rf2 Qb6 17. Qh4 Rac8 18. b3 Ne3 19. Bd3 Nf5 20. Qf4 Qd4 21. Qxd4
Nxd4 22. Be3 Nc6 23. Bc5 Rfe8 24. Bd6 $14 {Topalov,V-Leko,P/Dubai,2002(1-0)(64)
}) 16. b3 Qxd6 17. Rf2 ({Comments to:} 17. Bb2 {and also 20.c3 you cand find
in annotations to games: Kasparov,G-Grischuk,A/Cannes,2001/CBM 82(1/2-1/2)
(Golod,V)(48)}) 17... Qb6 18. Bb2 Qxd4 19. Bxd4 Nb4 {
Black wants to start to move the central pawns.} 20. c3 d5 ({
It deserves attention:} 20... Nc6 $5 21. Be3 d5 22. Bf1 Ne7 {+/=/=}) 21. Bf1 ({
Leads to minimal advantage of white:} 21. Bb5 Nc6 22. Bxc6 Rxc6 23. Re1 f6 24.
f4 Ba6 25. Rd2) 21... Nc6 22. Be3 Ne7 $6 $146 ({
From my point of view it is more logically at first:} 22... a5 23. a4 $140 {
(now for white it will be very difficult to advance the PP  on the queen side)
and only now:} Ne7 {You can see comments to Kasparov,G-Grischuk,A/Cannes,2001/
CBM 82(1/2-1/2)(Golod,V)(48)}) 23. Rc1 a5 (23... f6 $5) 24. Rfc2 e5 ({
Now senseless:} 24... a4 $6 {in view of:} 25. b4 {/\Bc5 and c4}) 25. c4 f6 {
'?!' Ftacnik.  Ftacnik: 'This solid defensive move is not good enough to
equalize for black against white's queenside pawn majority and bishop's pair.
Much more promising seems 25...d4!? with better chances to keep balance.'} ({
It was necessary to decide on a more risky continuation:} 25... d4 26. Bf2 {
but,keeping thus determined counterplay} Rd8 (26... f6 $13 {Ftacnik})) 26. cxd5
Rxc2 27. Rxc2 Nxd5 28. Bd2 $14 a4 (28... Nb4 {Ftacnik} 29. Rc5 Rd8 30. Be1 Nxa2
31. Bc4+ Kh8 32. Rc7 Bc8 33. Bxa5 $16) 29. bxa4 Rxa4 {
Now white pawn "a2" can become a determinative factor for a victory.} 30. Bb5
Ra8 ({Black can not keep the pawn in point "a2":} 30... Ra3 31. Bc4 {
/\Bc1 ,Bb3 and so on.} Ra8 32. Rb2 Ra4 33. Bb5 Ra3 34. Bd7 $16) 31. a4 Kf8 ({
Can be recommended:} 31... Ba6 32. Bc6 Rd8 $14) 32. a5 Ba6 ({After:} 32... Ke7
33. Bd3 {white begins pressure on weak king side of contender.}) 33. Ba4 (33.
Rc5 {Ftacnik} Bxb5 34. Rxb5 Nc7 35. Rc5 Ne6 $14) 33... Rb8 (33... Ke7 {Ftacnik}
34. Rc5 Bb7 35. Bc1 $14) 34. Kf2 Rb1 35. Rc1 Rb2 $5 {
Without a rooks black will be completely deprived a counterplay!} (35... Rxc1 {
Ftacnik} 36. Bxc1 Ke7 $14) 36. Rc2 {
Sometimes it is desirable to repeat  the moves.} Rb1 (36... Rxc2 $6 {Ftacnik}
37. Bxc2 g6 38. Be4 $16) 37. Kg3 Ne7 ({Weakly:} 37... g5 $2 38. Rc6 Bb7 39. Rd6
Ke7 40. Rd7+ Ke6 41. Rxh7 $16) ({and also} 37... Nf4 $2 38. Rc6 Bf1 39. Bc2 Ra1
40. Bxh7 $16) (37... Ke7 {Ftacnik} 38. Rc5 $16) 38. Bd7 Kf7 39. Rc7 Rb2 40. Bc3
Ra2 $6 ({Can it was necessary to decide on exchange of rooks:} 40... Nd5 $5 41.
Bxb2 Nxc7 $14) 41. Bh3 {'!' Ftacnik.  Ftacnik: 'Excellent move combining
defense of the g2 pawn with aggressive ideas of Bb4.'} Ra4 (41... h5 {Ftacnik}
42. Bb4 (42. Ra7 {Ftacnik} g5 43. Rxa6 f5 44. Bxf5 Nxf5+ 45. Kh3 Ra4 $14) 42...
h4+ 43. Kxh4 Ra4 44. Rxe7+ Kg6 45. Be6 Rxb4+ 46. g4 Ra4 47. Ra7 $1 Bd3 48. Kg3
Ra3 49. Bd5 $18) 42. Ra7 Bb5 43. Bf5 h5 44. h4 ({
Conducts to more concrete game:} 44. Bc2 h4+ 45. Kh3 Rf4 46. Bb3+ (46. Be4 $143
g5 47. Bb4 g4+ 48. fxg4 Rxe4 49. Bxe7 Be2 $16) 46... Ke8 (46... Bc4 $2 47. g3)
47. Be6 $16) 44... Kf8 ({Much worse is:} 44... Rc4 45. Bb2 Rf4 46. Be4 Ke6 47.
Rb7 $18) 45. Ra8+ Kf7 46. Bc2 $1 {Now rook is not kept in <->a.} Rf4 (46... Ra3
$2 47. Bb4 $18) 47. a6 $16 Bc6 48. Rd8 ({Also good enough:} 48. Rb8 $5 Nd5 49.
Ba5 Ne3 $140 50. Rb7+ $1 Ke6 51. Bb3+ Kf5 52. Rc7 Ba8 53. Rc8 $18) 48... Nf5+ {
'?' Ftacnik.} ({It was better:} 48... Rc4 $5 49. Bb3 Nf5+ 50. Kh3 Ke7 {
'!' Ftacnik.} 51. Bxc4 Kxd8 52. Ba5+ Kd7 53. Bb6 $16) 49. Bxf5 Rxf5 50. Rc8 $1
{An important intermediate move!} (50. a7 $143 e4 $1 51. Rc8 (51. f4 $6 Rd5) (
51. a8=Q $6 Bxa8 52. Rxa8 exf3 53. gxf3 g5 {+/=/+/-}) 51... exf3 52. Rxc6 f2
53. a8=Q f1=Q 54. Rc7+ Kg6 55. Qe8+ Kh7 56. Qe4 $16) 50... Bd5 51. a7 Rf4 ({
Now impossibly:} 51... e4 $2 {because of:} 52. Rc5 exf3 53. Rxd5 $18) 52. a8=Q
Bxa8 53. Rxa8 {+/-/+- The win of  white does not cause doubts.} Rc4 54. Bd2 {
Ftacnik: 'White's position is technically winning, but Leko plays cautiosly
not to spoil the deserved point.'} Kg6 (54... Rc7 {Ftacnik} 55. Be3 Rd7 56. Ra7
$18) 55. Ra7 Rd4 56. Be3 Rc4 57. Rb7 Rc3 58. Bd2 Rc2 59. Ba5 Ra2 60. Bd8 Ra8
61. Bb6 Rc8 62. Rc7 Rb8 63. Bc5 Re8 64. Kf2 Rh8 65. Ke3 {
The white king prepares for translation in camp of black.} Ra8 66. Kd3 Ra4 ({
Also there is no rescue,after:} 66... Ra5 67. Bf8 (67. g4 $143 hxg4 68. fxg4
Ra4 69. Bf8 Rxg4 70. Rxg7+ Kh5 71. Rh7+ Kg6 72. Rh6+ $16) 67... Ra8 68. Bxg7 $1
(68. Rxg7+ $143 Kh6 69. Rg3+ $1 (69. Rg8+ Kh7 70. Rg7+ Kh6 71. Rf7+ Kg6 $11)
69... Rxf8 70. Ke4 $16) 68... Rd8+ (68... Rg8 69. Ke4 Rxg7 70. Rxg7+ Kxg7 71.
Kf5 Kf7 72. g3 $1 Kg7 $140 73. g4 hxg4 74. Kxg4 $1 Kg6 75. h5+ Kh6 76. Kf5 $18)
69. Ke3 $1 Rg8 70. Ke4 Rxg7 (70... Ra8 71. Bxf6 Kxf6 72. Rc6+ Kg7 73. Kxe5 $18)
71. Rxg7+ Kxg7 72. Kf5 Kf7 73. g3 {-see 68...Rg8}) 67. g3 (67. Bf8 $143 Rxh4
68. Rxg7+ Kf5 $16) 67... Ra8 ({Also loses:} 67... Ra1 68. Ke4 Rc1 (68... Re1+
69. Kd5 Rf1 70. Ke6 Rxf3 71. Bf8) 69. Bd6 Rd1 70. Bf8 Rd8 71. Rxg7+ $1 (71.
Bxg7 $5 Rg8 $140 72. g4) 71... Kh6 72. Kf5 Rxf8 73. Rg6+ Kh7 74. Rxf6 Rg8 75.
Rf7+ Kh8 (75... Kh6 76. g4) 76. g4 e4 77. g5 $1 exf3 78. g6 Rg7 79. Rf8+ Rg8
80. Rf6 Re8 81. Kg5 $18) 68. Ke4 Rh8 69. Kd5 (69. f4 $1 $18 {Ftacnik}) 69...
Rd8+ 70. Ke6 {White has achieved the purpose! The rest is a matter of technics.
} Ra8 71. Bd6 Re8+ 72. Be7 Ra8 73. Rb7 Ra6+ 74. Bd6 Ra8 75. f4 $1 exf4 76. gxf4
Ra6 (76... Ra5 77. f5+ Kh7 78. Bf8 Re5+ 79. Kf7 Rd5 80. Re7 $1 $18 (80. Bxg7 $4
Rd7+ 81. Rxd7 $11)) 77. Rd7 Ra8 78. f5+ Kh7 79. Kf7 Ra4 80. Bf8 Rg4 81. Bxg7 $1
{Final chord. Good achievement of GM Peter Leko.} (81. Bxg7 Rxg7+ 82. Ke6 Rxd7
83. Kxd7 Kg8 84. Ke7 Kg7 85. Ke6) 1-0

