1. e4 {Ftacnik} c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7.
Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 gxf6 10. Nd5 f5 11. Bd3 Be6 12. O-O Bxd5 13. exd5 Ne7
14. c3 Bg7 15. Qh5 e4 16. Bc2 O-O 17. Rae1 Qc8 18. Kh1 Rb8 $1 {Lately Black
was facing problems in this line and Leko's novelty might change its
evaluation.  Black goes for a quick ...b4.} 19. g4 {Ftacnik: 'Topalov is brave
in his desire to refute Leko's successfull idea from his match game against
Shirov.'} (19. f3 {is another principled move, played by Shirov:} b4 20. Nb1
bxc3 21. bxc3 Bxc3 22. Nxc3 Qxc3 23. fxe4 f4 (23... Qxc2 24. exf5 $40) 24. Bb3
Ng6 {Usually if Black can achieve such a domination on the dark squares, he
has no opening problems, to say the least.} 25. Rc1 Qf6 26. Qf5 Qe7 27. Rc4 a5
28. h3 Rb4 29. Rxb4 axb4 30. Bd1 Ra8 31. Rf2 Qa7 32. Rc2 Kg7 33. Kh2 Qe3 $17 {
0-1 Shirov,A-Leko,P/Dortmund 2002 (47)}) 19... b4 20. cxb4 Nxd5 {I have no doub
ts both sides analyzed this position very well, Leko having the advantage of
doing it before the tournament though, in opposite to Topalov, who must have
analyzed it only after the game Shirov-Leko, played a few days before the
present game.} (20... Bxb2 $2 21. gxf5 Bxa3 $2 22. Rg1+ Kh8 23. Rxe4 $18 {
is a demonstration of White's potential. Black's main task is to defend
kingside, because usually he has enough possibilities to create counterplay on
the queenside later on.}) 21. gxf5 Kh8 22. Rg1 (22. Bxe4 Nf6 23. Qf3 Rxb4 24.
b3 Rxe4 $5 25. Rxe4 Nxe4 26. Qxe4 Qc5 27. b4 Qc3 28. Nb1 Qb2 $44) 22... Bxb2 {
White's problem is that he cannot open the diagonal b1-h7 for his bishop.} 23.
Qh6 (23. Bxe4 Nf6 24. Qh6 Nxe4 25. Rxe4 Qxf5 $15) 23... Qc3 $1 {White must
carefully, since at one moment Black might just take the piece on a3.} 24. Rxe4
Qf6 {Ftacnik: 'Black is applying the same sound strategy of domination on the
dark squares, white Na3 makes a sorry picture.'} 25. Qh3 Rg8 $1 26. Rf1 {
After this move is clear that Black won the theoretical battle. Topalov was in
a must-win situation and it influenced him from taking objective decisions.} (
26. Qb3 Rxg1+ 27. Kxg1 Bxa3 28. Qxd5 (28. Qxa3 Qa1+ 29. Kg2 Rg8+ 30. Kf3 Qh1+
31. Ke2 Rc8 32. Qb2+ Nc3+ 33. Kd2 Qxh2 {is just bad for White}) 28... Bxb4 {
with a high probability of draw was the logical outcome.}) 26... Bxa3 27. Qxa3
Rbc8 {Now Black is better in spite of being a pawn down. All his pieces are
active, while White has no co-ordination at all.} 28. Bd1 Nc3 29. Re3 d5 {
Black has a strong initiative.} 30. Rg3 d4 31. Bf3 d3 32. Qb2 Qd4 33. Rd1 $6 (
33. Qd2 $15) 33... Rxg3 34. hxg3 Rc4 {'!' Ftacnik.} 35. Rf1 d2 36. f6 $5 {
'?' Ftacnik.  An interesting practical chance, which almost worked out.} (36.
Qb3 {Ftacnik} Kg7 $1 37. a3 Ne4 $17) 36... Qxf6 (36... Ne4 {
is a simple win for Black:} 37. Qxd4 Rxd4 38. Kg2 Nc3 39. Bd1 Rxb4 $19 40. Kf3
Rb1 41. Ke3 Rxd1 42. Rxd1 Nxd1+ 43. Kxd2 Nxf2) 37. Kg2 Qd4 38. Qc2 {Now Topalov
is back in the game. As it often happens, the pawn on f5 only disturbed white
pieces from creating threats against black king.} Rc7 {'!' Ftacnik.} 39. Qf5 f6
40. Rh1 d1=Q 41. Bxd1 Nxd1 {Black won a piece, but amazingly White has good
chances to escape, since for the moment the knight on d1 is out of play and
black king needs permanent protection (weaknesses on h7 and f6, easy to attack)
.} 42. Rh4 Qd8 43. Rh6 Rf7 44. Qe6 Rf8 45. Qe4 (45. Qf5 Qe7 (45... Rf7 46. Qe6
Qf8 47. Rh4 $44) 46. Qd3 Qb7+ 47. f3 (47. Kh2 Nxf2 $19) (47. Kg1 Nb2 48. Qc2
$140 Rd8 $19) 47... Nb2 48. Qc2 Qg7 49. Rh1 Rg8 50. g4 f5 51. Qxf5 Nc4 52.
Rxh7+ Qxh7 53. Qf6+ {is an amazing drawish line.}) 45... Qd7 46. Qf3 Kg7 47.
Rh5 Nb2 (47... Rd8 $1 {Ftacnik} 48. Qe4 h6 $17) 48. Rd5 Qe6 49. Rd4 $1 Rc8 50.
Re4 Qc6 51. Kh2 Kf8 52. Qf4 {'!' Ftacnik.} Kf7 53. Qf5 Rg8 54. Qxh7+ Rg7 55.
Qh5+ Kf8 56. Qf5 $2 {Overestimating the position.  After a skillful play from
Topalov, who being a piece down succeeded to keep the knight out of play and
even win pawn h7, he finally collapses. Probably inspired by the last part of
the game, he decides to continue, missing that Black's extra piece will come
back and only Black has winning chances after that.} (56. Qh8+ Kf7 57. Qh5+ {
would have forced a draw.}) 56... Nc4 $17 {/-+} 57. Re2 (57. Re6 Rh7+ {
maybe being tired Veselin missed this move, which is the only one, but enough
for a win.} 58. Qxh7 Qxe6 $19) 57... Rg5 58. Qh7 Ne5 59. Qh6+ Kg8 {
The game is over. White cannot defend against Black's threats.} 60. Qxg5+ fxg5
61. Rxe5 Qf6 62. Re2 Qf3 63. Rd2 Kf7 64. a4 Qb3 65. Rd6 Qxa4 66. Rb6 Qa2 0-1

