{1/2-1/2 Sakaev,K-Timoshenko,G/Kherson 1991/CBM 21 ext/[Milov,V] (32)}) 5...
Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 {now the game is transposed into the Saemisch variation.} Ne8 {
Black avoids an unpleasant pin which could arise after Bc1-g5 and is preparing
for a possible Ne8-d6 attacking the c4-pawn in the future.} (6... d6 7. e4 e5
8. Bd3 c5 (8... Nc6 9. Be3 (9. Ne2 Ne8 10. O-O (10. g4 $6 Qh4+) (10. Be3 f5 $13
) (10. d5 Na5 11. g4 b6 12. Ng3 Ba6 $15) 10... f5 11. exf5 Bxf5 12. Bxf5 Rxf5
13. Rb1 Rb8 $11) 9... Re8 (9... Ne8 10. g4 $14) (9... b6 10. Ne2) 10. Ne2 b6
11. g4 Na5 12. Ng3 Ba6 13. Qe2 Nd7 14. h4 Nf8 15. Nf5 (15. f4 exf4 16. Bxf4 Qd7
17. O-O (17. a4 Qc6 18. d5 Qd7) 17... Qa4 18. Nf5 Bxc4 $13 {
1-0 Mikenas,V-Zinner,E/Brno 1931/EXT 99 (32)}) 15... Qd7 16. a4 $36 {/\17.h5})
9. Ne2 Nc6 10. O-O {
White is not in a hurry with d4-d5 and keeps the tension in the centre} (10. d5
$5 Ne7 (10... Na5 11. Ng3 b6 12. Bg5 h6 13. Be3 {
and the knight on a5 is out of play}) 11. g4 $36) 10... b6 (10... Ne8 11. Be3
b6 12. f4 {here, in comparison with the position with white pawn on d5 where
White mostly plays g2-g4, White can play f3-f4} Qe7 13. d5 Na5 14. Ng3 Kh8 15.
Ra2 g6 16. Raf2 f6 17. h4 Rg8 18. Qe2 Nb7 19. f5 Nd8 20. fxg6 Rxg6 21. Nf5 Bxf5
22. Rxf5 Nf7 23. Qf3 Nh6 24. Bxh6 Rxh6 25. h5 $16 {
1-0 Geller,E-Arlamowski,E/Szcawno Zdroj 1950/MCD (33)}) (10... cxd4 11. cxd4
Nxd4 (11... exd4 12. Bg5 $36) 12. Nxd4 Qb6 13. Be3 exd4 14. Bf2 $14 {
/\ 15.Be2 and 16.Bd4}) 11. Bg5 $1 Ba6 $2 (11... h6 {was obligatory} 12. Bh4 (
12. Be3 Ba6) 12... g5 $5 13. Bf2 Nh5 14. Re1 $14) 12. f4 $1 $16 {
now white initiative becomes very dangerous} cxd4 13. cxd4 exd4 (13... Nxd4 {
Milov,V;ChessBase} 14. Nxd4 exd4 15. e5 $18) 14. Ng3 {
1-0 Gligoric,S-Plater,K/Warsaw 1947/MCL/[Milov,V;ChessBase] (30)}) 7. e4 b6 8.
Bd3 (8. Nh3 $5 Ba6 9. Bg5 (9. e5 Nc6 10. Bg5 f6 11. exf6 Nxf6 12. Bd3 e5 13.
O-O h6 14. Bh4 exd4 15. cxd4 Nxd4 16. Be4 Ne6 (16... Nc6 17. Bd5+ Kh8 18. Nf4
$18) 17. Bxa8 Qxa8 18. Bxf6 Rxf6 19. Qxd7 Bxc4 20. Rfe1 Rf7 21. Qd2 c5 $14)
9... f6 10. Be3 (10. Bh4 Nc6 11. e5 Na5 12. Qa4 d6 13. Nf2 d5 14. cxd5 Bxf1 15.
Rxf1 Qxd5 $15 {0-1 Kantsler,B-Tiviakov,S/Frunze 1989/TD (32)}) 10... Nc6 11.
Bd3 Na5 12. c5 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 d5 14. cxd6 (14. O-O c6 15. Rfe1 Qd7 16. Re2 Nc7
17. a4 Rfe8 18. Rae1 b5 19. axb5 Nxb5 20. Bf2 Nc4 $11 {
0-1 Byrne,R-De Firmian,N/Philadelphia 1989/EXT 97 (44)}) 14... Nxd6 15. Nf4 Qd7
16. d5 exd5 17. Qxd5+ Qf7 18. Kf2 Qxd5 19. exd5 c6 $11 {
1/2-1/2 Volkov,S-Timoshenko,G/Tusnad 2000/EXT 2001 (33)}) 8... Ba6 9. Nh3 (9.
f4 $5 Nc6 10. a4 f5 11. e5 d5 12. Ba3 dxc4 13. Bc2 Rf7 14. Nf3 Qd5 15. O-O Bb7
16. Qe1 Na5 17. Qh4 $36 {1-0 Vladimirov,B-Ruban,E/USSR 1968/Inf 06 (31)}) 9...
Nc6 (9... c5 10. O-O Nc6 11. e5 $5 $14 (11. Be3 Na5 12. Qe2 Rc8 13. e5 cxd4 14.
Bg5 f6 15. Qe4 g6 16. exf6 Nxf6 $17 {1-0 Toth,B-Flesch,J/Budapest 1971/MCD (29)
})) 10. e5 Na5 {The plans for both sides are becoming clear: White has to try
to develop an initiative on the kingside, even if it`s going to cost the
c4-pawn, Black wants to try to win a pawn on c4 and to block white`s play on
the kingside.} 11. Qe2 f6 12. O-O $146 {This position isn`t research at all
and this simple move appears to be a novelty.} (12. Rb1 {
was played in the earlier game and certainly deserves attention:} d5 (12... c5
13. dxc5 bxc5 14. exf6 Nxf6 15. O-O $14) 13. Nf4 Qd7 14. cxd5 Bxd3 15. Qxd3
exd5 16. O-O $14 {1/2-1/2 Najdorf,M-Beni,A/Dubrovnik 1950/MCD/[Milov,V] (52)})
