1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 6. e3 c5 7. Bd2 Bxc3 8.
bxc3 {This move was popular in the 1930s ,but in the last years Evgenij Bareev,
already third time uses him.} (8. Bxc3 $5 {It's main line.See comments to
Stohl,I-Suba,M/Halkidiki,2002/CBM 92(1-0)(Golod,V)(54)}) 8... b6 $5 {
Besides,black has two principales moves:} (8... O-O 9. Nf3 b6 10. c4 Qh5 11.
Be2 Bb7 12. O-O Nbd7 13. Rfd1 Rfe8 14. Bc3 Qg6 15. Qxg6 hxg6 16. a4 $14 {
Bareev,E-Huzman,A/Panormo,2001(1/2-1/2)(54)}) ({and} 8... Nc6) 9. Nf3 Nbd7 ({
Also met in this tournament:} 9... Bb7 10. Be2 (10. Ne5 $6 Nbd7 11. Nxd7 Qxd7
12. f3 O-O 13. Be2 Rac8 14. Qb2 Rfd8 15. Rd1 Bc6 $11 {
Kjeldsen,J-Christensen,T/DEN,1996(1/2-1/2)(20)}) 10... Nbd7 11. O-O Rc8 12. c4
Qe4 (12... Qd6 $5) 13. Bd3 Qg4 14. d5 $1 exd5 15. cxd5 Bxd5 16. e4 $36 {
Bareev,E-Ivanchuk,V/Wijk aan Zee,2003(1-0)(34)}) 10. c4 Qd6 11. Be2 Bb7 12. Rd1
$146 ({A little prematurely:} 12. O-O {in view of:} Ng4 $1 (12... O-O $143 13.
Bc3 cxd4 14. Nxd4 Qe5 $6 (14... Rfd8 $5) 15. a4 Rac8 16. Nb5 Qb8 17. Rfd1 $14 {
Frydman,P-Regedzinski,T/Lodz,1938(1-0)(38)}) 13. g3 Ngf6 $11) 12... Rc8 {
I think,that it was better to unload a situation at the centre:} (12... cxd4
13. exd4 $140 Ne4 14. O-O (14. Be3 $143 Qb4+) 14... Nxd2 15. Rxd2 Rc8 $11) 13.
O-O Qc7 ({Now pretty dubiously:} 13... Ng4 {in view of:} 14. d5 exd5 15. cxd5
Qxd5 (15... Bxd5 $2 16. Bc3) 16. Bc3 Qh5 17. e4 $14) 14. dxc5 $5 {White want
receive a point "d4" for translation of the his knight on queen side.} Nxc5 15.
Nd4 O-O 16. f3 Rfd8 17. Be1 {/\Bg3 /^h2-b8 or Bh4/^h4-d8} ({Senselessly:} 17.
Nb5 {because of:} Qb8 18. Bc3 a6) 17... Qe7 18. Bh4 Bc6 ({
It deserves attention:} 18... e5 $5 19. Nf5 Qe6 20. Rxd8+ Rxd8 21. Rd1 Rd7 $11)
19. Nb5 ({Leads to equality:} 19. Nxc6 Rxc6 20. Rxd8+ Qxd8 21. Rd1 Rd6 22. Rxd6
Qxd6) 19... h6 20. Rxd8+ Rxd8 $11 21. e4 ({Pa7 is inviolable:} 21. Bxf6 $2 Qxf6
22. Nxa7 Ba4 23. Qc1 Ra8 24. Nb5 Bxb5 25. cxb5 Rxa2 $15) 21... Bxb5 {
Differently,after:} (21... e5 {
White can translate the knight on the following route:} 22. Nc3) 22. cxb5 e5
23. Rd1 Ne6 24. Rxd8+ Qxd8 25. Qc1 Qd6 26. Bf2 {
The weakness of a point "d4" is compensated by advantage BB.} Nd7 (26... Nd4
$143 27. Qc8+ Kh7 28. Bf1 Qa3 29. Qc4 $14) 27. Bc4 Nd4 28. h3 Nc5 29. Kh2 g5 {
Veselin Topalov places all pieces on black fields.} 30. Qa3 Qd7 31. Bg3 Qe7 32.
Qb4 h5 33. Kh1 Qf6 34. Qa3 Kg7 {The concrete game begins!} 35. Qxa7 h4 36. Bxe5
{Practically leads to a drawn game.} (36. Bh2 $143 Nxf3 37. Bxf7 (37. gxf3 $2
Qxf3+ 38. Kg1 Qe3+) 37... Nxh2 38. Bd5+ Kh6 39. Kxh2 Qf4+ $11) (36. Bf2 $2 Nxe4
37. Bxd4 Ng3+ 38. Kg1 exd4 $17) ({Can it was necessary to risk?} 36. Be1 Nxf3
37. gxf3 Qxf3+ 38. Kg1 Nxe4 (38... g4 $6 39. Qe7 $16) 39. Qxb6 Qxh3 40. Bf1
Qg4+ 41. Kh1 Qf4 $44) 36... Qxe5 37. Qxf7+ Kh6 38. Qf8+ Qg7 $8 (38... Kg6 $4
39. Bf7+ Kf6 (39... Kh7 40. Qg8+ Kh6 41. Qg6#) 40. Bg8+ Kg6 41. Qf7+ Kh6 42.
Qh7#) (38... Kh7 $4 39. Bg8+ Kh8 (39... Kg6 40. Qf7+ Kh6 41. Qh7#) 40. Bf7+ Kh7
41. Qg8+ Kh6 42. Qg6#) 39. Qd6+ Kh7 ({It was a very interestingly:} 39... Kh5
40. Qxb6 $140 Nxf3 41. e5 (41. gxf3 $2 Qa1+ 42. Kg2 Qb2+ $17) 41... Qh7 $1 42.
Bf7+ $8 (42. gxf3 $2 Qb1+ $17) 42... Qxf7 43. Qxc5 Nd2 44. Qc1 Qf2 45. b6 Nf1
46. b7 Ng3+ 47. Kh2 Nf1+ 48. Qxf1 Qxf1 49. b8=Q Qf4+ 50. Kg1 Qc1+ 51. Kf2 Qd2+
52. Kf3 Qd3+ $11) 40. Qxb6 (40. e5 $143 Nf5 41. Qxb6 Qxe5) 40... Nxf3 $1 (40...
Na4 $2 41. Qd6) 41. gxf3 Qa1+ 42. Kg2 Qb2+ 43. Kf1 Qc1+ 44. Kf2 {
After this move Veselin Topalov is agreed for draw, because of next variants:}
(44. Kf2 Qxc4 45. Qc7+ Kg6 46. Qc6+ Kf7 47. Qc7+ Ke6 48. Qc8+ (48. Qc6+ $2 Ke5
49. Qc7+ Kd4) 48... Ke7 (48... Ke5 $2 49. Qh8+ Kd6 $8 50. Qd8+ Nd7 (50... Ke6
$4 51. Qg8+) (50... Ke5 51. Qxg5+ Kd4 52. Qf6+ $16) 51. e5+ Kxe5 52. Qxd7 Qxa2+
53. Ke3 $14) 49. Qc7+ $11) 1/2-1/2

