1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6 4. Bxc6+ {Quite popular line, ten year ago} (4.
O-O Bd7 5. Re1 {was the main hit}) 4... bxc6 5. O-O Bg4 6. d3 Nf6 7. Bg5 (7. c3
e6 8. Bg5 Be7 9. Nbd2 O-O 10. Qa4 Bxf3 11. Nxf3 Qc7 12. Rfe1 Rfb8 13. Re2 e5
14. d4 exd4 15. cxd4 Rb4 16. Qa3 Rab8 $13 {
1/2-1/2 Rublevsky,S-Tiviakov,S/Russia (ch) 1996/ (39)}) (7. Nbd2 Nd7 8. h3 Bh5
9. c3 e6 10. Qa4 Qc7 11. Re1 Be7 12. d4 O-O 13. c4 Bf6 14. dxc5 Nxc5 15. Qa3 a5
16. e5 Be7 17. exd6 Bxd6 18. Qc3 Rfd8 $14 {
0-1 Skripchenko,A-Babula,V/Valle d'Aosta op 2002/ (27)}) 7... Nd7 $146 {
Deviating from the theory at very early stage} (7... e5 8. Nbd2 Be7 9. Nc4 O-O
10. Ne3 Be6 11. c3 h6 12. Bh4 g6 13. Qc2 g5 14. Bg3 Nh5 15. Rfd1 f6 16. d4 cxd4
17. cxd4 $14 {Maiko,J-Chistiakov,A/Kiev op 1998/1-0 (51)}) 8. Nbd2 f6 $5 {
Interesting and brave idea} 9. Bh4 (9. Be3 $5) 9... e5 10. Nc4 Be7 (10... h5 $5
11. h3 Be6 12. Bg3 g5 $132) 11. Ne3 Be6 12. c3 (12. Nf5 Bxf5 13. exf5 O-O $15)
12... Rb8 13. b3 d5 {Even from the first look it is easy to see that Black
solved all opening problems - he has couple of bishops and strong pawn center.}
14. Nd2 (14. Nf5 $5) 14... g6 {Taking f5 square under the control} 15. Bg3 (15.
Rc1 $5) 15... d4 16. Nc2 (16. Nec4 $5 dxc3 $140 17. Nb1) 16... g5 {
Topalov is getting more amd more space.} 17. f3 Nf8 18. Be1 Ng6 19. Nc4 Qd7 (
19... Nf4 $5) 20. Nb2 $5 {
Bringing knight on a4 and at least organizing some preassure on c5 pawn.} O-O
21. Na3 (21. Na4 $5) 21... f5 22. Nac4 g4 (22... f4 {also worth considering})
23. cxd4 cxd4 24. exf5 Rxf5 25. Bg3 (25. fxg4 $143 $6 Rxf1+ 26. Kxf1 Bxg4 $17)
25... Rbf8 26. Qe2 gxf3 27. Rxf3 Rxf3 28. gxf3 Bd5 29. Nd2 $1 {
Knight on e4 will be good defender.} (29. Nxe5 Nxe5 30. Bxe5 Bxf3 $36) 29...
Qf5 (29... Bg5 $5 30. Nbc4 Qf5 $36) 30. Nbc4 Bb4 31. Rf1 h5 $5 32. h4 $8 Kh7 (
32... Nf4 33. Bxf4 Qxf4 34. Ne4 Bxc4 35. bxc4 Qxh4 $15) 33. Ne4 Be7 34. Qh2 Nf4
(34... Bxc4 35. dxc4 $5) 35. Bxf4 exf4 (35... Qxf4 36. Qxf4 exf4 37. Rf2 $13)
36. Rf2 $1 a5 {Topalov played all game in very active style!} (36... Rg8+ 37.
Rg2) 37. Kf1 (37. Rg2 $5) 37... a4 38. bxa4 Bxc4 $2 {Terrible mistake!} ({After
} 38... Bxe4 $1 39. dxe4 (39. fxe4 Qg4) 39... Qe6 $19 {
Topalov will be very close to victory which he surely deserves.}) 39. dxc4 Qa5
40. Rb2 Qxa4 41. Qe2 Qa3 42. Rb7 (42. Rb7 Kh6 $1 43. Ng5 Bxg5 44. hxg5+ Kxg5
45. Qe5+ Rf5 46. Rg7+ Kh6 47. Rh7+ $1 $11) 1/2-1/2

