1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. bxa6 g6 6. Nc3 Bxa6 7. g3 d6 8. Bg2
Nbd7 9. Nf3 Bg7 10. Rb1 O-O 11. O-O Qa5 12. Bd2 Rfb8 13. Qc2 Ne8 14. Rfe1 {
White wants to make as many useful moves as possible before changing the
structure on the << and thus limits Black's <=>.} (14. a4 $5 Qc7 (14... c4 15.
Nb5 Qb6 16. Be3 Nc5 17. Qxc4 Bxb5 18. axb5 Qxb5 19. Qxb5 Rxb5 20. Nd4 Rb7 21.
b4 Na4 22. Rb3 $16 {Gustafsson,J-Szieberth,A/Budapest/2001/}) (14... Qb6 15. b3
Nc7 16. Rfd1 $14) 15. b3 Ra7 16. Rfe1 Nef6 17. h3 Rab7 18. e4 Ne8 19. Bf1 (19.
Na2 $5 $14 {/+/-,/\Bc3}) 19... Bxf1 20. Kxf1 Qc8 21. Kg2 c4 22. Nb5 cxb3 23.
Qxb3 Nc7 24. Qc2 Nxb5 25. Qxc8+ Rxc8 26. Rxb5 Rxb5 27. axb5 Rb8 28. Rb1 Nc5
$132 {Drasko,M-Cmiel,T/Porz/1991/}) (14. b3 Qa3 $142 $1 (14... Nc7 15. a4 Qb6
16. Rfd1 (16. Rfe1 {-14.Rfe1}) 16... Qa7 (16... Bb7 17. e4 Na6 18. Na2 Rc8 19.
Be3 Nb4 20. Nxb4 Qxb4 21. Bh3 Rd8 22. Bd2 Qb6 23. Be3 Qa5 24. Bd2 Qa7 25. Be3
Qa5 26. Bd2 Qa7 27. Bc3 Bxc3 28. Qxc3 Nf6 29. Qe3 $14 {
Shaidullina,S-Pogonina,N/RUS-chW Elista/2002/}) 17. e4 Rb6 18. Bg5 Re8 19. Na2
e6 20. Nc3 $6 (20. dxe6 $5 Nxe6 21. Be3 $16) 20... exd5 21. Nxd5 Nxd5 22. exd5
Re2 $44 {Gustafsson,J-Fogarasi,T/Budapest/2001/}) 15. Bc1 Qa5 16. Bb2 (16. Bd2
$11) 16... c4 17. Rfd1 Nc5 18. Ba1 Rb4 19. Nd2 cxb3 20. axb3 Nc7 21. Bf1 Bc8
22. e4 Qa7 $44 23. Na4 Nxa4 24. Bxg7 Kxg7 25. bxa4 Rxa4 26. Qc3+ Kg8 27. Rdc1
Ne8 28. Nc4 Ra2 29. Nb6 Rb8 $11 {Epishin,V-Krivoshey,S/Graz op/2001/}) 14...
Nc7 {/\Nb5} 15. a4 $1 $146 {
Doesn't allow Black to exchange the important Nc3, which cements the <<.} (15.
e4 Nb5 16. Nxb5 Qxb5 17. Bf1 (17. Bc3 Qd3 18. Rbc1 Bxc3 19. bxc3 Qxc2 20. Rxc2
Bc4 21. Ra1 Bd3 $15 {Varga,Z-Fogarasi,T/Budapest/2000/}) 17... Qb7 18. Bxa6
Qxa6 19. a3 Qa4 $44 20. b3 $6 Qxa3 21. Bc3 Bxc3 22. Qxc3 Qb4 23. Qe3 f6 $15 {
Krstev,R-Jacimovic,D/Skopje op/1998/}) 15... Qb6 16. b3 {
The pawn sacrifice is the point of the previous move.} (16. e4 $6 Qb3 $1 $44)
16... Bxc3 17. Bxc3 Nxd5 18. Ne5 $1 {
Connects strategy with tactics. White gets a better P-structure.} Nxe5 $8 {
Otherwise Black loses material, or heavily compromises his position.} (18...
N7f6 19. Nc4 (19. Bxd5 $16) 19... Qa7 20. Bxf6 $16) (18... dxe5 19. Bxd5 $16)
19. Bxd5 Bb7 {A difficult choice-give your opponent a permanent advantage, or
a dangerous attack?} (19... Nc6 20. Qe4 Bb7 21. Qf4 Nd8 22. a5 $40) 20. Bxb7
Rxb7 21. Bxe5 dxe5 22. Rec1 $14 {/+/-} f6 23. Qe4 (23. Qxc5 $2 Qxc5 24. Rxc5
Rxa4 $11) 23... Kg7 24. Rc3 Rab8 25. Qc2 Qe6 (25... Rc7 $2 26. b4 $18 {o^a,b})
26. a5 Kf7 (26... Rb5 $5 27. Rxc5 (27. Ra1 Qd6 28. a6 Ra8 $14) 27... Rxb3 28.
Rxb3 Qxb3 29. Qxb3 Rxb3 30. Rc7 $14 {/+/-}) 27. Ra1 Rxb3 28. Rxb3 Qxb3 29. Qxc5
Qb2 30. Qc4+ Kg7 31. Qa2 $5 {White decides to go for further simplification,
but even a major piece _|_ was promising.} (31. Ra2 Qd4 $16 (31... Qb1+ 32. Kg2
Qb7+ 33. f3 $16)) 31... Qxa2 32. Rxa2 $16 {White has transposed into an ideal
R_|_, he supports his o^ from behind. But despite this it's not easy to
demonstrate a forced win, Topalov continues to defend tenaciously.} Ra8 33. a6
Ra7 34. Kg2 Kf7 (34... e4 35. Kf1 Kf7 36. Ke1 (36. Ra4 $5) 36... Ke6 37. Kd2
$16) 35. Kf3 Ke6 36. g4 Kd6 (36... Kd5 37. h4 Kc6 38. Ke4 $16) 37. h4 h6 38. g5
({Even after} 38. h5 {Black retains drawing chances:} gxh5 $142 (38... g5 $6 {
loses time and keeps more vulnerable P on the board:} 39. Ke4 e6 40. Ra3 Kd7
41. Kd3 Kc6 42. Kc4 Kb6 43. e4 Kc6 (43... Rc7+ 44. Kb4 Ka7 45. Rf3 Rf7 46. Kc5
$18) 44. Rf3 Rf7 45. a7 Rxa7 (45... Kb7 46. Kc5 Kxa7 47. Kd6 $18) 46. Rxf6 Kd6
47. Rxh6 Rf7 48. Rg6 $18) 39. gxh5 e6 (39... f5 40. e4 e6 41. Ra5 $16 {/+-})
40. Ke4 Kc6 41. Ra3 (41. Kd3 Kb5 $1 $11) 41... Kb6 (41... Kd6 $5) 42. Rf3 Rf7
43. Rg3 Kxa6 44. Rg6 Kb5 45. Rxh6 Kc6 46. Rg6 Kd6 $14 {/=,/\f5}) 38... hxg5 39.
hxg5 f5 (39... Kc6 40. Ke4 Kb6 41. gxf6 exf6 42. Kd5 {/\Ke6+-}) 40. e4 (40. Ke3
e6 41. Ra5 Kc7 42. f3 Kb8 $14) 40... e6 41. Ra5 Kc7 42. Ke3 Kb8 43. Rxe5 {
This seems to be premature.} (43. f3 $5 {
keeps the tension, White's K strives to enter via c5, e.g.} f4+ (43... Kc7 44.
Kd3 Kb6 45. Rxe5 Rd7+ 46. Kc4 Rd6 47. Rb5+ Kxa6 48. Kc5 $1 Rd3 49. Rb6+ Ka7 50.
Rxe6 Rxf3 51. e5 $18 {o^e,g}) 44. Kd3 (44. Ke2 $5 $16) 44... Rd7+ (44... Kc7
45. Kc4 Kb6 46. Kb4 $22 $18) 45. Kc4 (45. Kc3 Rd6 46. Ra3 Rc6+ 47. Kb4 Ka7 48.
Kb5 Rc8 49. Rd3 Rd8 $5 50. Rc3 Rb8+ 51. Ka5 Rc8 $1 $14) 45... Rd4+ (45... Rd6
$6 46. Ra3 Ka7 47. Kc5 Rd1 48. Kc6 {/\Ra5} Rg1 49. Kd7 Rxg5 50. Kxe6 $18) 46.
Kc5 (46. Kc3 Rd6 {-45.Kc3}) 46... Rd3 47. Rb5+ Ka7 48. Rb7+ Kxa6 49. Rg7 Rxf3
50. Rxg6 $14 {/+/-}) 43... Rxa6 44. Rc5 (44. exf5 exf5 45. Re7 Kc8 46. Kf4 (46.
Rf7 Re6+ 47. Kf3 Kd8 $11) 46... Kd8 47. Rf7 Re6 48. Rf6 Ke7 49. Rxe6+ Kxe6 50.
Ke3 Kd5 51. Kd3 Ke5 52. Ke3 f4+ 53. Kd3 Kf5 54. f3 Kxg5 55. Ke4 $11) 44... Kb7
45. Kf4 Kb6 46. Rc8 fxe4 47. Kxe4 (47. Rg8 Kc6 48. Rxg6 Kd7 $5 $14 (48... Kd5
49. Rg8 $1 Ra2 50. Rd8+ Kc6 51. Kg3 Ra7 52. Kg4 Ra2 53. Rf8 $16)) 47... Kb7 48.
Rg8 (48. Rc3 Ra5 (48... Ra4+ 49. Ke5 Ra5+ 50. Kf6 Rf5+ 51. Kxg6 Rxf2 52. Re3
$18) 49. f4 Rb5 50. Rh3 Kc7 51. Rh6 Kd6 52. Rxg6 Rb4+ 53. Kf3 Ke7 {
leads only to the game position anyway.}) 48... Kc6 49. Rxg6 Kd6 50. f4 (50.
Rg7 Ra4+ 51. Ke3 e5 52. Rg6+ Ke7 $14) 50... Ra4+ 51. Kf3 Ke7 52. Rg7+ Kf8 53.
Rb7 Rc4 $2 {Only this can be identified as the losing mistake.} ({After} 53...
Ra1 $1 {Black's position is holding:} 54. Kg4 (54. g6 $2 Rg1) (54. Ke4 Re1+)
54... Rg1+ 55. Kh5 Rf1 56. Kh6 (56. Rb8+ Kg7 $11) (56. Rb4 Kg7 $11) 56... Rxf4
57. Rb8+ Ke7 58. g6 Rh4+ 59. Kg5 (59. Kg7 e5 $132) 59... Rh1 60. g7 Rg1+ 61.
Kh6 Rh1+ 62. Kg6 Rg1+ 63. Kh7 Rh1+ 64. Kg8 e5 65. Rb5 Rh5 66. Ra5 Ke8 $11 {
and because the Pe5 shields Black's K from frontal checks, White has no way to
extricate his K from g8.}) 54. g6 $1 $18 Rc1 (54... Rc5 55. Rf7+ {/\Kg4+-} (55.
Kg4 $143 Rf5)) 55. Kg4 Rc5 (55... Rg1+ 56. Kh5 Rg2 (56... Kg8 57. Re7 $18) 57.
Kh6 Rh2+ 58. Kg5 Rf2 59. f5 $1 (59. Rf7+ Ke8 (59... Kg8 60. Re7 $18) 60. Kh6
Rh2+ 61. Kg7 $18) 59... Rxf5+ (59... exf5 60. g7+ Kg8 61. Kf6 $18) 60. Kh6 Rf6
61. Kh7 $18) 56. Rf7+ Ke8 (56... Kg8 57. Rf6 Rc6 58. Kg5 $18 {/\,f5,Kh6,g7})
57. f5 $1 (57. f5 exf5+ 58. Rxf5 Rc1 (58... Rxf5 59. Kxf5 Ke7 60. Ke5 Ke8 61.
Ke6 Kf8 62. Kf6 $18) 59. Kg5 Rh1 (59... Ke7 60. g7 $18) 60. g7 Ke7 61. Kg6 Rg1+
62. Kh7 Rh1+ 63. Kg8 $18 {and White has reached a simple Lucena position.}) 1-0

