1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. g3 Qb6 6. Nb5 $5 (6. Nc2 e6 7.
Bg2 d5 8. O-O $5 dxc4 9. Nba3 $44) ({and} 6. Nb3 {are the usual moves, the
text is a very rare alternative. White manoeuvres his N to the natural square
c3-but this is where the Nb1 belongs! Therefore Black should be able to
equalize, but the practical material is still rather meagre.}) 6... a6 (6...
Ne5 $5 7. b3 a6 (7... d5 8. Be3 Qd8 9. Bf4 a6 10. Bxe5 axb5 11. cxd5 $36) 8.
N5c3 (8. Nd4 d5 $15) 8... Neg4 9. e3 Qc6 10. f3 Ne5 11. e4 $13) 7. N5c3 (7. Qa4
$6 Rb8 $6 (7... Ne5 $36 {Nc4,Qc6}) (7... Ng4 $5) 8. N5c3 e6 9. Bg2 Bc5 10. O-O
O-O 11. Nd2 d6 (11... Qc7 $142) 12. Nde4 Nxe4 13. Nxe4 Qb4 14. Nxc5 dxc5 15.
Qxb4 cxb4 16. Rd1 e5 17. Be3 Be6 18. Bd5 Rfd8 19. Bb6 Re8 20. Rac1 $16 {
Cleven,M-Fuchs,A/Krefeld/2001/}) (7. Be3 Qa5+ 8. N5c3 (8. Bd2 Qb6 $1 (8... Qd8
9. N5c3 e6 (9... d5 10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. Bg2 $14) (9... b6 $5 $132) 10. Bg2 Be7
11. e4 O-O 12. O-O Qc7 13. Be3 d6 14. f4 Rb8 15. Qe2 Bd7 16. Nd2 Rfc8 17. Rac1
$14 {Andreeva,N-Ovod,E/Moscow/1999/}) 9. Be3 Qa5+ $11) 8... Ng4 9. Qd2 e6 10.
Bg2 Nxe3 11. Qxe3 Bc5 12. Qd2 b5 13. Ne4 Qxd2+ 14. Nbxd2 Bd4 15. O-O-O f5 16.
e3 fxe4 17. exd4 d5 {Miles,A-Schmittdiel,E/Ostend/1993/} 18. cxd5 exd5 19. f3
O-O $1 $11) 7... g6 $146 {Karjakin lets White finish his >> development
undisturbed and goes for a Maroczy-like position.} (7... e6 8. Bg2 Ne5 9. Qb3 (
9. b3 {is a more logical move, with chances for an opening advantage.}) 9...
Qb4 10. Nd2 Rb8 11. O-O Be7 12. Qc2 O-O 13. a3 Qc5 14. Rd1 Qc7 15. b3 b5 16.
cxb5 axb5 17. Bb2 Bb7 18. Bxb7 Rxb7 $11 {Miles,A-Gligoric,S/Bugojno/1984/}) 8.
Bg2 d6 9. O-O Bg7 10. b3 (10. Nd5 Nxd5 11. cxd5 Ne5 $11 {
releases the tension and favours Black.}) 10... O-O 11. Bb2 Qa5 12. Nd2 (12. e4
Rb8 {/\b5<=>}) 12... Qh5 $5 (12... Bd7 13. h3 b5 14. a3 $5 {/\b4+/=}) 13. e4 (
13. Re1 Bh3 14. Bh1 Ng4 $132) 13... Qxd1 {
Black's move is logical, but also playable was} (13... Bg4 14. f3 Bh3 15. Bxh3
Qxh3 16. Rb1 Nd7 17. Nd5 e6 $13) 14. Rfxd1 Nd7 15. Rab1 Nc5 16. Nd5 Be6 17.
Bxg7 (17. b4 Nd7 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. f4 a5 $132) 17... Kxg7 18. Nf1 b5 {
Natural <=>, although it softens Black's <<.} (18... a5 19. Nfe3 $14) 19. b4 $1
(19. Nfe3 b4 $11) 19... Nd7 $6 {A passive follow-up.} (19... Na4 $142 20. Nfe3
Ne5 $132 {/\} (20... Bxd5 21. cxd5 Ne5 22. f4 Nc4 23. Nxc4 bxc4 24. Rdc1 $14)
21. Nc7 $6 Nc3 $36) 20. Nfe3 bxc4 $6 (20... Nde5 $142 21. c5 $5 $14) 21. Nxc4
Rab8 22. a3 Rfc8 23. Nce3 Nb6 24. Bf1 $1 $36 {><a6} Bxd5 25. exd5 (25. Nxd5 $5
$16) 25... Ne5 26. Rbc1 $5 {Topalov has outplayed his opponent and doesn't
want to squander any of his advantage by giving Black activity. Especially in
a rapid game this seems a sensible decision.} (26. Bxa6 Rc3 27. Ra1 Ra8 28. b5
Nd3 $14 {<=>}) 26... Rxc1 27. Rxc1 Ra8 28. Rc7 Kf8 {For the time being Black
has defended his ><a6 and it's becoming clear White can't win the endgame on
the << alone. Therefore he must open a second front and create another
wekaness or target on the >>. Topalov realizes this plan in a model way from
move 37 onwards.} 29. Rb7 (29. Kg2 $36 {would have saved tempi.}) (29. f4 $5
$16) 29... Na4 30. Kg2 $6 (30. f4 Nf3+ 31. Kg2 Nd4 $14) 30... Ke8 31. f4 Nd7 {
/\Kd8-c8} 32. Rc7 Kd8 33. Rc2 a5 $5 {Black wisely decides he can't defend the
><a6 forever. Although now the passed o^b5 will be seemingly firmly blockaded,
it nevertheless requires attention and enables White to concentrate his forces
on the opposite flank (the 2 weaknesses principle).} 34. b5 Nab6 35. Kf2 (35.
Kf3 Nf6 $132) 35... Nc5 36. Kf3 Kc7 (36... h5 $142 $5 37. h3 Kc7 38. g4 hxg4+
39. hxg4 Rh8 {and Black is close to equality.}) 37. g4 $1 $36 {
/\g5,h4-h5->,()>>} e6 38. dxe6 fxe6 39. Bg2 Rf8 40. Kg3 Kd7 ({
Black finds it difficult to activate his [+] pawns, e.g.,} 40... Nbd7 41. h4 d5
42. f5 $1 $36) 41. h4 (41. Bf3 {was perhaps somewhat more accurate.}) 41... Rg8
(41... Rc8 42. Bc6+ (42. Bf3 $5) 42... Kc7 (42... Ke7 43. Re2 $14) 43. Rh2 {
/\h5+/=}) (41... h5 $5 {/\} 42. gxh5 gxh5 43. Bf3 Rg8+ 44. Kh2 Rf8 $132) 42.
Bf3 (42. g5 $5 $36) 42... Rg7 $2 (42... h5 $142 $132) 43. g5 $1 Rf7 44. h5 Ke7
45. hxg6 hxg6 46. Nc4 $1 {Again the principle of 2 weaknesses-once Black's K
has moved in the direction of the >>, possibly to protect the ><g6, White
shifts his sights to the long dormant o^b5.} Nxc4 $8 47. Rxc4 Kd7 $6 (47... Rf8
$142 48. Rc2 (48. Be4 $5 Nxe4+ 49. Rxe4 Rb8 50. a4 Rc8 $132) 48... Rh8 49. Rb2
$36) 48. Rc2 Rh7 49. Bc6+ Kc7 (49... Ke7 50. b6 Rh8 51. Rh2 $5 Rxh2 52. Kxh2
Kd8 53. Kg3 $16) 50. Be8 $1 {
Now g6 is again a target, this time it can;t be defended anymore.} Rg7 (50...
Rh1 51. Bxg6 Ra1 52. Rc3 (52. Bf7 Rxa3+ 53. Kg4 $16) 52... Kb6 53. Kg2 $1 {
o^g5,/\Rg3,Bh7+-}) 51. Rh2 Rg8 52. Rh7+ Kb6 53. Bf7 $18 Rb8 54. Bxg6 Kxb5 55.
Bf7 Ka4 56. g6 Ne4+ 57. Kf3 Nf6 58. Bxe6 $1 d5 (58... Nxh7 59. gxh7 {/\Bg8} Rh8
$8 60. Bg8 Kb5 61. f5 Kc6 62. f6 Kd7 63. Ke4 Ke8 64. Kd5 Kd7 65. a4 $22 $18) (
58... Kxa3 59. Rf7 Nh5 60. Kg4 $18) 59. Rf7 Rb3+ 60. Ke2 Ne4 61. g7 Rg3 62.
Bxd5 Nc3+ (62... Nd6 63. Ra7 $18) 63. Kf2 Rxg7 64. Rxg7 (64. Bc6+ $142 Kxa3 65.
Rxg7) 64... Nxd5 65. Kf3 Kxa3 66. Rg5 Nxf4 67. Kxf4 a4 (67... Kb4 68. Ke3 a4
69. Kd2 $18) 68. Ke3 (68. Rb5 Ka2 69. Ke3 $18) 68... Kb2 69. Kd2 a3 70. Rb5+
Ka1 71. Kc3 Ka2 (71... a2 72. Kb3 Kb1 73. Ka3+ Ka1 74. Rg5 $18) 72. Rb3 1-0

