1. c4 Nf6 2. d4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Na6 8. Re1
Qe8 ({Of course black has other possibilities in this position:} 8... exd4) ({
and} 8... c6) 9. Bf1 Bg4 10. d5 Nb4 {With typical idea in 8 Re1 -line to take
on f3 and white cannot take with queen because of Nc2.} 11. Be2 ({
Still very interesting:} 11. a3 Bxf3 12. gxf3 Na6 13. b4 {
with double-edged play}) 11... a5 12. h3 (12. Be3 Na6 13. a3 (13. Nd2 $5) 13...
Bd7 14. Nd2 h5 (14... a4 $142) 15. h3 Nh7 16. b4 $5 (16. b3 $5) 16... axb4 17.
axb4 Nxb4 18. Qb3 c5 19. dxc6 Nxc6 20. Qxb7 $14 {
1-0 Fridman,D-Papa,S/Bad Wiessee GER 2003/The Week in Chess 471 (35)}) 12...
Bd7 13. Nh2 {Preventing black's typical idea Nh5 with next Nf4,or f5.} Kh8 14.
Be3 $146 (14. Nf1 Ng8 15. Ng3 Na6 (15... f5 $140 16. exf5 gxf5 17. Nh5 Bh6 18.
f4 $14) 16. Rb1 Nc5 17. Qc2 Qe7 $13 {0-1 Rezan,S-Stevic,H/Pula 2000/CBM 75 (42)
}) 14... Na6 (14... Ng8 {Allows white to play} 15. c5 f5 16. a3 Na6 17. cxd6
cxd6 18. Qb3 {
getting some targets on the queenside,though the position remains unclear}) 15.
b3 Ng8 16. Qd2 Nc5 {First black improves the position of his knight.} 17. Kh1 {
White prepares himself to meet f5-advance with ef-gf and f4 and starts to
regroup his piecies on the kingnside.} b6 {
The last useful move before f7-f5 -advance.} 18. Rf1 f5 19. exf5 gxf5 20. f4
Nf6 (20... e4 {strategically not so good decision,as now white has a very
clear plan:to transfer his knight to e3,putting bishop on d4 and to provoke
g2-g4 advance,for example:} 21. Bd4 Nf6 22. Rg1 Qg6 23. Nf1 {
and white has much better prospects}) 21. Bf3 Nh5 ({Not so good:} 21... e4 22.
Be2 Nh5 23. Qe1 $1 Qg6 24. g4 $1 $36) (21... Nfe4 $6 22. Bxe4 Nxe4 23. Nxe4
fxe4 24. Rae1 Qg6 25. fxe5 Bxe5 26. Bd4 $14) (21... Rd8 $142 {
with next Nh5 deserved serious attention}) 22. Bxh5 Qxh5 23. fxe5 dxe5 (23...
Bxe5 $2 24. Bd4 $16) 24. d6 $1 {Otherwise white is simply worse} cxd6 (24... c6
$2 25. Bxc5 bxc5 26. Na4 $16) 25. Qxd6 ({
A very serious alternative to the text was:} 25. Bxc5 bxc5 26. Qxd6 {
winning the pawn,but after correct} Bc8 $1 (26... Rad8 $143 27. Qxc5 e4 28.
Rad1 $1 Bxc3 $140 29. Rxd7 $16) (26... Rfd8 $143 27. Rad1 (27. Qxc5) 27... e4
28. Nd5 $16) 27. Qxc5 Bb7 28. Nd5 a4 {
black has some compensation with two bishops}) 25... Rf6 26. Qd1 (26. Qxe5 $140
$2 Rg6 27. Qd5 Bc6 $19) (26. Qd2 Bc6 27. Bxc5 (27. Nd5 $2 Ne4 $1 28. Nxf6 Bxf6
$40) 27... bxc5 28. Nd5 Rd6 $11) 26... Qf7 $6 ({
A very clear way for the equality was:} 26... Qxd1 $142 27. Raxd1 Bc6 28. Nf3 (
28. Nd5 Bxd5 29. Rxd5 Ne4 30. Re1 Re8 $11) 28... Re8 29. Nd5 Bxd5 30. Rxd5 Ne4
31. Re1 Rfe6 32. Ng5 (32. Rb5 $143 f4 $1 33. Bg1 Ng3+ 34. Kh2 e4 35. Rxb6 e3
$17) 32... Nxg5 33. Bxg5 Bf8 $11) 27. Nd5 Rg6 28. Qc2 $1 {
Very good positional move,which prevents both Bc6 and Ne4.} (28. Nxb6 Rxb6 29.
Bxc5 Rg6 30. Qd5 Qe8 $44) 28... f4 $1 (28... Rc8 $143 29. Rad1 f4 30. Bxc5 Rxc5
31. Nf3 Bc6 32. Nc3 $1 {winning a battle for the important e4-square}) 29. Bxc5
(29. Nxb6 $2 Bf5 30. Qd1 Qb7 31. Qd5 Qxd5 32. Nxd5 Be4 $19) 29... bxc5 30. Rae1
Bf5 (30... Bc6 $143 31. Nf3 Bxd5 32. cxd5 Qxd5 33. Re4 $44 {and despite extra
pawn black should defend clearly inferior position,due to the difference
between black's dark bishop and white's knight.}) 31. Qe2 (31. Qd2 Re6 32. Nf3
h6 $1 $13) 31... Rg8 (31... Rg3 $143 $6 32. Rf3 $1 Rg5 33. Rf2 $1 Rg3 34. Nf1
$16) 32. Nf3 {
allows black to create a serious counterplay against white's king.} (32. Qh5
Be6 $1 {the only continuation,which keeps balance} (32... Bd3 33. Rf3 $1) (
32... Qd7 $140 33. Ne7 $1 Qxe7 34. Qxf5 $16) 33. Nf3 (33. Rxe5 $143 Bxe5 34.
Qxe5+ Qg7 35. Qxg7+ R6xg7 36. Nxf4 Bf5 $13) 33... Bxd5 34. cxd5 Qxd5 35. Ng5
Bh6 36. Rxe5 (36. Nf3 Bg7 $11) 36... Qd7 $1 $11 (36... Qd3 37. Nf7+ Kg7 38.
Rfe1 $36)) 32... e4 33. Nh4 f3 $1 {
Opening up the position around white's monarch.} 34. Nxf3 $4 ({After the best:
} 34. Nxg6+ $142 {
the game could have finished draw after a brilliant variation:} Qxg6 35. gxf3
Bxh3 36. Nf4 (36. Rg1 $2 Qh5) 36... Qh6 37. Nxh3 Be5 $3 38. f4 Rg3 $1 39. Rf2
$8 e3 40. Rg1 (40. Rg2 Rxh3+ 41. Rh2 Bc3 $3 {and e3-pawn decides}) 40... Rxh3+
(40... Rxg1+ 41. Kxg1 exf2+ 42. Kxf2 $11) 41. Rh2 Rxh2+ 42. Qxh2 Qc6+ 43. Rg2
Qf3 44. fxe5 Qd1+ {with perpetual}) 34... exf3 35. Qxf3 Rg5 $4 {
