1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. g3 b6 4. Bg2 Bb7 5. O-O g6 6. d4 cxd4 7. Qxd4 Bg7 8. Nc3
d6 9. Rd1 Nbd7 10. Be3 a6 11. Rac1 Rb8 $5 {
A playable alternative to the more usual and satisfactory main line} (11... Rc8
12. b3 O-O 13. Qh4 Rc7 $5 $11) 12. b3 O-O 13. Qh4 b5 $6 {Black in fact plays
11...Rb8!? to get in this advance in due time, but at this moment it's
premature and loses a P.} ({Better is the patient} 13... Re8 $142 {Black keeps
the b5-advance in reserve after White will not be able to directly attack the
Pb5.} {Possibly somewhat stronger is} 14. Ne1 $5 (14. Bh6 b5 (14... Bh8 $5 15.
Bh3 b5 16. cxb5 axb5 17. Qb4 Bxf3 18. exf3 Ne5 19. Bg2 Nc6 20. Qh4 Qa5 21. Bd2
Qa6 22. Bf1 Ne5 23. Qf4 Qa8 24. Be2 Rec8 25. Kg2 Bg7 26. Qe3 Rc5 27. Kg1 Rbc8
28. h3 b4 $36 {Topalov,V-Gelfand,B/Monte Carlo act/2001/}) 15. Bxg7 $142 (15.
Ng5 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Bxh6 (16... Qb6 17. Nd5 Qb7 18. e4 Rbc8 $132 19. cxb5 axb5
20. Rxc8 $6 Qxc8 21. Rd3 Qb7 22. Rf3 Bh8 $15 23. g4 $4 Nxe4 24. Nxe7+ Rxe7 25.
Nxf7 Bf6 26. Nd8 Qa8 {0-1,Gurevich,D-Milov,V/New York op/1998/}) 17. Qxh6 bxc4
18. Rd4 cxb3 19. Rh4 Nf8 20. Nce4 b2 21. Nxf6+ exf6 22. Nxh7 {
Vassallo Barroche,M-Estremera Panos,S/ESP-chT Lanzarote/2003/} Rb4 $1 {/\} 23.
Rh3 bxc1=Q 24. Ng5 Qa8+ $19) 15... Kxg7 16. cxb5 axb5 17. Qb4 $14 (17. Nd4 $6
b4 18. Bxb7 Rxb7 19. Nc6 Qb6 $36)) 14... Bxg2 15. Nxg2 Qc7 16. Nf4 Qb7 17. Nfd5
Rbc8 18. Bg5 {Notice we have achieved the position from the game
Illescas-Gelfand, but it's Black's move instead of White's!;Illescas Cordoba,M
(2600)-Gelfand,B (2713)/Ciudad de Pamplona 1999 (3)/1/2-1/2} (18. a4 $142 $5)
18... b5 $1 19. cxb5 axb5 20. Nxf6+ Nxf6 21. Bxf6 $6 {
1/2,Tadic,B-Marinkovic,S/Herceg Novi/2001/} (21. Qb4 Rc5 22. Be3 Nd5 $11) 21...
Bxf6 $15) 14. cxb5 axb5 {><b5} 15. Nd4 $6 {Now Black could have retained his
><b5. Topalov had already in his practice applied a plan of gradual pressure
against the b5-P in;Topalov,V (2690)-Psakhis,L (2581)/FIDE-Wch k.o. 1999 (3.1)/
1-0} ({but better was to win it outright with} 15. Qb4 $142 $1 {
although Black still retained some chances to complicate matters after} Re8 (
15... Bc6 16. Nd4 $14) 16. Ne1 h5 17. Nxb5 Bxg2 18. Nxg2 d5 19. a4 e5 20. Qd6
d4 21. Bg5 Re6 22. Qc7 Qe8 23. Qc2 Reb6 $14 {
/+/-,Jackelen,T-Epishin,V/Bundesliga 0203/2003/}) 15... b4 $2 {
Such things happen in rapid chess-now Black loses his b-P after all.} (15...
Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Qb6 (16... Qa5 $5 17. Nc6 Qa8 18. Nd5 Nxd5 19. Rxd5 Rfe8 $13) 17.
Kg1 (17. Ndxb5 $6 Qc6+ 18. Kg1 Rxb5 19. Qa4 Rb6 20. Qxc6 Rxc6 21. Nd5 Nxd5 22.
Rxc6 Ne5 $17) 17... Qa6 $132) 16. Bxb7 Rxb7 (16... bxc3 $2 17. Nc6 $18) 17. Nc6
Qe8 (17... Qa8 18. Nxe7+ (18. Nxb4 $5 $16) 18... Kh8 19. Na4 $5 $16 (19. Ncd5
$5 Qxa2 20. Qc4 Ne5 $14)) 18. Nxb4 Qa8 (18... Ne5 19. Nbd5 $16) 19. Nc6 Nb8 (
19... Re8 20. Qa4 $16 (20. b4 $5 Nb8 21. Na5 $16)) 20. Nxb8 Rfxb8 {
Now White forces the Q off the board and achieves a technically won _|_.} (
20... Qxb8 $142 21. Bd4 $16) 21. Qa4 $16 {/+- White's o^ on the << will decide
the game in the long run. In the end Topalov finishes Black off elegantly.} h5
22. f3 {White has time, so he first stops Ng4.} Nd7 23. Qxa8 Rxa8 24. Na4 $1 (
24. Bd4 $143 $2 Bxd4+ 25. Rxd4 Rc7 {and the pin on the <->c is unpleasant.})
24... Bf8 25. Rc2 e6 26. Rdc1 Rbb8 27. Rc7 Nf6 28. Ba7 Rb4 29. Bf2 (29. e4 $5 {
stops Nd5 and further limit Black.} Ne8 30. Rc8 Rxa7 31. Rxe8 $18) 29... Nd5
30. Rc8 Rbb8 (30... Rxc8 $6 31. Rxc8 Kg7 32. e4 $18) 31. Rxb8 Rxb8 32. Kf1 (32.
e4 Nb4 33. a3 Nd3 $14 {/+/- gives Black more <=>, than in the game.}) 32... f5
33. Rc4 Bh6 (33... Rb4 34. Nb2 $1 {/\Nd3+-} (34. Rxb4 Nxb4 35. Nc3 Bg7 $14))
34. Nc3 Ne3+ 35. Bxe3 Bxe3 36. Rc6 Bc5 37. Na4 Ba3 (37... Bb4 38. Rb6 Rxb6 39.
Nxb6 d5 40. e4 $5 fxe4 41. fxe4 dxe4 42. Nc4 $18) 38. Nb6 Kf7 39. Rc7+ (39. Nc4
Ra8 $1 $16) 39... Kg8 40. Nd7 Rb5 (40... Ra8 41. e4 Ra5 42. Ke2 $18 {leaves Bla
ck hopelessly pinned on the 8-th rank, a B move allows a4. White will simply
march his K over to the <<.}) 41. h4 Kf7 {Now White finds a pretty forced win.}
42. Ra7 $1 {Discovered checks only help Black.} Bc1 (42... Ke7 43. Nc5+ Kf6 44.
Nxe6 $1 Kxe6 45. Rxa3 $18) (42... Bb2 43. Nb6+ Kf6 44. Nc4 Be5 (44... Bd4 45.
Nxd6 $18) 45. f4 Bd4 46. Nxd6 Bxa7 $8 47. Nxb5 $18) 43. a4 $1 {Traps Black's R.
} Rb4 (43... Be3 44. axb5 Bxa7 45. b6 $18) (43... Rxb3 $2 44. Nc5+ $18) 44.
Ne5+ Kf6 45. Nd3 Rxb3 (45... Be3 46. Nxb4 Bxa7 47. Nc6 Be3 48. a5 $18 {o^a,b})
46. Nxc1 Rb1 47. Rc7 Ra1 48. Rc4 d5 49. Rc6 Ke7 (49... Rxa4 50. Nd3 $18) 50. f4
Kd7 51. Rc2 {/\Kf2,Nd3-e5} 1-0

