1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8.
Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 gxf6 10. Nd5 Bg7 11. c3 f5 12. exf5 Bxf5 13. Nc2 O-O 14. Nce3
Be6 15. Bd3 f5 16. O-O (16. Qh5 e4 17. Bc2 Ne7 18. Rd1 Kh8 (18... b4 {
is nowadays considered the simplest way to equality.}) 19. O-O Rc8 {is a differ
ent line, which transposes to the game (it's the same position as in the game
after move 19).}) 16... Kh8 {A move with very good result for Black, which was
played for the first time by Sulava, but became popular after the game J.
Polgar-Illescas, 1999.} (16... Ra7 {
has been the main move lately and nowadays is analyzed often until forced draw.
}) 17. Qh5 (17. Bc2 Ra7 18. Qh5 Raf7 19. Rad1 Ne7 20. f4 Nxd5 21. Nxd5 e4 22.
Kh1 a5 23. a3 Qa8 24. Ne3 Qc6 $15 {
1/2-1/2 Timoscenko,G-Sulava,N/Oberwart 1995 (32)}) 17... e4 (17... Bf7 18. Qh3
e4 19. Bc2 Ne5 20. Rfd1 (20. f3 $2 exf3 21. gxf3 Bxd5 22. Nxd5 Qg5+ 23. Kh1 Qd2
$15 {0-1 Polgar,J-Illescas Cordoba,M/Dos Hermanas 1999 (61)}) 20... Bxd5 21.
Rxd5 Qf6 22. Rad1 Rad8 23. f4 $14 {
1/2-1/2 Topalov,V-Leko,P/Monte Carlo 2003 (39)}) 18. Bc2 Ne7 19. Rad1 Rc8 20.
f3 Bf7 (20... Nxd5 21. Nxd5 Bxd5 22. Rxd5 Qb6+ (22... Be5 23. f4 $1 (23. fxe4
$2 f4 24. Bb3 Rc7 $44)) 23. Kh1 Qe3 24. f4 Rc5 25. Rxd6 b4 $44 {
1/2-1/2 Schmaltz,R-Chuchelov,V/France 2003 (41)}) 21. Qh3 Nxd5 22. Nxd5 b4 (
22... Be5 $5 23. fxe4 f4 24. Nxf4 Qg5 25. Nd5 Bh5 $44) 23. fxe4 (23. Nxb4 a5
24. Nd5 Bxd5 25. Rxd5 Qb6+ 26. Kh1 Qxb2 $15) (23. Qxf5 {
is critical. For instance:} bxc3 24. bxc3 Bg8 (24... Bg6 25. Qh3 Bxc3 26. Bxe4
Bxe4 27. fxe4 Rxf1+ 28. Rxf1 $16) 25. Qxe4 {and there is no clear compensation.
}) 23... bxc3 24. bxc3 Bxd5 25. exd5 (25. Rxd5 $2 Rxc3 26. Bd3 fxe4 $19) 25...
Rxc3 26. Bd3 Bd4+ 27. Kh1 Qg5 28. Rxf5 (28. g3 Rf6 $1 (28... h6 29. Bxf5 (29.
Rxf5 Rxf5 30. Bxf5 Rc1 $11) 29... Be5 {Here White can claim a slight advantage.
}) 29. Bxf5 (29. Rxf5 $4 Rxd3 $1) 29... Rh6 $132) 28... Rxf5 29. Qxf5 Qxf5 30.
Bxf5 Be3 31. g3 Rc1 1/2-1/2

