1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 5. Ng3 Bg6 6. h4 h6 7. Nf3 Nd7 8. h5
Bh7 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 e6 11. Bf4 Ngf6 12. O-O-O Be7 13. Kb1 O-O 14. Ne4 Nxe4
15. Qxe4 Nf6 16. Qe2 Qd5 17. Ne5 (17. Be3 $143 {
cannot be recommended, the B is too passive here.} Rfd8 (17... Nxh5 $6 18. g4
$40) (17... Ng4 18. Bc1) 18. Ne5 c5 19. f3 cxd4 20. Bxd4 Qa5 21. Rhe1 Qc7 22.
g4 Bc5 23. Bxc5 Qxc5 $11 {Gershenzon-Kruppa, Dnepropetrovsk 1993}) (17. Be5 b5
18. Rd3 {avoids the exchange of Q, but unfortunately this was White's main
threat getting a slightly better _|_.} Rfd8 19. Rg1 Ng4 20. Bc7 Rdc8 21. Bf4 c5
22. Ne5 Nf6 23. dxc5 Qxc5 24. Rg3 Kf8 25. Rf3 Rd8 26. g4 Rd5 27. Nd3 Qc4 28. g5
hxg5 29. Bxg5 $13 {Firman-Ekstroem, Lausanne 2001}) 17... Qe4 18. Qxe4 (18. Qd2
$6 {is completely illogical.} Nd5 19. Bg3 Rfd8 20. Rde1 Qf5 21. Nd3 Rac8 22.
Be5 c5 23. dxc5 f6 24. g4 Qf3 25. Bd4 Qxg4 26. Be3 Qf5 $17 {
Kupreichik-Lobron, Ljubljana/Portoroz 1989}) 18... Nxe4 19. Rhe1 $1 {In general
White is happy to get a slightly better _|_ right after the opening. However
with precise play Black can neutralize the pressure, just without any winning
chances.} (19. Rhf1 Bg5 {1/2:1/2 A.Sokolov-Dautov, Bled ol 2002}) (19. Be3 Rfd8
20. c4 Rac8 (20... Kf8 21. g4 Nf6 22. f3 Nd7 23. f4 a6 24. Kc2 Nxe5 25. dxe5
$14 {Stefansson-S.Kasparov, Tanta City 2001}) 21. g4 Nf6 22. f3 $14) 19... Nf6
(19... Nxf2 $2 20. Rd2 Bh4 21. Ree2 $1 $16 {and the N is trapped.}) 20. g4 Rfd8
(20... c5 {is the other main alternative here.} 21. dxc5 Bxc5 22. Nd7 $5 {
penetrating on the 7-th rank deserves attention.} (22. Be3 {White is certainly
slightly better because of the << P majority, the pressure on the d <-> and
the strong centralized N, but if Black defends himself carefully he can
consolidate his position.} Rfc8 (22... Bxe3 23. Rxe3 Rfd8 24. Red3 Rxd3 25.
Rxd3 Kf8 26. c4 Ke7 {neutralizing White's pressure on the d <->.}) 23. c4 Kf8
24. Bxc5+ Rxc5 25. f4 Rc7 26. Rd4 Ke7 27. Red1 Re8 28. b3 {
1/2:1/2 V.Gurevich-Khlian, Azov 1995}) (22. f3 Rfd8 {- 20....Rfd8}) 22... Nxd7
23. Rxd7 Bxf2 24. Rf1 Bc5 25. Rxb7 $14) 21. f3 (21. c4 c5 $1 22. Be3 (22. dxc5
Bxc5 23. f3 {- 21.f3}) 22... Bd6 (22... cxd4 23. Rxd4 Rxd4 24. Bxd4 {
and the white B is finally on the right /^.}) 23. f3 Rac8 24. b3 a6 ({
There is no need to hurry with} 24... cxd4 $143 25. Bxd4 Bb4 26. Rf1 a6 27. Kb2
) 25. Bf2 cxd4 26. Bxd4 Bb4 27. Rg1 (27. Rf1 Rxd4 (27... b5 $5) 28. Rxd4 Bc3
29. Rfd1 {- 27.Rg1}) 27... Rxd4 $5 (27... b5) 28. Rxd4 Bc3 29. Rgd1 Bxd4 30.
Rxd4 $14 {and White has a P majority on the <<, plus the better placed pieces,
Areshchenko-Grant, Istanbul 2003 CBM 96.}) (21. Be3 {
Kasparov-Anand, Linares 2003 CBM 94}) (21. c3 {/\ Kc2} c5 22. dxc5 Bxc5 23. f3
Rxd1+ (23... Nd5 24. Bd2 Bd6 25. Nd3 Rac8 26. Re2 Kf8 27. Rh1 Rc4 28. Kc2 Rdc8
29. Re4 Nb4+ 30. Nxb4 Rxb4 31. Bf4 Rb6 32. Be3 Bc5 33. Bf4 Bd6 34. Bd2 {
White certainly wants to avoid the repetition of moves.} Rbc6 35. a4 $14 {
Kalezic-Mateuta, Bucharest Blue Autumn 2002}) (23... Rac8 24. Bc1 Bf2 25. Rf1
Bb6 26. Rxd8+ Rxd8 27. Kc2 {
It is advisable for White to exchange one pair of rooks and keep the other.}
Kf8 28. Re1 Bc7 29. Nd3 Bb6 30. a4 $14 {Guseinov-Mchedlishvili, EU-chT 2003})
24. Rxd1 Nd5 25. Nd3 Be7 26. Bc1 Rd8 27. Kc2 f6 28. Nf4 Kf7 29. a3 b5 {
blockading the light squares.} 30. Nxd5 Rxd5 31. Rxd5 {
1/2:1/2 Lutz-Dorfman, Bled ol 2002}) (21. Rd3 c5 22. Red1 cxd4 23. Rxd4 Rxd4
24. Rxd4 Rd8 25. Rxd8+ Bxd8 {
Without rooks White's advantage is only microscopical.} 26. c4 Bc7 27. f3 Nh7
28. b4 f6 {attacking soon >< f3} 29. Nd3 Bxf4 30. Nxf4 Ng5 $11 {
Thorteins-Lobron, Reykjavik op 1984}) 21... Rac8 (21... c5 22. dxc5 Bxc5 23. c4
{/\ Kc2} Bf2 (23... Kf8 24. Kc2 Ke7 25. Rd3 Rac8 26. Red1 Rxd3 27. Nxd3 Bd4 28.
Kb3 Nd7 29. Bd2 e5 $11 {and Black gets reasonable counterchances on the >>,
Andreev-Bets, Alushta Golden Autumn 2001.}) (23... Rac8 24. Rxd8+ Rxd8 25. Kc2
Kf8 26. a3 {
/\ b4 and a quick advance of pawns on the << is White's main threat.} Ke8 27.
b4 Bd6 28. Rd1 Bc7 29. Rxd8+ Bxd8 30. Be3 a6 31. Bd4 $14 {
Kovalev-Kruppa, Berliner Summer 1993}) 24. Rf1 Bd4 25. Rd3 Bxe5 26. Rxd8+ Rxd8
27. Bxe5 Nh7 28. b3 f6 29. Bf4 f5 30. Re1 fxg4 31. fxg4 Nf6 {
and again Black has ample play against the weakened pawns on the >>.} 32. Rxe6
Kf7 33. Re5 Nxg4 $11 {Lutz-Khenkin, Bundesliga 2002}) (21... Nd7 22. Nc4 Nf8
23. Na5 Rd7 24. c3 Rc8 25. Kc2 Bd8 26. Nc4 Bc7 27. Bc1 f6 28. b3 b5 29. Nb2 Kf7
30. Nd3 $14 {Ginzburg-Bykhovsky, Israel Int op 2003}) 22. c3 c5 (22... Kf8 23.
Kc2 Nd5 24. Bc1 c5 {Soon or later Black has to play this freeing move.} 25.
dxc5 Rxc5 26. f4 b5 27. a3 Kg8 28. g5 hxg5 29. fxg5 $14 {
Shirov-Kramnik, RUS-The World rapid 2002}) 23. dxc5 Bxc5 (23... Nd5 24. Bc1)
24. Rxd8+ Rxd8 25. c4 $14 {
White's hopes are based on the advance of his << P majority.} Kf8 26. Kc2 Ke8
27. Nd3 Bd4 28. b3 Rc8 29. a4 a6 30. a5 {White has to gain space on the <<.}
Nd7 (30... Nd5 31. Bd2 $14 {- 30...Nd7}) 31. Re4 Ba1 32. Bd6 Nf6 33. Re1 Bd4
34. Bb4 Nd5 35. Bd2 Nf6 36. Bc3 {
The exchange of the bishops was inevitable for a winning attempt.} Bxc3 37.
Kxc3 {Now a typical _|_ has arisen, compare to the game Areshchenko-Grant,
Istanbul 2003 CBM 96.} Ke7 {On any other attempt b4 may come soon.} (37... Nd5+
38. Kd4 Ne7 39. b4 $14) (37... Nd7 38. b4 $14) 38. b4 Nd7 39. Re2 Rf8 $6 {
Black wants to create some active counterplay on the other flank. However this
allows a quick advance on the <<.} (39... Rc7 {was the passive defence.} 40. c5
(40. f4 $143 {It is better for White to keep quiet on the >> and concentrate
to the other flank.} Nf6 41. f5 $5 (41. Rg2 Rd7 $1 42. Nc5 Rd1 $132 (42... Rc7
43. Kd4)) 41... Nxg4 42. fxe6 fxe6 43. Nc5 Kf6 44. Nxe6 Re7 45. Re4 Rxe6 46.
Rxg4 Kf7 $14) (40. Kd4 Rc6 $14) 40... Nf6 41. Ne5 Nd5+ 42. Kc4 $14) 40. b5 $1
g5 (40... Ra8 41. Kb4 $16) 41. Rb2 {/\ bxa6 and Rb7.} Kd6 (41... f5 {
was consequent, but then comes the penetration on the seventh rank.} 42. bxa6
bxa6 43. Rb7 fxg4 44. fxg4 Kd6 45. Ra7 $16) 42. bxa6 bxa6 43. Rb7 $1 Ra8 {
The R has to defend the a P passively.} 44. Nb4 $1 {
Now the black K cannot come for a defence to the <<.} (44. Kd4 {allows} Kc6 (
44... e5+ $2 {founders on} 45. Nxe5 $1 Nxe5 46. c5+ $18) 45. Rb1 f6 46. c5 Rd8
$14) 44... f5 $2 {Black still organizes his counterblow on the other flank,
but in the P race White comes first.} (44... Ne5 {
defending against the push c5-c6 was more stubborn.} 45. Rb6+ (45. Nd3 Nd7)
45... Ke7 46. Rxa6 Rxa6 47. Nxa6 Nc6 48. Nb4 Nxa5 49. c5 Kd7 $14) 45. gxf5 exf5
46. Kd4 g4 47. fxg4 fxg4 48. c5+ $1 {
and there is no defence against the winning march of the o^.} Ke6 49. c6 $18
Nf6 50. c7 Rc8 51. Nxa6 (51. Rb6+ Kf5 52. Nxa6 g3 53. Ke3 $18 {
was an easy win as well.}) 51... g3 (51... Nxh5 52. Rb6+ Kd7 53. Rxh6 Nf4 54.
Ke5 $18) 52. Rb3 (52. Rb6+ $1 {was again more precise.} Ke7 (52... Kf5 53. Ke3)
53. Ke3 $18) 52... Nxh5 53. Kc5 $1 (53. Rb6+ Kf5 54. Ke3 g2 55. Rb5+ Kf6 (55...
Kg4 56. Kf2) 56. Rb1 Ke5 {was not so effective.}) 53... g2 (53... Kd7 54. Kb6
$18) 54. Rb1 Nf4 55. Kc6 {The active white K decides the battle.} h5 56. Kb7
Rg8 57. Nc5+ Kd5 (57... Kd6 58. Ne4+ Ke5 59. Nf2 Kd4 60. a6 Ke3 61. Ng4+ $1 $18
) 58. Nd7 Ke6 59. c8=Q 1-0

