Na3 b5 9. Bxf6 gxf6 10. Nd5 Bg7 11. Bd3 Ne7 12. Nxe7 Qxe7 13. c4 f5 14. O-O O-O
15. Qf3 d5 16. cxd5 fxe4 17. Bxe4 Rb8 18. Rfd1 (18. Rad1 Rb6 19. Qd3 Qd7 20. g3
f5 21. Bg2 Rh6 22. f4 exf4 23. gxf4 Bxb2 24. Nc2 Bg7 $11 {
1/2-1/2 Leko,P-Radjabov,T/Linares 2004 (27)}) 18... Qh4 ({
Later in the same tournament Radjabov played differently:} 18... Qd7 19. d6 Rb6
20. Qd3 Rd8 21. Rac1 Bf8 22. Qg3+ Bg7 $13 {
0-1 Vallejo Pons,F-Radjabov,T/Linares 2004 (62)}) 19. g3 Qg5 20. Qb3 Bg4 21.
Bf3 f5 22. Bxg4 Qxg4 23. d6+ Kh8 24. Qd5 {The queen is very strong in the
center. Black's only hope to create any real counterplay is connected with the
poor position of the knight on a3.} f4 (24... e4 25. Rd2 Rbd8 26. Rc1 Qh3 27.
Rc7 $16 f4 28. Qg5) 25. Nc2 Qg6 $6 26. Nb4 $16 Qg4 27. Nc6 (27. Qe4 $1 {
This seems most precise, not allowing ...f3 yet.} Qh3 28. Qg2 $16) (27. Nxa6 f3
28. Nxb8 Qh3 29. Qxf3 Rxf3 30. d7 Bf6 31. d8=Q+ Bxd8 32. Rxd8+ Kg7 33. Rd7+ Rf7
$11) 27... f3 28. Nxe5 Qh5 29. Nxf3 $2 (29. Re1 Rbd8 30. d7 Bxe5 {
Black has chances to escape in the rook endgame, but White is clearly better.})
29... Qxf3 30. Qxf3 Rxf3 31. d7 Rd8 32. Rd2 (32. Rac1 Bxb2 33. Rc8 Rff8 34. Rc6
$11) 32... Kg8 33. Kg2 Rf5 34. Rc1 Kf7 35. f4 b4 (35... Rf6 36. Kf3 Ke7 37.
Rcd1 Rc6 38. Re2+ Re6 39. Red2 {and Black cannot improve.}) 36. Rc4 Rb5 37. Kf3
b3 38. Ra4 bxa2 39. Rxa6 Rxb2 1/2-1/2

