1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3
O-O 9. h3 Na5 10. Bc2 c5 11. d4 Qc7 12. d5 $5 {This natural advance is rather
unusual. The reason for this is probably the highly acclaimed notion that
White should keep the pressure against e5 in the Closed Ruy Lopez - waiting to
see if dxe5, d5 or just waiting yet another move is the best continuation. The
strategy of keeping all options in the centre has the disadvantage that it
gives Black quite a few choices as well, like taking on d4.} Nc4 {The most popu
lar move at this point. Black avoids the a5-b7-d8-f7 route for his N.} 13. b3
Nb6 14. a4 Bd7 15. a5 Nc8 16. c4 {Remarkably a novelty. Garry the great has
played b4 at this point. I guess one reason for prefering b4 over c4 is to
protect a5, thereby freeing Ra1 for action on the K-side. c4 on the other hand
gives added support to d5 - which can be useful later on if Black tries to
free himself with f7-f5 at some point.} (16. b4 c4 17. Nbd2 Bd8 (17... g6 18.
Nf1 Nh5 19. Bh6 Re8 (19... Ng7 20. Ng3 Bd8 21. Qd2 Kh8 22. Rad1 f6 23. Nh2 Ne7
{1/2-1/2 Reutsky,S-Farakhov,R/Fakel Jamala, Noyabrsk RUS 2003 (23)}) 20. Qd2
Bf8 21. Ng3 $5 Nxg3 22. fxg3 Ne7 23. Rf1 $14 {
1/2-1/2 Kasparov,G-Ivanchuk,V/Prague 2002/CBM 89/[Wedberg] (45)}) 18. Nf1 Ne8
19. g4 Ne7 20. Ng3 Kh8 21. Kh2 Ng8 22. Rg1 g6 23. Be3 Ng7 24. Nd2 Bf6 25. Qf3 {
1/2-1/2 Fressinet,L-Sokolov,I/Selfoss 2003/CBM 98 no vc (25)}) 16... g6 {
Open b-file with bxc4 or closed Q-side with b4? Black decides to wait with
that decision.} 17. Nc3 Nh5 18. Ne2 Re8 (18... f5 {Logical from a structural
point of view, but Black's pieces are badly placed to support this type of
aggression. Still as a bid for more space it could be the best option in a
cramped situation.} 19. Bh6 Ng7 20. exf5 gxf5 21. Ng5 $36) 19. Ra2 Bf8 20. g4
$1 {White gains even more space and prepares to go for the black K.} Ng7 21.
Ng3 f6 22. Nh2 $1 {This is a nice idea. White sees that f4 might be a good
option since both Black's N:s are light years away from e5.} Re7 23. h4 Rf7 24.
f4 {Threatening to overwhelm Black with f5, g5 and h5.} exf4 25. Bxf4 Qd8 26.
Rf1 Qe7 27. h5 Ne8 28. Bd3 $1 {White finds simple moves to increase the
pressure, while Black struggles to find any squares at all for his pieces.} Bg7
29. Kg2 Qf8 30. Qc1 bxc4 {Black hopes to create some counterplay on the Q-side,
but again he has no pieces to attack with.} 31. bxc4 Rb8 32. Raf2 Rb3 33. Rf3
Ne7 34. Bd2 Bc8 35. Qc2 Rb8 {End of counterplay.} 36. Kh1 gxh5 {This looks
ly ugly. But waiting  to see how White was going to open the black position
wasn't very nice either.} (36... Bh6 37. Bc3 Rb7 38. e5 $1 $16) 37. Nxh5 Ng6 {
One more move (Ne5) and Black would have something resembling a position.} 38.
e5 $3 {This line opening move cuts through Black's plans.} dxe5 (38... Nxe5 39.
Bxh7+ Kh8 40. Rh3 $18) 39. Bxg6 hxg6 40. Qxg6 e4 41. Rh3 Rfb7 (41... f5 42.
Nxg7 Rxg7 43. Qh5 Nf6 44. Qh8+ Kf7 45. Qxf8+ Kxf8 46. Bh6 $18) 42. Nf4 Rb1 43.
Qh7+ Kf7 44. Qh5+ Kg8 45. Ng6 (45. Ng6 Qd6 46. Bf4 $18) 1-0

