1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 Nf6 3. d3 c6 4. Nf3 Be7 5. O-O d6 6. a4 O-O 7. Re1 Nbd7 (7...
Qc7 8. Nbd2 Nbd7 9. Nf1 (9. Ba2 d5 10. exd5 cxd5 11. c4 $13) 9... d5 $1 {
This is Black's main idea here.} 10. exd5 (10. Bb3 $2 dxe4 11. dxe4 Nc5 {
and the B cannot be saved.}) ({Also on} 10. Ba2 dxe4 11. dxe4 Nc5 {
comes into consideration.}) 10... cxd5 11. Ba2 e4 $1 {
Now Black grabs the |^ in the [+].} 12. dxe4 dxe4 13. Ng5 (13. Nd4 Nc5 14. Ng3
(14. Nb5 Qe5) 14... Rd8 {with a nasty pin on the d <->.} ({and certainly not} 
14... Nxa4 $6 {in view of} 15. Bxf7+)) 13... Nc5 14. Be3 ({
White has to play carefully. In case of} 14. Ng3 $2 Bg4 {Black has a good game.
}) 14... h6 $1 {This is a nice temporary P sacrifice in order to activate the
pieces and get the ^^.} 15. Bxc5 Bxc5 16. Nxe4 Nxe4 17. Rxe4 Bf5 {
In an opened position the ^^ is very dangerous.} 18. Re1 (18. Re2 $4 {loses to}
Bg4) 18... Qb6 $1 $44 {Kudrin-I.Sokolov, Las Vegas 1999 CBM 72} (18... Qf4 19.
Ne3) (18... Rad8 19. Qe2)) 8. Nc3 (8. Nbd2 Qc7 {- 7...Qc7}) 8... Nc5 (8... a5
9. d4 Qc7 {leads to the Philidor with an extra tempo for Black.} 10. Ba2 $13)
9. d4 (9. a5 {avoiding ...a7-a5} d5 (9... Ne6) 10. exd5 cxd5 11. Ba2 {
and Black has problems with holding his P [+].} d4 12. Nb1 $14) 9... exd4 10.
Nxd4 {Now we reach a Philidor type of position with an extra tempo for Black.}
a5 {Black wants to secure his c5 N's position and gain some control over the
dark squares.} (10... Re8 11. Qf3 $14 (11. Bf4 Bf8 12. e5 {
White's pieces are not active enough for this opening of the position.} (12. f3
d5 $1 13. exd5 Rxe1+ 14. Qxe1 cxd5 15. Bf1 Ne6 16. Be3 Bc5 17. Nce2 Qb6 $132)
12... dxe5 13. Rxe5 Bg4 14. f3 Bh5 15. Rxe8 Nxe8 16. a5 Bg6 17. Be3 Nc7 18. Qe2
a6 19. Qf2 Qe7 20. Nce2 Re8 21. Bd2 N5e6 22. Nxe6 Nxe6 23. c3 Qc5 24. Qxc5
Bxc5+ 25. Kf1 Rd8 26. Be1 h6 27. b4 Be7 28. Bf2 Bf6 $11 {
Heinemann-Enders, Germany 2000 CBM 74 ext})) 11. Bf4 Ng4 12. Be2 (12. Nf5 $5 {
deserves attention.} Ne5 (12... Bxf5 13. exf5 Ne5 (13... Nf6 $2 {
The "natural" retreat loses to} 14. Rxe7 $1 $18) 14. Bxe5 dxe5 15. Rxe5 (15.
Qxd8 Raxd8 16. Rxe5 Rfe8 17. Rae1 Kf8) 15... Bd6 16. Re3 Bf4 (16... Bxh2+ $2
17. Kxh2 Qh4+ 18. Rh3 Qxc4 19. Qh5 $16) 17. Rf3 $14 {
with an extra P and the ^- helps also for White.}) 13. Nxe7+ (13. Bf1 Bxf5 14.
exf5 Bf6) 13... Qxe7 14. Bf1 $14 {White has the ^^ and >< d6 may become weak.})
12... Nf6 13. Bf3 (13. Bc4 Ng4 $11 {is only a repetition of moves.}) 13... Re8
14. Qd2 g6 (14... Ng4 $5 15. Bxg4 (15. Rad1 Bh4 16. Rf1 Ne5 17. Be2 Ng6 18. Nf3
Bf6 $132) 15... Bxg4 16. f3 {If Black cannot play the freeing move d6-d5, the
position remains a bit better due to the >< d6.} (16. h3 Bd7 17. Rad1 Qb6 18.
b3 Qb4 $132) 16... Bd7 17. Rad1 {+/=/=}) 15. h3 {
This allows the following regrouping of pieces.} (15. Rad1 $142 Ng4 16. Qe2 $14
) 15... Nfd7 16. Rad1 Bf8 (16... Qc7 17. g4 $5 {
/\ Bg2, Bg3, f4 but needs a lot of time.} Ne5 (17... Bf8 18. b3 $14) 18. Bg2
Nc4 19. Qc1 Ne6 20. Nxe6 Bxe6 21. b3 Ne5 22. Be3 $14) 17. g4 $5 Qb6 {
Now White has the natural retreat to g2, because >< c4 can be defended in time.
} (17... Ne5 $142 18. Be2 {White has to keep an eye on >< c4.} (18. Bg2 Bg7 $13
19. b3 $140 Ned3 $1 $15) 18... Bg7 19. Be3 Ned7 20. f3 Qh4 $132) 18. Bg2 (18.
b3 Ne5 19. Bg2 {- 18.Bg2}) 18... Ne5 19. b3 Qb4 20. Nde2 $14 {
White has consolidated his position and the weakness of d6 begins to tell.} (
20. Be3 Bg7 21. Nde2 $14) 20... f6 {
This is another small concession closing the /^ for the fianchettoed B.} (20...
f5 $6 {founders on the energetic} 21. Bxe5 Rxe5 22. gxf5 gxf5 23. Qg5+ Bg7 24.
Qd8+ Kf7 25. Qxd6 $16) 21. Be3 h5 $2 {Black wants to fish in troubled waters.}
(21... Nf7 22. f4 $14 {and White has the ideal set-up of his pieces.}) 22. f4
Nxg4 (22... hxg4 23. fxe5 gxh3 24. Bf3 dxe5 25. Kh2 $16 {
was not correct either.}) 23. hxg4 Bxg4 24. Qc1 $16 {Black has no adequate
compensation, but from practical point of view the idea may work well...} f5
25. Rd4 Qb6 26. Qd2 Qc7 27. Bf2 Re6 28. Rc4 (28. e5 dxe5 29. fxe5 Kh7) 28...
Rae8 29. Nd4 Rxe4 30. Nxe4 Nxe4 31. Bxe4 fxe4 32. Rc3 d5 {Black has already
sacrificed a R for three pawns in order to keep the position complicated.} 33.
Rg3 Bd6 34. Be3 Qd7 35. c3 Rf8 36. Rf1 b6 37. Rf2 c5 38. Nb5 Bb8 39. Rfg2 (39.
Kf1 $1 g5 40. Rg1 $18 {would have won easily.}) 39... g5 $1 {
Now (probably in time trouble) Black gets real counterchances.} 40. Rf2 (40.
Rxg4 hxg4 41. fxg5 Rf3 $44) 40... Kg7 41. Qc1 (41. Rgg2 Rf5 42. fxg5 Rxf2 43.
Qxf2 Bf3 44. Qh4 Bxg2 45. Kxg2 Kg6 $44) 41... Kg6 42. Qf1 Rf5 43. Rgg2 Qf7 44.
fxg5 Bf3 45. Rh2 Bxh2+ 46. Rxh2 {#} Rf4 $1 {Black is not greedy at all in this
game, he has sacrificed a piece a rook and an exchange...} 47. Bxf4 Qxf4 48.
Rg2 $2 {This is the final mistake.} (48. Qe1 {
was still enough for a draw, for example:} Qxg5+ 49. Kf1 (49. Kf2 Qf4) 49...
Qf4 50. Qh4 Qc1+ 51. Qe1 Qf4 $11) 48... h4 $1 $19 {Now White is a R up, but he
is completely helpless against the advance of the pawns.} 49. Qe1 e3 (49...
Bxg2 50. Kxg2 Kxg5 $19) 50. Rh2 Qxg5+ 51. Kf1 h3 $1 52. Qb1+ (52. Nd6 Bg2+ 53.
Ke2 Qg4+ 54. Kxe3 Qe6+ 55. Kf2 Qxd6 $19) 52... Be4 53. Qb2 Bd3+ 0-1

